n is a carefree man who is obsessed with beauty. He once sees Nishaal and falls madly in love with her beauty and tries to approach her. A misunderstanding leads him to believe that the name of the girl he loves is Rabail. He thinks that Nishaal is Rabail. He meets Nishaal on numerous occasions, first Nishaal ignores him but then grows a liking for him too. Zain discovers that the girl he loves is the daughter of his father's friend Asad Niazi, and sends a proposal for Rabail. Rabail, under pressure from Nishal, tricks Umair into going college to study and promises that she'd wait for him and would not marry anyone else. Umair is satisfied and he happily leaves. But the original plan of Rabail, Nafeesa and Nishaal is to get Rabail married.\n\nNishaal finally finds out that the proposal that has come for Rabail is of Zain. Both Zain and Nishaal are heartbroken because they had fallen in love, even though they had not spent much time together. Nishaal tells Zain about her newly developed feelings for him because she had come  to see him as her \"ideal\" man, but Zain refuses because for the first time in his life, he had made his father proud and happy and Zain does not want to spoil this new, sweet relationship with his father, so he sacifices his love and gets married to Rabail. Umair gets to know about the betrayal and he reaches the Nikkaah ceremony, but Rabail is already married to Zain. Umair has a nervous breakdown.\n\nZain tries to make Nishaal jealous by pretending to get close to his fianc\u00e9e Rabail, but Nishaal backfires by flirting with Zain's best friend Zia. Rabail and Zain are finally married, but Zain leaves Rabail alone on the wedding night because he cannot have a relationship with her. Zain and Nishaal leave their egoes and rekindle their relationship. However, their relationship is discovered by Zain's father Ibrar, who has a heart attack and dies after making Zain promise that he would never divorce Rabail. Zain agrees to fulfil his father's last wish despite being in love with Nishaal. Zain and Rabail agree to continue their relationship for the sake of Zain's dead father, but Nishal can't tolerate seeing them together. She instigates Zain against Rabail by telling him about Umair's feelings for Rabail and make her look like a culprit who was responsible for developing those feelings and left after she got bored of Umair.\n\nAfter patching up with Zain, Nishaal starts to ignore Zia totally and he keeps on trying to contact her by calling and messaging her. Zia knows that Zain's sister Sobia has a crush on Zia so Zia uses this to take revenge from Zain by getting engaged to Sobia and disappearing on the wedding day. Because of Rabail, Zia finally realizes his mistake and Rabail gets Zia and Sobia married. Zain and Nishaal get a nikkahfied and Zain leaves his house to settle with Nishaal in a new one. Rabail finds out she is pregnant. She receives tremdous support from Zain's mother Gulshan in every aspect of her life. Gulshan tries her best to bring Rabail and Zain together. Nishal tries to persuade Zain to divorce Rabail but for some reason Zain avoids this. Rabail gives birth to Zain's daughter Ujala. A year later, Zain realizes that he doesn't truly love Nishaal, he was just attracted to her beauty. In fact, she is a horrible girl who knows nothing about love, family values and respects. He realizes that he has never been truly happy with Nishaal as she is shallow. He realizes that beauty isn't everything someone needs in life. On the other hand, he looks towards Rabail's moral and cultural values and regrets for not valuing her deep sense of existence. He goes back to Rabail, apologises for everything he has done. But it is just not easy to forgive so easily when the wounds are deep. The innocent Rabail turns into a cold-hearted lady. Meanwhile, Gulshan dies due to the trauma of the separation from her son. Zain is full of guilt and regret. Zain, is guilty about what he did and asks Rabail to forgive him. Meanwhile, Nishaal is furious on Zain who starts having feelings for Rabail. She gets to know that she is expecting. She waits for a whole day for Zain to come home, but unfortunately he doesn't. She goes to his house and gets a slap from Zain. In fury, she leaves her report there and leaves. Zain who reads it now goes after her. Nishaal tries to commit suicide but is saved by Rabail's friend. Nishaal blames Rabail for being responsible for the death of her child. But Rabail's friend tells her that Rabail didn't even touch her and instead she did her treatment. Rabail gets really hurt and leaves.\n \nUmair comes to her house later that day and brings flowers for her as it is her birthday. Zain, comes the very moment but knowing the truth he doesn't say anything. He rather asks Umair to request Rabail to forgive him for his mistakes. Umair ensures him that he will talk to Rabail.\n\nZain comes to Umair's house to take her back home but she refuses. Later Rabail accepts Umair. They are shown enjoying rain which indicates happily ever after for the two. The show ends with Zain regretting with no loved one left in life.\n\n==Cast== \n{| class=\"wikitable\n! Actor !! Character !! Notes\n|-\n|[[Ayeza Khan]]\n| Dr. Rabail\n|a [[Gynecologist]], Zain's first wife\n|-\n| [[Imran Abbas Naqvi|Imran Abbas]]|| Zain|| Rabail and Nishaal's husband\n|-\n| [[Areeba Habib]]|| Nishaal Niazi\n|Zain's second wife, Rabail's cousin\n|-\n| [[Muneeb Butt]] || Umair Niazi\n|Nishaal's brother, Rabail's cousin\n|-\n| [[Asma Abbas]] || Gulshan Abrar\n|Zain and Sobia's mother\n|-\n| Yasmin Huq || Sobia\n|Zain's sister\n|-\n| [[Sabiha Sumar]] || Nafisa Niazi\n|Asad's wife, Nishal and Umair's mother\n|-\n| Hashim Butt || Asad Niazi\n|Nafisa's husband, Nishal and Umair's father\n|-\n| Tanvir Jamal || Abrar|| Zain and Sobia's father \n|-\n| Rana Majid || Zia|| Zain's friend and Sobia's husband \n|-\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Koi Chand Rakh - OST\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2018|07|18}}\n| recorded   = 2018\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Television soundtrack]]\n| length     = (5:11)\n| language   = [[Urdu]]\n| label      = [[ARY Digital]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{Youtube|bTfiCRPxVlI|\"Koi Chand Rakh\" OST}}|type=song}}\n}}\nThe title song was sung by [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]]. The music was composed by Shani Arshad and the lyrics were written by Sabir Zafar.\nIt has more than 25 million views on [[YouTube]].\n\n==Production==\nThe series was earlier titled '''''Yeh Galat Fehmi Mere Naam Ke ''''' considering the title song of the series, but the makers changed it to ''Koi Chand Rakh''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/pakistani-cinema/imran-abbas-and-ayeza-khan-partner-up-again-1.2206219|title=Imran Abbas and Ayeza Khan partner up again|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==International Broadcasts==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Network\n! Local title \n! Series premiere\n! Episodes\n|-\n| {{flag|Somaliland}}\n| [[Horn Cable Television]]\n| '''Iftiinkii Noloshayda''' \n| August 18, 2019\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n| [[MBC Bollywood]]\n| '''\u0623\u0636\u064a\u0626\u064a \u0644\u064a\u0644\u064a'''\n| May 2, 2019\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.arydigital.tv/videos/category/koi-chand-rakh/ ''Koi Chand Rakh''] on [[ARY Digital|ARYDigital.TV]]\n*{{imdbtitle|tt9035410}}\n\n[[Category:2018 Pakistani television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Pakistani drama television series]]\n[[Category:Urdu-language television programs]]\n[[Category:ARY Digital television series]]\n", "name_user": "182.176.228.220", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koi_Chand_Rakh"}
{"title_page": "Sardar Ahmad", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sardar Ahmad\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n| term_start = 29 May 2013\n| term_end   = 28 May 2018\n|constituency= \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1933|11|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ajmer]], India\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Mutahida Quami Movement]]\n}}\n\n'''Sardar Ahmad''' is a Pakistani politician who was a member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]] from May 2013 to May 2018.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born on 9 November 1933 in [[Ajmer]], India.<ref name=\"pas\">{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Website of Provincial Assembly of Sindh|url=http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/31/518|website=www.pas.gov.pk|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has a degree of Bachelor of Arts and a degree of Master of Arts from [[Sindh University]].<ref name=\"pas\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]] as a candidate of [[Mutahida Quami Movement]] from Constituency PS-124 KARACHI-XXXVI in [[2013 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Sindh Assembly election result|url=https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20Sindh%20Assembly.pdf|publisher=ECP|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128071918/https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20Sindh%20Assembly.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmad, Sardar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sindh MPAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Muttahida Qaumi Movement politicians]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sardar Ahmad\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n| term_start = 29 May 2013\n| term_end   = 28 May 2018\n|constituency= \n| birth_date =   {{birth date and age|1933|11|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ajmer]], India\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Mutahida Quami Movement]]\n}}\n\n'''Sardar Ahmad''' is a Pakistani politician who had been a Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]], from May 2013 to May 2018.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born on 9 November 1933 in [[Ajmer]], India.<ref name=\"pas\">{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Website of Provincial Assembly of Sindh|url=http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/31/518|website=www.pas.gov.pk|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe has a degree of Bachelor of Arts and a degree of Master of Arts from [[Sindh University]].<ref name=\"pas\" />\n\n==Political career==\n\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]] as a candidate of [[Mutahida Quami Movement]] from Constituency PS-124 KARACHI-XXXVI in [[2013 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Sindh Assembly election result|url=https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20Sindh%20Assembly.pdf|publisher=ECP|accessdate=28 January 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128071918/https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20Sindh%20Assembly.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmad, Sardar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sindh MPAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Muttahida Qaumi Movement politicians]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bkell", "label": "safe", "comment": "touch up first sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sardar_Ahmad"}
{"title_page": "Soham murders", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Jessica Chapman<br />Holly Wells\n| image           = File:HollyWellsJessicaChapmanSummer2002SohamCambridgeshire2.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Jessica Chapman (left) and Holly Wells (right), pictured in the summer of 2002\n| birth_name      = Jessica Aimee Chapman<br />{{Birth date|1991|9|1|df=y}}<br />Holly Marie Wells<br />{{Birth date|1991|10|4|df=y}}\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = [[Soham]], [[Cambridgeshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date      = Both [[Circa|c.]] {{Death date and age|2002|8|4|1991|9|1|df=y}}\n| death_place     = Soham, Cambridgeshire, England\n|death_cause      = [[Determinism|Undetermined]]. Possible [[asphyxiation]]<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref>\n| body_discovered = 17 August 2002<br />[[Lakenheath]], [[Suffolk]], England\n| resting_place      = Soham Cemetery, Cambridgeshire, England\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|52.32662|N|0.34642|W|region:UK_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| known_for = Victims of [[child murder]]\n| parents         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Soham Murders''' are the murders of two 10-year-old girls which occurred in [[Soham]], [[Cambridgeshire]], England on 4 August 2002. The victims, Holly Marie Wells and Jessica Aimee Chapman, were lured into the home of a local resident, Ian Kevin Huntley,<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> who subsequently murdered the children\u2014likely via [[asphyxiation]]\u2014before disposing of their bodies in an irrigation ditch close to [[RAF Lakenheath]], [[Suffolk]]. The girls' bodies were discovered on 17 August 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Arrested in Girls' Murder Enquiry|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2199168.stm|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nHuntley was convicted of the [[Murder in English law|murder]] of both girls on 17 December 2003 and sentenced to two terms of [[life imprisonment]], with the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] later imposing a [[Mandatory sentencing|minimum term]] of 40 years. His girlfriend, Maxine Ann Carr\u2014the girls' [[teaching assistant]]\u2014had knowingly provided Huntley with a false [[alibi]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr Gave Alibi to Save Me; Not to Deceive Police|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448355/Maxine-gave-alibi-to-save-me-not-to-deceive-police.html|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=3 December 2003}}</ref> She received a three-and-a-half year prison sentence for [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiring]] with Huntley to [[perverting the course of justice|pervert the course of justice]].<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Judge Gives Huntley Forty Years - And Little Hope|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499550/Judge-gives-Huntley-40-years-and-little-hope.html|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe efforts made to locate Wells and Chapman in the thirteen days of their disappearance have been described as one of the most intense and extensive in British criminal history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caretaker Charged with Murder of Two Girls and Sent to Rampton|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404950/Caretaker-charged-with-murder-of-two-girls-and-sent-to-Rampton.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=21 August 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\">{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/last-hours-of-holly-and-jessica-6950277.html | title = Last Hours of Holly and Jessica| work = The Evening Standard| accessdate = 4 November 2019 | date = 6 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\nAt 11:45&nbsp;a.m. on Sunday, 4 August 2002, Jessica Chapman left her home in Brook Street, Soham, to attend a barbecue at the home of her best friend, Holly Wells, in nearby Redhouse Gardens.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/> Prior to leaving her home, Chapman informed her parents of her intention to also give her friend a necklace engraved with the letter ''H'' she had purchased for her on a recent family holiday to [[Menorca]].<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/>\n\nThe two girls and a friend named Natalie Parr played computer games and listened to music for approximately half an hour<ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\">{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting For News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> before Parr returned home.<ref name=\"The Scotsman\">{{cite news|title=At Night I Sometimes Just Lay There and Cry|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/at-night-i-sometimes-just-lay-there-and-cry-1-897763|accessdate=27 October 2019|work=The Scotsman|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> By 3:15&nbsp;p.m., both girls had changed into distinctive replica [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] football shirts; one of which belonged to Wells and the other to her older brother, Oliver.<ref name=\"Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved t\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/23/childprotection.uk |title=Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved to Woodland |work=The Guardian |date=23 August 2002 |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> At 5:04&nbsp;p.m., a photograph of the two friends was taken by Wells' mother before the children ate dinner with the other house guests. They then returned to playing in Wells' bedroom at approximately 6:10&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/><ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\"/>\n\nAt approximately 6:15&nbsp;p.m., the two girls left the Wells residence without informing any of the house guests to purchase sweets from a vending machine at the local sports centre. While returning to 4 Redhouse Gardens,<ref>{{cite news|title=Holly and Jessica: Timetable|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=4 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> Wells and Chapman walked past the College Close home of Ian Huntley, the senior caretaker at the local [[secondary school]]. Huntley evidently lured the girls into his house, stating that his girlfriend, Maxine Carr\u2014the girls' teaching assistant at [[St Andrew's Primary School (Soham)|St Andrew's Primary School]]\u2014was also present in the house. (Carr was actually visiting her mother in [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]] on this date.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mistake Made by Maxine Carr that Showed She Knew Ian Huntley had Killed Soham Schoolgirls|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/maxine-carr-ian-huntley-soham-16320951|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=Chronicle Live|date=23 May 2019}}</ref>)\n\nThe precise chain of events to occur after the girls entered 5 College Close is unknown, although investigators believe sections of Huntley's later claims in initial interviews granted to the media prior to his arrest and his later trial testimony\u2014such as that he had been cleaning his dog at the time the girls passed by his house at approximately 6:30&nbsp;p.m. and that one girl had been suffering from a mild nosebleed\u2014may have actually been true.<ref name=\"https\"/> In any event, the [[cause of death]] of both girls was later ruled to be [[asphyxiation]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite news|title=As Day Breaks, Huntley's House is Turned Into Dust and Rubble |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/apr/04/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=3 April 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"Huntley guilty of Soham Murders\"/> Chapman's [[Nokia 6110|Nokia]] mobile phone was switched off at 6:46&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=Was Jealousy Over Maxine the Trigger for Murder?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449727/Was-jealousy-over-Maxine-the-trigger-for-murder.html|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nAt 8:00&nbsp;p.m., Nicola Wells entered her daughter's bedroom to invite the girls to say goodbye to her house guests, only to discover both children were missing from their home. Alarmed, she and her husband, Kevin, searched their house and nearby streets. Minutes after their daughter's 8:30&nbsp;p.m. [[curfew]] had expired, Nicola Wells phoned the Chapman residence to determine if the girls were at this location, only to learn Leslie and Sharon Chapman were becoming concerned why their youngest daughter had not returned home.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting For News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> Following subsequent frantic efforts by the families of both girls to locate their daughters, Wells and Chapman were reported [[missing person|missing]] by their parents at 9.55&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3244403.stm | work=BBC News | title=Timeline: Girls' Last Movements | date=5 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nPolice immediately launched an intensive manhunt to locate the missing children.<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> Over 400 officers were assigned full-time to search for the girls.<ref>{{cite news|title='Calculated Cover-up' by Huntley and Carr as Girls Lay Dead in Wood|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446118/Calculated-cover-up-by-Huntley-and-Carr-as-girls-lay-dead-in-wood.html|accessdate=25 October 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> These officers conducted extensive house-to-house enquiries across Soham;<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404950/Caretaker-charged-with-murder-of-two-girls-and-sent-to-Rampton.html | work=The Telegraph | first1=Sean | last1=O'Neill | first2=David | last2=Sapsted |title=Caretaker Charged With Murder of Two Girls and Sent to Rampton | date=21 August 2002}}</ref> their efforts to search local terrain were bolstered by the assistance of hundreds of local volunteers<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm | title = How Huntley's Charade Crumbled| work = BBC News | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 17 December 2003}}</ref> and, later, [[United States Air Force]] personnel stationed at nearby airbases.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holly and Jessica: Two Bodies Found in Woods|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/18/childprotection.society6|accessdate=7 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=18 August 2002}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|The total population of [[Soham]] in 2002 was 8,700<ref>{{cite news|title=The Whole Town is Weeping: A Community Dazed by Grief and Disbelief|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/19/childprotection.children1|accessdate=25 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 August 2002}}</ref>}}\n\nTo assist in their public appeals for information, [[Cambridgeshire Constabulary|Cambridgeshire Police]] released the photograph Nicola Wells had taken of the children less than two hours before their disappearance depicting both girls wearing distinctive Manchester United replica football shirts. A physical description of each girl was also released to the media, describing both girls as being white, approximately 4&nbsp;ft 6 in tall, and slim. Chapman was described as being tanned, with shoulder-length, brown hair; Wells was described as being [[Light skin|fair]], with blonde hair.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2173505.stm | title = 'Extreme Concern' for Missing Girls | work = BBC News | accessdate = 30 August 2008 | date = 5 August 2002}}</ref> The parents of both girls were adamant their daughters had been wary of talking with strangers, having warned them not to trust individuals they did not know from early childhood. This insistence was supported by the headteacher of St Andrew's Primary School, who informed reporters: \"The possible danger from strangers is something we have impressed upon [the children] from an early age.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 98</ref>\n\nSuspecting the children had been [[kidnapping|kidnapped]], investigators questioned every registered [[sex offender]] in Cambridgeshire and Lincolnshire.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 171</ref> Over 260 registered sex offenders across the UK\u2014including fifteen high-risk [[paedophile]]s\u2014were also questioned, although all were eliminated from the enquiry.<ref name=\"Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls\">{{cite news | url = https://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/missing-abduction-linked-to-soham-girls-1-104788 | title = Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls | work = Peterborough Telegraph | accessdate = 22 November 2019 | date = 13 August 2002}}</ref> Police also investigated the possibility that the girls had arranged to meet with an individual either or both had contacted via an [[Chat room|internet chat room]], although this possibility was soon discounted.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2002/aug/12/childprotection.missingpersons | title = Chatroom Contact Dismissed as False Lead | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 12 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3232051.stm|title=Soham Trial Timeline|date=3 November 2003|publisher=}}</ref> [[CCTV]] footage of the girls, recorded minutes before their disappearance, was released to the public. This footage depicted the children arriving at the local sports centre at 6:28&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/09/childprotection.children | title = Film Released of Missing Girls | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 9 August 2002}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators were able to obtain extensive footage of the children's movements following their departure from the Wells household. The last piece of footage of Wells and Chapman depicts the children walking onto a car park on the grounds of Soham Village College<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 106</ref>}} A televised reconstruction of the children's last known movements was also broadcast nationally on 10 August,<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404103/Reconstruction-of-childrens-walk-too-painful-for-parents-to-watch.html | title = Reconstruction of Children's Walk Too Painful for Parents to Watch | work = The Telegraph | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 11 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/11/childprotection.society2 | title = Walking in the Last Known Footsteps of Holly and Jessica | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 11 August 2002}}</ref> and both sets of parents granted an interview with presenter Colin Baker on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] programme ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'', which was broadcast on 12 August.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404171/Parents-in-TV-plea-for-return-of-girls.html | title = Parents in TV Plea for Return of Girls | work = The Telegaph | accessdate = 16 December 2019 | date = 12 August 2002}}</ref> Other family members and friends of both girls also appealed via the media for the safe return of the children.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 5</ref> These appeals for information regarding the whereabouts of Wells and Chapman would see more than 2,000 phone calls and tips received from the public, with all information obtained entered into the investigation's [[HOLMES 2]] database.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2177998.stm|title=Van Seized in Missing Girls Inquiry|date=7 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley was present at one of the [[press conference]]s in which the parents of Wells and Chapman pleaded for the safe return of their daughters.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 13</ref> On this occasion, he offered his condolences to the father of Wells, stating: \"Kevin, I'm so sorry. I didn't realise it was your daughter.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3263615.stm | title = Huntley 'Comforted Holly's Dad' | work = BBC News | accessdate = 31 December 2019 | date = 12 November 2003}}</ref>}} A [[candlelight vigil]] was held by the community on 7 August.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/friend-tells-of-worry-for-girls-6310331.html | title = Friends Tell of Worry for Girls | work = The Evening Standard | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 8 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the children's disappearance, [[Staffordshire Police]] contacted their counterparts to report their suspicions the girls' likely [[Child abduction|abduction]] may be linked to an abduction which had occurred in their jurisdiction the previous year, in which a six-year-old girl had survived an [[indecent assault]] by an abductor who was still at large and whose green [[Ford Mondeo]] was identified as having number-plates which had earlier been stolen in [[Peterborough]]. The individual responsible for this abduction and assault was also believed to have followed a 12-year-old girl in the same area, although in this instance, his car had been fitted with number-plates which had been stolen in [[Nottinghamshire]].<ref name=\"Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls\"/> The same vehicle had recently been sighted in [[Glatton]], Cambridgeshire. This information was later included in a televised appeal pertaining to the children's disappearance on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Crimewatch]]'', although this potential lead ultimately failed to bear fruition or relevance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Abduction-sixyearold-linked-missing-girls/story-21477497-detail/story.html|title=Abduction of Six-year-old May be Linked to Missing Girls|date=12 August 2002|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Sightings===\nSeveral members of the public reported having seen the children in the early days of the investigation. One individual, Mark Tuck, informed investigators that as he had driven past the girls upon Sand Street in Soham town centre at approximately 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on 4 August,<ref>{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting for News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> his attention had been drawn toward their Manchester United replica shirts, causing him to remark to his wife, Lucy: \"Look! There's two little [[David Beckham|Beckhams]] over there.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Countdown to Murder of 'Two Little Beckhams'|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/countdown-to-murder-of-two-little-beckhams-20031106-gdhqdv.html|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> A young woman named Karen Greenwood also reported seeing the girls walking \"arm in arm\" along College Road approximately two minutes later.<ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\"/> Another woman living in the nearby village of [[Little Thetford]] claimed to have seen two girls whose appearance and clothing matched those of Wells and Chapman walking past her home the morning after the children had been reported missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2175995.stm|title=Beckham's Plea to Missing Girls|date=6 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Police also received statements regarding a white van that had been seen in Soham on the evening of the children's disappearance. Investigators located and seized this vehicle from a caravan park in [[Wentworth, Cambridgeshire|Wentworth]] on 7 August, although this lead ultimately proved fruitless.<ref name=\"BBC News\"/>\n\nOn 12 August, police launched a media appeal to trace the driver of a four-door, dark green saloon car seen struggling with two young girls by a taxi driver who stated he had observed this individual \"thrashing his arms\" as he struggled to either placate or contain two female children inside his vehicle as he had driven upon the [[A142 road|A142]] south of Soham towards [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]] on the early evening of 12 August. The following evening, a jogger alerted police to two mounds of recently disturbed earth he had encountered at Warren Hill, just outside Newmarket.<ref>{{cite news |title=Soham Murders: Timeline|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/soham-murders-timeline-8045799.html |newspaper=The Evening Standard |date=14 August 2012}}</ref> The initial speculation by this individual had been that these mounds of earth may be the impromptu burial locations of the two missing girls. However, an overnight examination of this location revealed the two mounds of earth to simply be [[Sett|badger setts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1404211/Driver-struggled-with-two-children.html|title=Driver 'Struggled' With Two Children|date=12 August 2002|publisher=|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOne individual who claimed to have spoken with the girls immediately before their disappearance was 28-year-old Huntley, who informed investigators on 5 August he had engaged in a brief conversation with both girls on his doorstep the previous afternoon.<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\">{{cite news|title=Huntley Cries in Dock|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-cries-in-dock-7235641.html|accessdate=5 November 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=1 December 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley's precise motivation for voluntarily informing police of his encountering the children outside his home is unknown, although it is speculated he chose to do so out of concerns [[witness|eyewitnesses]] may have seen him engaging in conversation with the girls outside his home<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 113</ref>}} According to Huntley, Wells and Chapman had briefly enquired as to whether his partner, Carr, had been successful in a recent application for a full-time teaching assistant position at their school.<ref name=\"Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine C\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446601/Jessica-and-Holly-doted-on-Maxine-Carr-says-teacher.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine Carr, Says Teacher|last1=O'Neill|first1=Sean|last2=Clough|first2=Sue|date=13 November 2003|access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref> When he had replied Carr had been unsuccessful, one of the girls had said, \"Tell her we're sorry\" before both children had walked along College Street in the direction of a bridge leading towards Clay Street.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Piece Together Last Sightings of Girls|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/police-piece-together-last-sightings-of-girls-1-616210|accessdate=4 January 2020|work=The Scotsman|date=9 August 2002}}</ref> Police were suspicious of Huntley's account of the children's disappearance. His house was searched by a single police officer on 5 August. Although no [[incriminating evidence]] was discovered on this date, this officer noticed numerous items of clothing upon the washing line despite the fact it had been raining. In reference to the evident extensive cleaning of the house's interior, Huntley stated: \"Excuse the dining room. We had a flood.\"<ref name=\"O'Neill\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446118/Calculated-cover-up-by-Huntley-and-Carr-as-girls-lay-dead-in-wood.html|work=The Telegraph|title='Calculated Cover-up' by Huntley and Carr as Girls Lay Dead in Wood|last=O'Neill|first=Sean|date=7 November 2003|access-date=9 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators would later determine Wells and Chapman had most likely been attacked\u2014and possibly murdered\u2014in the dining room of College Close<ref>{{cite news|title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm|accessdate=3 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>}} This officer was unconvinced by Huntley's claims and suspicious of his agitated demeanour, and he remained a strong suspect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime6|title=Poor Intelligence, Poor Data System and Poor Media Strategy: Police Own Up to Failures|date=17 December 2003|publisher=|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nOne day later, on 6 August, Huntley drove from Soham to Grimsby to pick up Carr. Shortly before the two returned to College Close,<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley's Question to Police: 'Am I a Suspect?'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/18/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=27 December 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 November 2003}}</ref> a neighbour of Carr's mother named Marion Clift observed the couple standing at the rear of the vehicle, with the [[Trunk (car)|boot]] open. According to Clift, a \"pale, shaking\"<ref name=\"Huntley's Question to Police: Am I\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/18/soham.ukcrime|work=The Guardian|title=Huntley's Question to Police: Am I a Suspect?|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=18 November 2003|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> Huntley had simply gazed into the boot for several moments, while Carr stood alongside him, her head bowed, weeping. When Huntley became aware of Clift's presence, he had abruptly closed the boot.<ref name=\"O'Neill\"/>\n{{quote box\n| quote =  I don't know the girls. I was stood on the front doorstep [[Dog grooming|grooming]] my dog down. She'd run away and come back a bit of a mess ... they just came across and asked how [Maxine] was ... I just said she weren't very good as she hadn't got the job and they just says please tell her that we're very sorry and off they walked; in the direction of the library over there.<ref>{{cite news |title=TV No Preparation for Witness Box|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/dec/18/broadcasting.comment1 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n| source = Ian Huntley, interviewed by [[Sky News]] correspondent [[Jeremy Thompson]]. 15 August 2002<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\">{{cite news |title=Last TV Interviews of the Accused|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447185/Last-TV-interviews-of-the-accused.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 November 2003}}</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\n\n===Media interviews===\nIn the weeks following the disappearances, Huntley reluctantly<ref>{{cite news|title=Caretaker was Sure Holly and Jessica had Not Run Away|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11955143.its-got-to-be-two-people-they-trust-caretaker-was-sure-holly-and-jessica-had-not-run-away/|accessdate=23 November 2019|work=Herald Scotland|date=17 August 2002}}</ref> granted several television interviews to media outlets such as [[Sky News]] and the regional [[BBC News]] programme, ''[[BBC Look East]]'', speaking of the general shock in the local community and his apparent dismay at being the last individual to see the children alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/missing-girls-police-in-appeal-to-abductor-172646.html|title=Missing Girls: Police Appeal to Abductor|date=9 August 2002|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|By the second week of the children's disappearance, Huntley had volunteered to become a spokesman for the community of Soham. His explanation for this decision was that he wished to convey the frustration and despair the community was feeling to the media, and to vocalise his belief the criticism some members of the public had begun to direct towards the police for failing to locate the children was misguided consternation.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 177</ref>}} In one interview granted to Sky News correspondent [[Jeremy Thompson]] during the second week of the search, he claimed to be holding on to a \"glimmer of hope\"<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\"/> the children would be found safe and well, claiming that he had last seen the girls walking in the direction of a local library.<ref name=beyond/> Having actively participated in the search for the children, Huntley also made efforts to ingratiate police officers; regularly asking questions as to how their investigation was progressing and just how long [[DNA profiling|DNA evidence]] could survive before deteriorating.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> One of these officers observed three vertical scratches upon Huntley's left jaw, each measuring approximately three centimetres, which he claimed had been recently inflicted by his dog.<ref name=\"Huntley's Question to Police: Am I\"/>\n\nCarr was also interviewed by the press during the second week of the search for the children.<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\">{{cite news |title=Last TV Interviews of the Accused|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447185/Last-TV-interviews-of-the-accused.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 November 2003}}</ref> In this live interview, Carr [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] Huntley's claims to have conversed with the children on their doorstep as she had been bathing before both girls had walked away from their doorstep, adding: \"I only wish we had asked them where they were going ... if only we knew then what we know now. Then we could have stopped them, or done something about it.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 187</ref>\n\nDiscussing the individual personalities of each girl, Carr described Wells as being the \"more [[femininity|feminine]]\" of the two, adding that Chapman was \"more of a [[tomboy]]\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Arrested Couple Publicly Declared their Affection for Girls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404703/Arrested-couple-publicly-declared-their-affection-for-girls.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=18 August 2002}}</ref> and that on one occasion, she had jokingly remarked to Chapman how, unlike many of her friends, she seldom wore a skirt. To this question, Carr stated the child had expressed her desire to be a [[bridesmaid]] at her own future wedding, adding how Chapman had said she would willingly wear a dress for such an occasion.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 188</ref> Carr also displayed a thank-you card to this reporter which had recently been given to her by Wells on the last day of the school year. Referring to Wells in the [[past tense]], Carr stated, \"She was just lovely, really lovely\", before making a direct appeal to the children: \"Just get on the phone and just come home. Or if somebody's got them, just let them go.\"<ref name=beyond/>{{refn|group=n|Carr's decision to corroborate Huntley's blatant lies to investigators and media in the early stages of the police investigation briefly resulted in police discounting Huntley as a suspect before eyewitness accounts as to Carr's actual whereabouts on 4 August and a search of mobile phone and telephone records proved the [[False evidence|falsity]] of her claims.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3301589.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Prolonged Soham's Agony | date=17 December 2003 | accessdate=23 May 2010 | first=Peter | last=Gould}}</ref>}}\n\nBy the second week of the children's disappearance, Huntley had begun to lose weight and vividly displayed symptoms of [[insomnia]].<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 11</ref> To one officer, he begged the question: \"You think I've done it? I was the last person to see them!\" before beginning to weep. His erratic and distressful behaviour led to his being prescribed [[anti-depressant]]s on 13 August.<ref name=\"Evening Standard 17 December 2003\">{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title= Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html| date= 17 December 2003 |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard|Evening Standard]] |location=London| accessdate= 2 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Police suspicions==\nOn 16 August, twelve days after the children's disappearance, Huntley and Carr were first questioned by police. Both were questioned for approximately seven hours. Each provided formal [[witness statement]]s to investigators before being placed in a safe house in the village of [[Histon and Impington|Histon]].<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 215</ref> By this date, police had received information from several Grimsby residents who had recognised Huntley in the television interviews he had granted to the media; these individuals recalled that he had been accused of [[rape]] several years earlier. Other individuals recalled that, contrary to her own televised claims, Carr had in fact been socialising in Grimsby town centre on the night that the girls had disappeared, and not at home in Soham as she had indicated in the interview she had granted to the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Said Fake Alibi was Her Idea|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3244798.stm|accessdate=31 October 2019|work=BBC News|date=27 November 2003}}</ref>\n[[File:Soham Village College - geograph.org.uk - 269552.jpg|190px|right|thumb|[[Soham Village College]]. Police discovered charred remnants of the children's clothes at this location on 16 August<ref>{{cite web|title=I Cut Clothes off Bodies, Says Huntley|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447645/I-cut-clothes-off-bodies-says-Huntley.html|accessdate=30 November 2019|date=25 November 2003}}</ref>]]\nThe same evening, police conducted a thorough search of both 5 College Close and the grounds of [[Soham Village College]] where Huntley worked as a senior caretaker<ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=16 April 2011|location=London}}</ref> as the couple remained under police watch at separate locations outside Soham. Although each room of Huntley's home had evidently been recently and meticulously cleaned<ref>{{cite news|title=Not a Single Fingerprint in the House|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449715/Not-a-single-fingerprint-in-the-house.html|accessdate=1 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> with what was later described as being a \"lemony\" cleaning fluid,<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref> these searches located numerous items declared as being of \"major importance\" to the ongoing investigation. Although the [[Evidence (law)|evidence]] and artifacts were not made public at the time, the items recovered from the school grounds included items of clothing the girls had been wearing when last seen, including their charred and cut Manchester United shirts, which were recovered from a bin within a [[hangar]] at Huntley's place of work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3233558.stm|title=Huntley Admits Cutting Up Clothes|date=24 November 2003|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley had attempted to burn these clothes in the late evening of 4 August, although the [[Fire accelerant|accelerant]] he used for this purpose had caused a blaze which he believed may attract attention, causing him to quickly extinguish the fire}} Fibres recovered upon these items of clothing proved to be a precise match to samples retrieved from both Huntley's body, his clothing and from 5 College Close. Furthermore, his [[fingerprint]]s were recovered from the bin.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/>\n\nHuntley's car was also subjected to a detailed forensic examination on 16 August. The forensic examination of this vehicle revealed the car had also been recently, extensively cleaned, although traces of a distinctive mixture of brick dust, chalk and concrete of precisely the same type used to pave the road leading to where the girls' bodies would be discovered were found around the wheel arches and upon and around the [[Car controls|pedals]].<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> Furthermore, a cover from the rear seat was missing, and the lining of the boot had been recently removed and replaced with an ill-fitting section of household carpet.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators would later discover that one week before his arrest, Huntley had taken his car to an [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] garage to have the vehicle's tyres changed. Using a false identity,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 148</ref> he had paid a mechanic \u00a310 to place a false number plate on the receipt for this purchase<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref>}}\n\n==Arrest==\nHaving discovered the children's clothes at Soham Village College,<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3249887.stm | work=BBC News | title=Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths | date=7 November 2003}}</ref> police decided to arrest Huntley and Carr. Both were arrested on suspicion of abduction and murder at 4:30&nbsp;a.m. on 17 August.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2180946.stm | work=BBC News | title=Timeline of events | date=18 August 2002}}</ref> Although investigators had publicly stated they strongly believed the children had been abducted; on 7 August,<ref name=\"BBC News\"/> they publicly announced their strong suspicions both girls had been murdered.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two Held on Suspicion of Murdering Missing Girls |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/17/childprotection.children5 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=17 August 2002 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nDuring initial questioning, Huntley refused to answer questions and appeared evasive, confused, and [[Emotional detachment|emotionally detached]]; occasionally drooling throughout police attempts to question him in an effort to feign symptoms of [[Mental disorder|mental illness]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/17/newsid_3985000/3985667.stm|title=Ian Huntley Guilty of Soham Murders|website=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref> This tactic left police with no option but to initially refer Huntley to a mental hospital to undergo an extensive [[psychological evaluation]].<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Carr quickly confessed to detectives she had lied about her whereabouts and her partner's actions on 4 August as, shortly before she had returned to Soham from Grimsby three days later, Huntley had claimed to her in a phone call to have seen the two girls shortly before their disappearance, admitting: \"The thing is, Maxine, they came in our house!\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 157</ref> According to Carr, Huntley then informed her the children had entered their home in order that Wells could stanch her nosebleed. He then claimed to her Chapman had sat upon their bed as he had helped Wells control the bleeding from her nose before both girls had left their home. Referencing one of the 1998 rapes he had committed but had earlier claimed to her to have been falsely accused of in this phone call, Huntley then began voicing concerns as to again being falsely accused of involvement on this occasion, also claiming his previous arrest had caused him to suffer a [[nervous breakdown]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Said Fake Alibi was Her Idea|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3244798.stm|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=27 November 2003}}</ref> She had therefore later agreed to concoct a false story with her partner to support his version of events.<ref name=\"O'Neill\"/>\n\nAfter being informed of the discovery of the children's bodies and the ample evidence attesting to Huntley's guilt, including his fingerprints being recovered from the bin in which the children's clothes had been found, Carr burst into tears, shouting: \"No! He can't have been! It can't have been! He hasn't done it!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/28/soham.ukcrime2|work=The Guardian|title=Tearful Carr Confronted with Evidence Against Lover, Court Hears |last=Branigan|first=Tania|date=28 November 2003|access-date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Despite these revelations, Carr initially remained emotionally attached to Huntley and professed her belief in his innocence to both the police and her family.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 258-259</ref>\n\n===Discoveries===\nAt approximately 12:30&nbsp;p.m. on 17 August,<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Reveal Horrors of Bodies in Ditch|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/police-reveal-horror-of-bodies-in-ditch-1-620448|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=24 August 2002}}</ref> a 48-year-old gamekeeper named Keith Pryer discovered the bodies of both girls lying side by side in a five feet deep irrigation ditch close to a pheasant pen near the perimeter fence of [[RAF Lakenheath]] in [[Suffolk]];<ref>''Crimes That Shocked The World'' {{ISBN|1-844-54974-7}} p. 65</ref> a location more than 10 miles east of Soham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2199785.stm|title=Bodies Found in Missing Girls Inquiry|date=18 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Pryer had noticed what he later described as an \"unusual and unpleasant smell\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/jury-hears-of-gamekeepers-discovery-6984709.html | work=Evening Standard | title=Jury Hears of Gamekeeper's Discovery | date=25 November 2003}}</ref> in the vicinity several days earlier; when returning to the area with two friends on 17 August, he had decided to investigate the cause of this odour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Uc4AAAAQBAJ|title=Beyond Evil - Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley|first=Nathan|last=Yates|date=18 October 2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> Walking through an overgrown [[Road verge|verge]] approximately 600 [[yard]]s from a partially tarmacked road, Pryer and one of his companions, Adrian Lawrence, discovered the children's bodies. Immediately upon viewing the corpses, Lawrence turned in the direction of his girlfriend, Helen Sawyer, and shouted: \"Don't come any closer, Helen! Get back in the van!\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 2</ref> Lawrence immediately reported the discoveries to police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Huntley: Girls Died in Freak Accidents |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/26/soham.ukcrime |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nBoth girls had been missing for thirteen days when their bodies were found, and both corpses were in an advanced state of [[human decomposition|decomposition]].<ref name=beyond/> In an apparent effort to destroy [[Forensic science|forensic evidence]], the murderer or murderers had attempted to burn both bodies.<ref name=\"Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3246118.stm |title=Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=28 November 2003 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> In addition, no clear footprints were discovered at the crime scene.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 137</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley would later inform investigators he had taped bin liners around his feet prior to carrying the children's bodies from his vehicle to the irrigation ditch}}\n\nDespite the perpetrator(s) efforts to destroy evidence and hinder identification, investigators rapidly deduced who the two victims most likely were, and that both had not died at the location of their discovery.<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2211087.stm|title=Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'|date=23 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Numerous hairs later determined to belong to Chapman were also discovered on a tree branch close to the location of the girls' bodies.<ref>{{cite news|title='Smothered and Set Alight'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/smothered-and-set-alight-6976321.html|accessdate=18 December 2019|work=The Evening Standard|date=7 November 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At his subsequent trial, Huntley admitted that, in an effort to destroy any [[Forensic science|forensic evidence]], he had returned to the body disposal site several days after the murders to set the bodies alight<ref name=\"Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3246118.stm |title=Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=28 November 2003 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"The Crime of Her Life\">{{cite news|title=The Crime of Her Life|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/10/gender.uk|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2005}}</ref>}}\n\nThe following day, a Cambridgeshire Deputy Chief Constable named Keith Hodder released a [[Press release|press statement]] to the media confirming the discovery of the children's bodies, adding that both families had been informed of the developments and that although positive formal identification would take several days, investigators were as \"certain as [they] possibly could be\" the bodies were those of Wells and Chapman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Bodies are Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/two-bodies-are-holly-and-jessica-1-128657|accessdate=17 January 2020|work=Ipswich Star|date=19 August 2002}}</ref>\n[[File:Ely Cathedral (18).JPG|190px|right|thumb|[[Ely Cathedral]]. A service to remember and celebrate the lives of the children was held at this location on 30 August 2002<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\">{{cite web|title=Last Farewell: Holly Buried in Private Service with Flowers from The Beckhams; Jessica is Laid to Rest 24 Hours Earlier as The Two Families Grieve Alone|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/LAST+FAREWELL%3B+Holly+buried+in+private+service+with+flowers+from+the...-a091024546|accessdate=30 October 2019|date=4 September 2002}}</ref>]]\n\n==Identification==\nOn 21 August, the bodies of both girls were conclusively identified via [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]].<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Police Identify Holly and Jessica's Bodies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/21/childprotection.uk?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 August 2002 |location=London}}</ref> Nine days later, a public memorial service was held at [[Ely Cathedral]] to remember and celebrate the lives of both girls.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/soham-murders-ian-huntley/ |title=Soham Murders: Why Did Ian Huntley Kill Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman? |work=The Telegraph |date=4 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> This service was attended by approximately 2,000 people, including the girls' classmates, teachers and the six [[family liaison officer]]s who had provided 24-hour service for both families.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\"/> The Reverend Tim Alban Jones officiated at this service, informing all present: \"Would not the best and most lasting memorial to these two lovely young girls be a change for the better in how we behave towards each other? Today's service is a small milestone in our shared journey of grief and sorrow ... it is our hope that we may perhaps draw a line under one phase of our grieving and begin to look forward.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 237-238</ref>\n\nAn online [[Condolence book|book of condolence]] attracted more than 31,000 messages of grief and sympathy<ref name=\"Judd\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-640559.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Terri | last=Judd | title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Huntley is Charged on Two Counts of Murder | date=21 August 2002}}</ref> and on 24 August, football clubs across Britain held a [[Moment of silence|minute's silence]] prior to commencing scheduled football matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/inquest-into-deaths-of-murdered-cambridgeshire-girls-opens-today-1.1092894 |title=Inquest Into Deaths of Murdered Cambridgeshire Girls Opens Today |work=The Irish Times |date=23 August 2002 |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Inquest===\nThe formal [[Coroner#inquest|inquest]] into the children's deaths was held at [[Shire Hall, Cambridge|Shire Hall]], [[Cambridge]], on 23 August 2002.<ref name=\"Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved t\"/> At this hearing, [[coroner]] David Morris testified the bodies of both girls were partially [[skeletonization|skeletonized]], and that no precise cause of death could be determined for either decedent, although Morris stated that the most likely cause of death of both girls had been asphyxiation.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> Furthermore, Morris stated the girls had almost certainly not died at the location where their bodies had been discovered,<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2211087.stm|title=Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'|date=23 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> and that both bodies had been placed at this location within 24 hours of their deaths.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>{{refn|group=n|Huntley would later inform investigators that he had waited for nightfall before opting to drive to RAF Lakenheath to dispose of the girls' bodies. He further elaborated that a deciding factor to dispose of the bodies in this particular location had been that RAF Lakenheath was just two miles from the home of his disabled grandmother, and that if eyewitnesses spotted his vehicle, he could falsely claim his purpose for being in this vicinity had been his decision to visit his grandmother<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 131</ref>}} These conclusions were physically supported by an analysis of the [[shoot]]s of [[Urticaceae|nettles]] located at the [[crime scene]] which enabled forensic [[Ecology|ecologist]] and [[Forensic palynology|palynologist]] [[Patricia Wiltshire]] to approximate that the actual time the bodies had been placed at this location had been almost two weeks prior.<ref name=\"The Crime of Her Life\">{{cite news|title=The Crime of Her Life|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/10/gender.uk|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Formal charges==\nBy 20 August, investigators had established sufficient [[Real evidence|physical evidence]] from Huntley's home, vehicle and Soham Village College to formally charge him with two counts of murder.<ref name=\"Judd\"/> He was formally charged with these offences while detained for observation at [[Rampton Secure Hospital]], and all [[preliminary hearing]]s against him were postponed until the conclusions of his [[mental health]] assessment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-174152.html|work=The Independent|title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Ian Huntley is Charged On Two Counts of Murder|last=Judd|first=Terri|date=21 August 2002|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> Carr was also charged with attempting to [[pervert the course of justice]] on this date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-174152.html|work=The Independent|title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Ian Huntley is Charged On Two Counts of Murder|last=Judd|first=Terri|date=21 August 2002|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At this hearing, Carr was informed by Principal Crown Prosecutor Marion Bastin this charge carried a maximum sentence of life imprisonment. Upon hearing this fact, Carr slumped forward.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/outrage-as-carr-appears-in-court-1-618413|work=The Scotsman|title=Outrage as Carr Appears In Court|date=22 August 2002|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>}} She was further charged with two counts of assisting an offender on 17 January 2003.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nWhile held on [[remand (detention)|remand]] at [[Holloway Prison]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/soham-accused-carr-to-testify-via-prison-video-link-1.1093546|work=The Irish Times|title=Soham Accused Carr to Testify Via Prison Video Link |date=29 August 2002|access-date=14 December 2019}}</ref> Carr regularly enquired as to Huntley's welfare,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 15</ref> and is known to have penned several letters in which she professed her continued love for him.<ref name=\"The Evening Standard\">{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr to Wed as She Finds Man Ready to Forget Her Past|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/maxine-carr-to-wed-as-she-finds-a-man-ready-to-forget-her-past-6630174.html|accessdate=5 December 2019|work=The Evening Standard|date=30 January 2008}}</ref> Carr would only sever all contact with Huntley in December 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Holly, Jessica and the Unravelling of a Dark and Terrible Mystery |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/07/ukcrime.soham |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 December 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Mental health assessment===\nTo determine Huntley's state of mental health, he was detained under Section 48 of the [[Mental Health Act 1983|Mental Health Act]] for almost two months at Rampton Secure Hospital. Here, his mental state was extensively assessed by Dr Christopher Clark, a consultant [[Forensic psychiatry|forensic psychiatrist]], to determine whether he suffered from any form of mental illness and whether he was [[Competence (law)|mentally competent]] to stand trial. Clark concluded in October that, although [[psychopathy|psychopathic]],<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 14</ref> Huntley did not suffer from any major mental or [[Psychosis|psychotic illness]].<ref name=\"Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html|title=Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill' |publisher=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003 |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/find_out/guides/uk/holly_and_jessica/newsid_3327000/3327903.stm |title=Holly and Jessica: Timeline of Events |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=19 December 2003 |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref> Resultingly, on 8 October, Huntley was deemed mentally competent to stand trial.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n{{quote box\n| quote = Although Mr Huntley made clear attempts to appear [[insane]], I have no doubt that the man currently, and at the time of the murders, was both physically and mentally sound and therefore, if he is found guilty, carried out the murders totally aware of his actions.\n| source = Dr. Christopher Clark. Consultant [[Forensic psychiatry|forensic psychiatrist]] reciting the conclusions of his assessment of Ian Huntley's mental state (2002)<ref name=\"Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html|title=Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill' |publisher=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003 |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\nHaving been declared mentally fit to stand trial, Huntley was faced with a sentence of [[Life imprisonment in England and Wales|life imprisonment]] if a jury could be convinced of his guilt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://89.207.56.140/news/2002/1008/soham.html |title=Huntley Declared Fit for Trial |publisher=RT\u00c9 News |date=8 October 2002 |accessdate=18 June 2011}}</ref> He was subsequently transferred to a [[Prison#Control_units|segregation unit]] at [[Woodhill (HM Prison)|Woodhill prison]] in [[Milton Keynes]], [[Buckinghamshire]]. On 9 June 2003, he attempted [[suicide]] by consuming 29 antidepressants which he had accumulated in his cell. Although staff initially feared Huntley might die as a result of this [[Drug overdose|overdose]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-184129/Soham-suspect-comfortable.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Soham Suspect 'Comfortable' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> he was returned to his prison cell within 48 hours. Huntley was later transferred to London's [[HM Prison Belmarsh|Belmarsh prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/ian-huntley-back-in-prison-after-taking-drug-overdose-1.116419 |title=Ian Huntley Back in Prison After Taking Drug Overdose |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date=11 June 2003 |accessdate=18 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Funerals==\nThe funeral services for Wells and Chapman were conducted on consecutive days in September 2002. Services for both children were held at St Andrew's parish church and both were officiated by the Reverend Tim Alban Jones. Both girls were laid to rest in private ceremonies attended by only family and close friends. At the request of both families that their privacy be respected, the media refrained from reporting upon either service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11952316.holly-and-jessica-laid-to-rest-in-private/|title=Holly and Jessica Laid to Rest in Private|access-date=October 23, 2019|newspaper=Herald Scotland|date=4 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1417463/MBE-for-vicar-who-united-Soham.html|title=MBE for Vicar Who United Soham|access-date=October 23, 2019|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 December 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Pretrial hearing==\nAt a preliminary hearing held at the [[Old Bailey]] on 16 June 2003, Huntley pleaded not guilty to the formal charges of murdering Wells and Chapman, although he chose to plead guilty to the charge both stood accused of: conspiracy to pervert the course of justice. Carr pleaded not guilty to the charges of attempting to pervert the course of justice and assisting an offender.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 264</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Huntley for the murders of Wells and Chapman opened at the Old Bailey on 5 November 2003 before Justice [[Alan Moses]]; Huntley was charged with two counts of murder, to which he entered a formal plea of not guilty. Carr was charged with two counts of assisting an offender and one count of perverting the course of justice.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nIn his [[opening statement]] on behalf of [[the Crown]], prosecutor Richard Latham [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] described the last day of the friends' lives and how, by \"pure chance\", they had happened to pass by Huntley's home at a time when Carr was not present. Latham contended Huntley had deliberately lured the girls into his home at approximately 6:37&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Jury Visits Huntley's House|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257725.stm|accessdate=21 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=10 November 2003}}</ref> and that both girls had been murdered shortly thereafter, with cell site analysis proving Huntley had switched off Chapman's mobile phone either outside his home or within the grounds of Soham Village College after both girls had been murdered.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jessica's Mobile 'is Vital Clue to Murder'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446018/Jessicas-mobile-is-vital-clue-to-murder.html|accessdate=11 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> Latham further emphasised that mobile phone records and eyewitness accounts proved Carr had been in Grimsby on the evening in question,<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Trial: 'Crucial' Phone Evidence|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3246111.stm|accessdate=26 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> thus proving the statements she had given to police and press alike had been false. Latham then outlined the details of how Keith Pryer and his two friends had discovered the children's bodies on 17 August<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/a-clever-spot-to-hide-bodies-1-2532117 | work=The Yorkshire Post | title=A Clever Spot to Hide Bodies | date=7 November 2003}}</ref> at a location Huntley had known to be restricted via his plane spotting hobby and thus where they were unlikely to be discovered.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/soham-trial-hears-further-witness-evidence-1.510629 | work=The Irish Times | title=Soham Trial Hears Further Witness Evidence | date=13 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nReferencing the likely [[Motive (law)|motive]] for the girls' murder and the actual cause of death of each decedent, Latham stated that due to the extensive state of decomposition of the bodies, the coroner had been unable to determine the precise cause of death of either child, or whether the girls had been [[sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] before or after death. However, Latham stated neither body showed signs of compressive neck injuries, knife wounds, drugging or poisoning, and that both girls had most likely died of asphyxiation.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nIn a direct reference to Huntley's claims both girls' deaths had been [[Accidental death|accidental]], Latham stated that \"only one person knows what happened\" after the friends entered his home.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/> However, he further stressed the cause of death was undoubtedly murder, adding: \"Ten-year-old girls don't just drop dead.\"<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> In reference to Carr's attempts to pervert the course of justice, Latham stated that \"as surely as night follows day\" the two had conspired to concoct a false [[alibi]] to divert suspicion from Huntley,<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> although he warned the jury Carr could only be convicted of assisting an offender if they believed she had known Huntley had murdered the girls, adding her actual motive for providing lies to police with reference to the charge of perverting the course of justice was irrelevant.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nOver the course of three days, Latham outlined the efforts of both defendants to divert suspicion away from Huntley, and Huntley's own efforts to destroy all physical and [[circumstantial evidence]] linking him to the crime,<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> although despite these efforts, investigators had retrieved enough evidence to prove the children had been murdered within his home and\u2014within approximately twelve hours of their deaths\u2014transported in his vehicle to the location where their bodies would be discovered on 17 August. This had included ample fibre evidence retrieved from Huntley's vehicle, clothes and carpets which had been a \"precise match\" to the Manchester United shirts the girls had been wearing at the time of their disappearance.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3251009.stm | work=BBC News | title=Soham Prosecution: The Forensic Case| date=7 November 2003}}</ref> Latham then closed his opening statement by again bringing the jury's attention to Huntley's claim both deaths had been accidental, remarking, \"We pose this question: Two of them?\" He then speculated Huntley's defence counsel may try and argue that he had been confused, commenting: \"In that case, they would have to consider [Huntley's] behaviour over the fortnight between the girls' disappearance and their bodies being found.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 268-269</ref>\n\nTestimony pertaining to the forensic evidence linking Huntley was heard on 24 November. On this date, a forensic scientist named Helen Davey testified as to the [[Real evidence|biological evidence]] recovered from the girls' clothing, footwear and a dishcloth discovered within the hangar at Soham Village College on 16 August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Trial Hears Forensic Evidence|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/24/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=20 December 2019|work=The Guardian|date=24 November 2003}}</ref> Davey testified she had found minute traces of blood and [[saliva]] upon these garments, although she had found no positive traces of [[semen]] upon the clothing. She further explained the reason for the lack of any definitive traces of semen being discovered could have been a result of the charred and melted condition of the articles she had inspected. A scenes of crime officer also testified on this date that, despite Huntley's exhaustive efforts to remove any physical evidence of his crime from his home, a forensic examination had revealed several traces of [[blood spatter]]ing about the hallway and main entrance to the master bedroom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley: 'I Hid Clothes'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-i-hid-clothes-7224896.html|accessdate=19 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=24 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Defendants' testimony===\nOn 1 December, Huntley testified before the court in his own [[defense (law)|defence]]. Responding to questioning by his own defence counsel, Stephen Coward QC,<ref>{{cite news|title=SPlease Don't Think I Could Kill, Said Huntley in Call to Mother|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448043/Please-dont-think-I-could-kill-said-Huntley-in-call-to-mother.html|accessdate=15 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=29 November 2003}}</ref> Huntley admitted both girls had died in his house but denied that either death had been intentional. According to Huntley, he, Wells and Chapman had entered his bathroom to stem a mild nosebleed Wells had been suffering when the girls had walked by his home. The bath was already filled with water as he had been cleaning his dog that afternoon. In the bathroom, he had slipped and accidentally knocked Wells into his bath while helping her [[wikt:stanch|stanch]] her nosebleed, and this unintentional act had caused her to drown as he himself had simply \"panicked and froze\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley 'Just Panicked and Froze'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3252382.stm|accessdate=28 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=1 December 2003}}</ref> He further claimed Chapman had witnessed this accident and began repeatedly screaming, \"You pushed her!\"<ref>{{cite news|title='You Pushed Her,' Jessica Screamed, then Huntley Moved to Silence Her|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447732/You-pushed-her-Jessica-screamed-then-Huntley-moved-to-silence-her.html|accessdate=26 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=26 November 2003}}</ref> and that he had then accidentally [[Asphyxia|suffocated]] her while attempting to stifle her screaming, which had preoccupied his attention as opposed to ensuring Wells did not drown. By the time his state of panic had waned, it had been too late to save the lives of either of the children<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\"/> and that his first coherent memory had been of himself sitting on his vomit-stained landing close to Chapman's body.<ref name=\"Evening Standard 17 December 2003\">{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title= Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html| date= 17 December 2003 |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard|Evening Standard]] |location=London| accessdate= 2 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nWhen questioned as to his failure to call emergency services and subsequent, extensive efforts to both destroy evidence and divert suspicion from himself, Huntley insisted he had first become preoccupied with whether the police and public alike would believe the girls' deaths had actually been accidental, and he had therefore decided to conceal all evidence of the deaths as opposed to either notifying police or paramedics.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> Weeping, Huntley admitted responsibility for both deaths, but repeated his insistence both deaths had been accidental. He further tearfully claimed he had not attempted to feign insanity upon his arrest; insisting the trauma of the children's deaths had temporarily erased his memory and his being in the presence of police had caused his mind to temporarily seize.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\"/>\n\nOn 3 December, Carr took the stand to testify in her own defence. Responding to questioning from her own defence counsel, Michael Hubbard QC, Carr briefly discussed her initial acquaintance with Huntley, their subsequent relationship and plans to start a family once they both obtained financial stability before Hubbard directed his questioning toward her return to Soham on 6 August and her discovering Huntley had recently washed their bedding and had evidently cleaned sections of the house. To these questions, Carr explained that her first impression had been that Huntley had \"had a woman in the house\", adding their bedding had been washed shortly before 4 August. Carr further testified to having noted a crack in the [[enamel paint|enamel]] of the bathtub which had not been there when she had travelled to Grimsby four days previously.<ref>{{cite news|title='I Thought He'd Had a Woman in the House|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448464/I-thought-hed-had-a-woman-in-the-house.html|accessdate=15 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=4 December 2003}}</ref> When questioned as to why she had then assisted Huntley in extensively cleaning their home in the days following the children's murder, Carr claimed she had done so as she had always been \"obsessive about tidiness.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceG\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 278</ref>\n\nQuestioned as to the efforts she had subsequently made to mislead both police and the media to divert suspicion from her partner, Carr emphasised she had only lied to police, the media and \"anyone who asks\" to protect Huntley, who had repeatedly assured her of his innocence of any wrongdoing and his fear or being \"fitted up\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A 'Charmer' Drawn to Schoolgirls|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3301527.stm|accessdate=22 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> by police for the girls' disappearance should they discover the 1998 rape allegation made against him.<ref>{{cite news|title='If, For a Minute, I Knew or Believed He Had Murdered Those Girls I Would be Horrified'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/if-for-a-minute-i-knew-or-believed-he-had-murdered-those-girls-i-would-be-horrified-81071.html|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=4 December 2003}}</ref> She further claimed to have referred to Wells and Chapman using past tense merely because had worked with the children in the past.<ref name=\"ReferenceG\"/>\n\nCarr further claimed she had initially attempted to persuade Huntley to contact police and \"be open\" as to his claims to have invited the children into his home in order that Wells could stanch her nosebleed, but that he had refused to do so, as inviting children into their home had been a violation of the rules imposed by St Andrew's Primary School. She further explained her focus had therefore been to protect Huntley's job and reputation, adding that had she known of Huntley's actual guilt, she would never have attempted to provide him with a false alibi, stating to her counsel: \"If, for a minute, I [had known] or believed he'd murdered either of those girls I would have been horrified.\"<ref name=\"biography.com\"/>\n\nConcluding his questioning, Hubbard cautioned the jury not to succumb to the temptation of judging Carr's [[morality]], but to consider her state of mind prior to her arrest when considering whether the lies she had told warranted any criminal liability, stating she had \"done no wrong\" on the date of the children's murder, and had not returned to Soham until 6 August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr Takes the Stand to Tell the Court Why She Stood by Huntley|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/maxine-carr-takes-the-stand-to-tell-the-court-why-she-stood-by-huntley-1.397193|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Irish Times|date=4 December 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Closing arguments==\nOn 10 December, counsels for both prosecution and defence delivered their [[closing argument]]s to the jury. Latham delivered his closing argument on behalf of the prosecution by describing both Huntley and Carr as \"accomplished liars\"<ref name=\"ReferenceG\"/> before outlining the prosecution's case both children had to die to satisfy Huntley's \"selfish self-interest\" before Huntley\u2014with Carr's support\u2014had embarked on twelve days of \"cynical deception\", with Carr only revealing the truth about her lies to police after being informed of the discovery of the children's bodies.<ref name=\"Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'\">{{cite news|title=Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3306221.stm|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nReferencing Huntley's likely motive for the murders and his claims at trial that both deaths had been accidental, Latham stated: \"We invite you to reject the accounts of both deaths [being accidental] as desperate lies; the only way out for him. We suggest that this whole business in the house was motivated by something sexual. But, whatever he initiated, plainly went wrong. Therefore, in this ruthless man's mind, both girls had to die in his own selfish self-interest.\" Referencing Carr's conscious efforts to deceive the police and media alike, Latham simply stated: \"She had the prospect of marriage, a baby, a nice home and a new start. She preferred to do what she could to make the best of the position she was in. That involved at all costs protecting Ian Huntley.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 277-279</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the prosecution's closing argument, Coward delivered his argument on behalf of the defence. He conceded his client was indeed guilty of physical responsibility for the girls' actual deaths\u2014as Huntley had admitted\u2014and therefore deserved punishment, although he argued the prosecution had failed to provide definitive [[Evidence (law)|proof]] Huntley had actually intended to actually murder the children or cause them actual [[bodily harm]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Him Guilty of Manslaughter, QC Tells Jury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/11/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Guardian]|date=11 December 2003}}</ref> Furthermore, Coward contended the prosecution had failed to provide conclusive evidence to support their claim that Huntley's actual motive for the murders had been sexual. Coward concluded his closing argument by requesting the jury deliver a verdict of [[manslaughter]] in relation to both deaths.<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Him Guilty of Manslaughter, QC Tells Jury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/11/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Guardian]|date=11 December 2003}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote =  Your tears have never been for them; only for yourself. In your attempts to escape responsibility, in your lies and [[Psychological manipulation|manipulation]] ... you have increased the suffering of two families. There is no greater task for the criminal justice system than to protect the vulnerable. There are few worse crimes than your murder of these two young girls.\n| source = Section of Judge [[Alan Moses]]'s, formal [[Sentence (law)|sentencing]] of Ian Huntley. 17 December 2003<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 280</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\nFollowing the conclusion of both counsels' closing argument, Judge Moses announced the jury would begin their deliberations on 12 December.<ref name=\"Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'\"/>\n\n===Convictions===\nThe jury deliberated for four days before reaching their verdicts against both defendants.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 279</ref> On 17 December 2003, they returned a majority verdict of guilty on two counts of murder against Huntley. He was subsequently [[Sentence (law)|sentenced]] to life imprisonment, with a minimum term of imprisonment to be imposed by the [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]] at a later date.<ref name=\"Huntley guilty of Soham Murders\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3312551.stm | work=BBC News | title=Huntley guilty of Soham Murders | date=17 December 2003|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> Huntley's face displayed no emotion as the verdict was announced, although the mothers of both Wells and Chapman burst into tears.<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 280</ref><ref name=\"The Legacy of Holly and Jessica\">{{cite news|title=The Legacy of Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-legacy-of-holly-and-jessica-1.400875|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=The Irish Times|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Carr willingly pleaded guilty to the charge of perverting the course of justice, she pleaded not guilty to the charge of assisting an offender. The jury accepted Carr's insistence that she had only lied to the police and media in order to protect Huntley because, prior to their arrest, she had actually believed his claims of innocence.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> As such, she was found not guilty of assisting an offender. Carr was sentenced to serve three-and-a-half years in prison for perverting the course of justice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr: What Happened to Ian Huntley's Girlfriend After the Soham Murders?|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/uk/maxine-carr-ian-huntley-girlfriend-where-now-what-happened-soham-murders-holly-wells-jessica-chapman-501362|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMinutes after the convictions, the parents of both girls granted an interview to the media. Discussing Huntley's mindset, Leslie Chapman opined: \"I think he was a time bomb waiting to go off and both our girls were in the wrong place at the wrong time. I hope the next time I see him, it will be like we saw our daughters\u2014and it will be in a coffin.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 281</ref>\n\n==Motive==\nHuntley's actual motive for killing the children is unknown, although minutes prior to encountering Wells and Chapman, he is known to have engaged in a heated argument with Carr, culminating in his slamming the telephone down.<ref name=beyond>{{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nathan|title=Beyond Evil|date=2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|location=London|isbn=1844541428}}</ref> Huntley had allegedly suspected Carr of conducting affairs throughout their relationship, leading both his mother and some police officers to suspect Huntley had killed the two girls in a fit of [[jealousy|jealous]] [[Rage (emotion)|rage]].<ref name=beyond/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-204291/Huntley-flipped-killed.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Huntley 'Flipped and Killed' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> However, prior to his trial, a [[Offender profiling|criminal profile]] had resulted in his being ruled by an eminent [[Criminal psychology|criminal psychologist]] as a \"latent, predatory paedophile\"<ref name=\"He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Wa\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/17/soham.ukcrime4 | work=The Guardian | title=He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Way Through Life | date=17 December 2003}}</ref> who had chosen to lure Wells and Chapman into his home upon a moment of [[opportunism]].<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news|title=His Lies and Shallow Charm Fooled Dozens of People but They Hid a Violent, Bitter Man |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=2 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe prosecution had contended at Huntley's trial a likely [[sexual desire|sexual motive]] existed for the murders. Testimony from Carr had indicated her suspicions sexual activity had occurred in their home in her absence as, although Huntley had insisted throughout the entirety of their relationship that Carr perform all domestic chores, she had observed that he had washed the quilts, pillow cases and sheets of their bed in her absence.<ref name=\"https\"/> However, [[Forensic pathology|pathological evidence]] retrieved from the bodies indicating at least one of the girls had been subjected to a sexual assault either before or after her murder was not disclosed to the jury at Huntley's trial. The reason for this decision had been that both bodies were too extensively decomposed and damaged by fire to enable a conclusive determination of either the actual cause of death or if either girl had been subjected to a sexual assault.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAlthough prosecutors at Huntley's trial contended he had intentionally lured the children into his house with a likely sexual motivation, investigators found no evidence of [[Malice aforethought|premeditation]] in relation to the murders.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-203297/Huntley-asked-sexual-motive.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Paul | last=Harris | title=Huntley Asked About 'Sexual Motive' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> However, at the September 2005 hearing in which the minimum term Huntley should serve before any form of parole eligibility was decided, Justice Alan Moses stated: \"There is a likelihood of [a] sexual motivation, but there was no evidence of sexual activity, and it remains no more than a likelihood.\"<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph\"/>\n\n===Psychology===\nPrior to murdering Wells and Chapman, Huntley had established an extensive record of consensual and unconsensual sexual activity with females\u2014many of whom had been beneath the legal [[age of consent]]. He would typically use guile and/or force to achieve his desires. Between 1992 and 2002, he had committed numerous acts of [[physical violence#Types|physical]] and [[sexual violence]] against women and children for which he had been legally unpunished.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley: A History of Violence|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huntley-a-history-of-violence-8967h3q6f6j|accessdate=27 November 2019|work=The Times|date=27 November 2006}}</ref> The youngest girl Huntley is known to have raped had been 12 years old, with another girl he had attempted to rape being 11 years old.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p.34</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators believe that prior to his 2002 arrest, Huntley had engaged in illegal sexual activity with up to 60 underage girls<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 35</ref>}}\n\nFollowing his arrest, several former girlfriends and sexual partners stated that, although Huntley presented himself as a charming and considerate individual in the early stages of a relationship, he would become domineering and [[domestic violence|violent]] upon having established a sense of control.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 37</ref> Having established control over his partner, Huntley severely restricted and supervised any contact she held with her family or social acquaintances. He would also [[Emotional blackmail|emotionally blackmail]] his partner if he detected any signs of her developing resistance to his control or indicating a desire to leave him.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 45</ref>\n\nAccording to one columnist, the fact that Huntley had remained unpunished for these often blatant and continuous acts had embellished Huntley's confidence and reinforced his domineering, [[misogynist]]ic mindset in addition to fuelling his [[recidivism]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/maxine-carr-is-one-more-huntley-victim-why-do-we-demonise-her-rn2jjbqk6fd | work=The Times | first=Joan | last=Smith | title=Maxine Carr is One More Huntley Victim: Why Do We Demonise Her? | date=11 May 2004}}</ref> Psychologists have also determined Huntley has [[Mental block|mentally blocked]] any attempts to accept either the reality or enormity of his actions pertaining to his repeated violence against females in order that he may cope with the consequences of his actions.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\"/>\n\n==Sentencing==\nThe minimum term of imprisonment Huntley should serve before being considered eligible for [[parole]] was decided on 29 September 2005. On this date, High Court judge Mr Justice Moses announced that Huntley must remain in prison until he had served a minimum of 40 years' imprisonment; a term which would not allow parole eligibility until 2042, by which time Huntley would be 68 years old.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Murders: Why Did Ian Huntley Kill Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/soham-murders-ian-huntley/|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=4 August 2017}}</ref> In setting this minimum term of imprisonment, Mr Justice Moses stated: \"The order I make offers little or no hope of the defendant's eventual release.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= [2005] EWHC 2083 (QB) Paragraph 16|url=http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/144_7208.htm|publisher= Her Majesty's Courts Service|date=29 September 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226093346/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/144_7208.htm|archivedate=26 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nHuntley avoided eligibility for a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment, as the passing of the [[Criminal Justice Act 2003]] had been just one day after his conviction; thus taking effect on 18 December 2003 and applying solely to murders committed on or after this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Ian Huntley\n| image_name     = Ian Kevin Huntley portrait.jpg\n| image_size     = 100px\n| image_caption  = Ian Huntley\n| birth_name = Ian Kevin Huntley\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|1|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]\n| alias          = Ian Nixon\n| conviction     = [[Murder]] (x2)\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] (40-year minimum term)\n| conviction_status = Convicted\n| occupation  = School [[Janitor|caretaker]]\n| education = [[Healing Comprehensive School]]\n| spouse =\n}}\n\n==Ian Huntley==\nIan Kevin Huntley was born in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, on 31 January 1974, the first of two sons born to Kevin Huntley and his wife, Lynda ([[n\u00e9e]] Nixon).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449738/Trail-of-underage-sex-and-violence-that-led-to-murders.html|title=Trail of Underage Sex and Violence that Led to Murders|date=18 December 2003|work=Telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The Huntley family were working class and at the time of the birth of their first child, lodged with Lynda's parents in Grimsby. Following the birth of their second child, Wayne, in August 1975, the family moved into a rented property in [[Immingham]], where Huntley attended school.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 19</ref>\n\nHuntley was a timid child, and something of a [[mother's boy]]. In his early years, he frequently threw tantrums in order to obtain his mother's attention, although childhood friends would later remark how markedly afraid he was of his stern father.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 22</ref>\n\nAt both primary and secondary school, Huntley was an average scholar. He was regarded as a loner, an oddball and an attention seeker by his peers, and became a frequent target for bullies.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 20</ref> The bullying Huntley endured escalated when he entered [[Healing School|Healing Comprehensive School]] at age 11, resulting in his academic performance waning. As a result, Huntley's parents enroled their son in Immingham Comprehensive at age 13. He was again the target of physical and verbal bullying at this school, although he did form a few friendships via a shared interest in computer games.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley also enjoyed football, and was an avid supporter of Manchester United.<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\nAt the urging of his father, Huntley joined the [[Air Training Corps]] at age 13. His activities with this youth organisation fuelled an interest Huntley had held since childhood for aeroplanes, and he seriously considered a future career with the [[Royal Air Force]]. Huntley also developed a hobby of [[Aircraft spotting|plane spotting]]. Via this hobby, he became familiar with the environs of RAF Lakenheath.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 24</ref>\n\nDespite having few friends, Huntley did form several relationships with girls while attending Immingham Comprehensive. Each of these girls was at least one year younger than himself, although none of these relationships lasted longer than a few weeks.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 25</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Huntley finished his schooling, obtaining five [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] passes. He chose not to enrol in college or university and instead committed himself to finding employment. Between 1990 and 1996, Huntley worked in a succession of menial jobs, although he seldom held any job for an extensive period of time.<ref name=\"Ian Huntley Biography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> He also viewed himself as something of a [[wikt:lady's man|ladies' man]], and was scrupulous with regards to his personal appearance and personal hygiene.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 10</ref>\n\n===Marriage===\nIn June 1994, Huntley began dating 18-year-old Claire Evans, with whom he first became acquainted through his employment at a local [[Heinz]] factory. After approximately two months of courtship,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley proposed to Evans. The couple married at Grimsby Registry Office on 28 January 1995,<ref>{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=28 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> although the marriage lasted scarcely one week due to Huntley's volatile temper. On one occasion, he is known to have beaten his wife so extensively she suffered a [[miscarriage]].<ref name=\"The Scotsman\"/> Shortly after their separation, Huntley's wife formed a relationship with and later married Huntley's younger brother, Wayne.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=27 October 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Previous criminal offences===\nIn March 1996, Huntley was charged with [[burglary]]. In this offence, he and an accomplice [[Allegation|allegedly]] broke into the house of a neighbour in Grimsby and stole numerous electrical goods, jewellery and cash. Although this case reached court, the prosecution offered no evidence, resulting in a judge ordering the offence to [[lie on file]].<ref name=\"Previous Allegations Against Huntley\">{{cite news|title=Previous Allegations Against Huntley|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3313501.stm|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nBetween August 1995 and May 1996, Huntley established numerous sexual relationships with teenage girls, all of whom were under the legal age of consent. Three of these girls were aged 15, and one 13. One of these girls would become pregnant,<ref name=\"Ian Huntley Biography\"/> and gave birth to a baby girl in 1998.<ref name=\"https\"/> Although reported to police on three occasions, Huntley was not charged for any of these offences as each of the girls denied having engaged in sex with Huntley. Each refused to file criminal complaints and/or rebuffed offers of help from social services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-detective Says 'Unspectacular' Huntley Did Not Stand Out|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/mar/02/childrensservices.soham|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=2 March 2004}}</ref> Despite not being charged with any of these offences, rumours of Huntley's sexual interest in underage girls soon became community gossip, and he was regularly insulted by neighbours and work colleagues. As a result, Huntley began rebuffing any offers to socialise with work colleagues for fear of being attacked while alone in their company.<ref name=\"Former Neighbour Describes Huntley\">{{cite news|title=Former Neighbour Describes Huntley Paedophile Slurs and Former Girlfriend Reveals His Violent Behaviour|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/12_december/17/realstory_soham.shtml|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1998, Huntley was arrested on suspicion of raping an 18-year-old woman. He admitted engaging in sex with the claimant, but claimed the act had been [[consensual sex|consensual]]. He was not formally charged with this offence. Just one month later, Huntley was charged and remanded in custody at [[HM Prison Wolds]] for one week after another 18-year-old Grimsby woman claimed to have also been beaten and raped by Huntley while walking home from a local nightclub.<ref name=\"Previous Allegations Against Huntley\"/> This complainant further stated Huntley had threatened to kill her before assaulting her. Huntley admitted engaging in sex with this woman, although he insisted the act had been consensual.<ref name=\"He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Wa\"/> The criminal charge was dropped a week later after the [[Crown Prosecution Service]], having examined CCTV footage from the nightclub and environs and finding evidence of the two socialising within the nightclub, determined [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]] existed to secure a conviction for this offence.<ref name=\"https\"/> As a result of this criminal complaint, further rumours regarding Huntley's [[sexual violence]] also became community gossip,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 49</ref> resulting in Huntley being fired from his job and forcing him to move into his mother's home. Furthermore, he was forbidden from initiating contact with his baby daughter or her mother.<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\"/>\n\nIn July 1998, police were notified Huntley had also sexually assaulted an 11-year-old girl in September 1997; having also threatened to kill the child if she informed her mother. He was never charged with this offence, although he subsequently confessed to this attack in April 2007.<ref name=\"The Scotsman\"/>\n\nThe final criminal allegation against Huntley prior to his committing the Soham murders dates from July 1999. In this instance, a woman was raped and Huntley\u2013by this stage suspected by police as being a serial sex offender\u2013was interviewed. Huntley supplied a DNA sample to assist in their enquiries, with Carr also providing an alibi to support his claims of innocence. The victim of this assault subsequently stated her belief that Huntley had not been the perpetrator of her assault. (This would prove to be the sole instance in which a suspected or proven victim of Huntley had not identified or named him as being her assailant.)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3313501.stm | work=BBC News | title=Previous Allegations Against Huntley | date=17 December 2003|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley had never been convicted of any of these criminal allegations, although his burglary charge had remained on file. Howard Gilbert, then-headteacher of Soham Village College\u2014having admitted the college's failure to check Huntley's references prior to offering him employment\u2014later said that he would not have employed Huntley if he had been aware of the burglary charge, as one of Huntley's key responsibilities was to ensure security in the school grounds\u2014a role unfit for a suspected burglar.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/mar/13/childrensservices.soham | work=The Guardian | title=School Admits Huntley References Not Checked | date=13 March 2004|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nBy 2001, Huntley's proven and alleged criminal activities had been reported to [[Humberside Police]] on ten separate occasions and to the social services on five occasions.<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\n===Acquaintance with Maxine Carr===\nIn February 1999, Huntley became acquainted with 22-year-old Maxine Carr, whom he first encountered in a Grimsby nightclub. On this occasion, Carr had been drinking with a former boyfriend named Paul Selby when Huntley\u2014a casual acquaintance of Selby\u2014approached the two and immediately initiated a conversation.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 70</ref> According to Carr, she was \"instantly attracted\" to Huntley's self-certain and pleasant persona, and agreed to begin dating him that same evening.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Within four weeks of their acquaintance,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/like-the-gullible-young-girls-before-her-carr-fell-for-huntley-s-evil-spell-1-498396 | work=The Scotsman | title=Like the Gullible Young Girls Before Her, Carr Fell for Huntley's Evil Spell | date=18 December 2003 | accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> she had moved into Huntley's [[Barton-upon-Humber]] flat, and the couple informed relatives of their eagerness to start a family.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/maxine-carr-the-teenage-anorexic-who-loved-working-with-children-and-nights-on-the-town-577012.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Maxine Carr: The Teenage Anorexic Who Loved Working With Children and Nights on the Town | first=Terri | last=Judd | date=18 December 2003 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, the couple moved to a ground-floor flat in [[Scunthorpe]], where Huntley formally proposed to Carr in June 1999.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 78</ref>\n\nAlthough publicly a besotted couple, Huntley was notably possessive of Carr, and is known to have both [[emotional abuse|emotionally abused]] and/or [[Assault|physically assaulted]] her on numerous occasions, often culminating in Carr returning to live with her mother before Huntley persuaded her to return to live with him.<ref name=\"Former Neighbour Describes Huntley\"/> Furthermore, both Huntley and Carr are known to have conducted affairs throughout the course of their relationship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Cheated on Fiancee with Teenager|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/carr-cheated-on-fiance-with-teenager-7237002.html|accessdate=10 December 2019|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> Noting how Carr often became [[Flirting|flirtatious]] whenever she had consumed alcohol, Huntley actively sought to minimise any opportunity for her to drink or otherwise socialise outside his presence for fear of her cheating on him with other males.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAt the time of their acquaintance, Huntley temporarily worked for an insurance company in [[Market Rasen]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.marketrasenmail.co.uk/news/rasen-area-link-to-soham-murders-1-1178676 | work=Market Rasen Mail | title=Rasen Area Link to Soham Murders | date=21 August 2002 | accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> He soon found alternate employment at a finance company in [[Binbrook, Lincolnshire|Binbrook]] while Carr maintained her employment packing fish at a local fish processing factory. The couple would relocate to [[East Anglia]] in early 2001. Shortly thereafter, Huntley secured employment as a bartender.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=13 March 2017|location=London}}</ref>\n\nBy 2001, Huntley had re-established contact with his father,{{refn|group=n|Huntley's parents had separated in 1993. Following their separation, Huntley had distanced himself from his father for several years}} who worked as a school caretaker in the village of [[Littleport, Cambridgeshire|Littleport]], near [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]]. He would regularly travel to Cambridgeshire from East Anglia on his days free from work to help his father, and soon developed aspirations to become a school caretaker himself. Via his father, Huntley learned of a school caretaker vacancy in nearby Soham Village College in the summer of 2001. He applied for and secured employment as a senior caretaker at this secondary school in September 2001, supervising the work of four other employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Maxine Carr\n| birth_name   = Maxine Ann Capp<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1977|2|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]<ref name=\"ReferenceI\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 53</ref>\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| conviction     = [[Perverting the course of justice]]\n| conviction_penalty        = 42 months' imprisonment\n| conviction_status         = Released\n| occupation     = [[Teaching assistant (United Kingdom)|Teaching assistant]]\n}}\n\n==Maxine Carr==\nMaxine Carr was born Maxine Ann Capp. She was was born in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, on 16 February 1977, the second of two daughters born to Alfred Capp and his wife, Shirley (n\u00e9e Suddaby).<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 52</ref>\n\nThe marriage between Capp's parents was marred by frequent arguments. Following a heated argument in the summer of 1979, Shirley ordered her husband to leave the household. Shortly thereafter, she and her daughters relocated to the village of [[Keelby]]. Alfred seldom maintained contact with his wife and children, and refused to provide any financial support for his daughters. Capp and her older sister, Hayley (born 1967), were largely raised by their mother and grandparents. The family regularly experienced severe financial difficulties, although Shirley would later state she \"spoiled\" her daughters to the best of her financial ability.<ref name=\"ReferenceI\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 53</ref>\n\nAs a child and adolescent, Capp was viewed by her peers as something of a timid outcast, with few friends.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine is Another of His Victims|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/maxine-is-another-one-of-his-victims-7224619.html|accessdate=3 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> She performed poorly academically, although she always held aspirations to become a teacher.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 83</ref>\n\nBy the time Capp entered adolescence, she was slightly overweight, leading her to become insecure about her physical appearance. Although she had shunned the company of boys as a child, as a teenager, she craved\u2014but seldom received\u2014the attention of boys her age, occasionally leading to bouts of [[binge eating]]<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 56</ref> in addition to her developing the habit of [[self-harm]]ing.<ref name=\"The Maxine Question\">{{cite news|title=The Maxine Question|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime3|accessdate=21 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> By age 15, Capp weighed more than 10 [[Stone (unit)|stones]], resulting in her becoming the recipient of bullying by her classmates. In an effort to lose weight, she developed a habit of forcing herself to [[purging disorder|vomit after eating]].<ref name=\"The Evening Standard\"/> This habit led to Capp developing [[anorexia]] by the age of 16, with her weight at one stage plummeting to just six stones, and her mother forcing her to eat in order for her to regain weight.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>\n\nIn 1993, Capp finished her schooling, having obtained no qualifications. She briefly worked alongside her mother in a fish processing plant as she considered which career path she should choose before enrolling at the [[Grimsby Institute of Further & Higher Education]], having chosen to study general care. Capp obtained her diploma in 1996. The same year, she and her mother moved from Keelby back to Grimsby. Shortly thereafter, she briefly obtained employment as a junior care assistant at a care home for the elderly in Grimsby before opting to return to work alongside her mother as a labourer at Bluecrest fish processing plant.<ref name=\"ReferenceJ\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 61</ref>\n\nSeveral of Capp's colleagues would later remark how they found her to be a distant and immature figure with few friends and few hobbies. To one colleague, Capp would talk incessantly about her dreams of leaving this employment and embarking on a teaching career.<ref name=\"ReferenceJ\"/>\n\nBy the time Capp had obtained employment at Bluecrest, she had garnered sufficient courage to begin dating men, although none of these relationships lasted more than a few months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrested Couple Publicly Declared Their Affection for Girls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404703/Arrested-couple-publicly-declared-their-affection-for-girls.html|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=18 August 2002}}</ref> Notably shy and reserved and prone to wear clothing which concealed her figure when sober, Capp became markedly flirtatious when having consumed alcohol, and is known to have occasionally engaged in [[exhibitionism]] in addition to frequently engaging in [[one-night stands]] with individuals she encountered in pubs and clubs.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>{{refn|group=n|Several of Carr's former partners would later inform reporters they found her to be an [[Emotional detachment|emotionally detached]] and sexually promiscuous individual who had also been markedly jealous by nature. These had been the reasons several of her early relationships had ended<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 65</ref>}}\n\nWhile Capp resided with her mother in Grimsby, she unofficially adopted the surname Benson.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham's 'Couple from Hell'|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/soham-s-couple-from-hell-1-1378495|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=The Scotsman|date=18 August 2002}}</ref> She later legally changed her surname to Carr in an apparent effort to distance herself from her father.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>\n\n==Soham employment==\nIn September 2001, Huntley responded to a job advertisement relating to a vacant position of senior caretaker at Soham Village College. He applied for this position using the alias Ian Nixon.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 81</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley's mother's maiden name had been Nixon. Following the separation of his parents in 1993, Huntley chose to use his mother's surname. He would only resume using his father's surname following the 2002 reconciliation of his parents.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=13 March 2017|location=London}}</ref>}} No form of [[background check]] was conducted before or after this job interview,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and although Huntley lacked extensive experience in this form of employment, his application for this position was successful.<ref name=\"https\"/> His employers assisted in his securing the tenancy of 5 College Close,<ref name=\"housegone\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3595801.stm|title=Soham Murder House is Demolished|accessdate=28 April 2017|agency=BBC News}}</ref> and he and Carr relocated to Soham in late September.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley began his employment at Soham Village College on 26 November. He worked as a senior caretaker at these premises until the date of his arrest.<ref name=\"Morris\"/>\n\nIn February 2002, Huntley secured part-time employment for Carr at St Andrew's Primary School, although Carr did lie as to her academic qualifications when applying for this position.<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr: The Teenage Anorexic Who Loved Working with Children and Nights on the Town|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/maxine-carr-the-teenage-anorexic-who-loved-working-with-children-and-nights-on-the-town-83059.html|accessdate=2 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> Although this employment was initially voluntary work, Carr later became a teaching assistant in the school's Year 5 class. Wells and Chapman became two of the pupils she taught,<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> and both girls were notably fond of her.<ref name=\"Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine C\"/>\n\nIn July 2002, Carr applied for a vacant full-time teaching assistant position at St Andrew's Primary School. She received notification on 23 July that her application was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murder Trial Hears of Soham Final Walk|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/murder-trial-hears-of-soham-friends-final-walk-76858.html|accessdate=18 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=5 November 2003}}</ref> One of the children to express dismay at this decision was Wells who, having broken down in tears upon learning Carr's application for the teaching position had been unsuccessful, had presented her with a hand-drawn card,<ref>{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> depicting a smiling face, in which she stated: \"I'll miss you a lot. Thank you! C ya! Miss ya! Luv Holly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Class Helper Failed to Win Full-time Post|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/19/childprotection.children3|accessdate=5 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=19 August 2002}}</ref>\n[[File:MaxineCappHollyWellsCardSoham2002a.jpg|184px|right|thumb|Maxine Carr, seen here on 8 August 2002 displaying the hand-drawn card given to her by Holly Wells. This card was made approximately two weeks before the child's murder.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 190</ref>]]\n\n===Summer 2002===\nBy the summer of 2002, the physical relationship between Huntley and Carr had begun to deteriorate. By Huntley's own later admission, he had become sexually frustrated, and he had unsuccessfully attempted to persuade a married colleague to date him on the weekend Carr visited her mother in Grimsby.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 107</ref>\n\nAt 9:53&nbsp;a.m. on 4 August, Huntley attempted to phone Carr, although she did not answer her mobile phone. Carr only replied to his missed call at 6:23&nbsp;p.m. This four-minute phone call escalated into a heated argument, culminating in Huntley angrily terminating the phone call after she informed him of her intentions to again socialise in Grimsby that evening. Four minutes later, Carr sent Huntley a text message which read: \"Don't make me feel bad because I'm with my family.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> Huntley did not reply to this message.<ref name=\"The Maxine Question\"/>\n\n==Bichard enquiry==\nImmediately following Huntley's conviction, his previous criminal history was disclosed to the public. These disclosures revealed that, despite his extensive record of sexual offences against underage girls and young women and evident criminal recidivism, not only had police failed to pursue these previous criminal complaints and allegations, but Huntley had secured a position of employment facilitating his access to children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley Investigated Eight Times|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/17/soham.ukcrime6|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nUpon learning of these public disclosures, [[Home Secretary]] [[David Blunkett]] announced a [[public inquiry|public enquiry]] into the [[Criminal Records Bureau|intelligence-based record keeping]] and [[Vetting|vetting system]] which had allowed Huntley to obtain employment as a school caretaker despite these previous criminal complaints, which had been reported to both police and social services. Chaired by [[Michael Bichard, Baron Bichard|Sir Michael Bichard]], the [[Bichard report|Bichard enquiry]] opened on 13 January 2004.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Holly and Jessica\"/> The results of this enquiry were published in June that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://police.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/operational-policing/bichard-inquiry-report|title=The Bichard Report|date=17 June 2009|publisher=|work=homeoffice.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe stated purpose of the Bichard enquiry was:\n{{cquote|Urgently to enquire into child protection procedures in [[Humberside Police]] and [[Cambridgeshire Constabulary]] in the light of the recent trial and conviction of Ian Huntley for the murder of Jessica Chapman and Holly Wells.\n\nIn particular to assess the effectiveness of the relevant intelligence-based record keeping, the vetting practices in those forces since 1995 and information sharing with other agencies, and to report to the Home Secretary on matters of local and national relevance and make recommendations as appropriate.}}\n\nOne of the pertinent issues of concern to be scrutinised by the Bichard report surfaced almost immediately when Humberside Police stated their belief in it being unlawful under the [[Data Protection Act 1984|Data Protection Act]] to hold data regarding criminal allegations which had not lead to a conviction; this claim was criticised by other police forces who thought this too strict an interpretation of the Act. The enquiry severely scrutinised the actual investigation by Cambridgeshire Police into the children's disappearance and murder, as almost two weeks had elapsed following the disappearance of Wells and Chapman before Cambridgeshire Police became aware of Huntley's previous criminal background, despite his claims to be the last individual to see the children alive.<ref name=\"Blunder After Blunder\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/children.soham | title=Blunder After Blunder| work=The Guardian |date=18 December 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Further criticism was directed at the force for their initial failure to scrutinise Carr's claims to have been in Soham on the date of the children's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poor Intelligence, Poor Data System and Poor Media Strategy: Police Own Up to Failures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime6|accessdate=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe enquiry also severely criticised Humberside Police for deleting information relating to the previous criminal allegations against Huntley and also criticised Cambridgeshire Police for not following standard vetting guidelines. Both the Humberside and Cambridgeshire Police were heavily criticised for their failings in maintaining criminal intelligence records on Huntley.<ref name=\"Blunder After Blunder\"/>\n\nBichard later ordered the suspension of the Chief of Humberside Police, [[David Westwood]], for ordering the destruction of criminal records pertaining to alleged child molesters which had not resulted in a conviction. (This suspension was later overturned.) Westwood retired from the position of Chief of Humberside Police in March 2005. The Chief Constable of Cambridgeshire Constabulary, Tom Lloyd, was also subjected to severe criticism as his force had failed to contact Humberside Police during the investigation into Huntley's criminal background prior to his securing employment at Soham Village College.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Cambridge Chief Tom Lloyd|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3827459.stm|date=22 June 2004|accessdate=11 March 2014|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAn added complication in these criminal vetting procedures was the fact that Huntley had applied for the caretaker's job under the name of Ian Nixon, although he did divulge upon the application form for this position that he was previously known as Ian Huntley. It is believed that Cambridgeshire Police failed to perform a background check under the name Huntley. Had they actually done so, they would have discovered an outstanding burglary charge on file relating to his November 1995 arrest for this crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blunkett Orders Police Chief's Suspension |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/jun/22/childrensservices.schools|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=22 June 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Recommendations===\nThe Bichard enquiry recommended the implementation of a mandatory registration scheme for people working with children and vulnerable adults such as the elderly and mentally handicapped.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2003/dec/17/childrensservices.soham | work=[[The Guardian]] | title=The CRB Explained: How the Criminal Records Bureau Operates| date=17 December 2003|accessdate=16 April 2011| location=London| first=Polly| last=Curtis}}</ref> This recommendation later led to the foundation of the [[Independent Safeguarding Authority]]. The findings also suggested a national system should be implemented for police forces to share intelligence information, and that all police forces should follow a clear code of practice on record-keeping. These findings ultimately led to the tightening of various procedures within the Criminal Records Bureau system, including compulsory checks into potential criminal backgrounds of people who apply to work with children.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4612038.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Concerns About Teachers' List 99| date=14 January 2006|accessdate=16 April 2011| first=Gary| last=Eason}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAn orange-petalled rose, dedicated to the memory of Wells and Chapman, was unveiled by representatives of Soham Town Council at the 2003 [[Chelsea Flower Show]]. The inspiration for dedicating a flower to the children's memory sourced from a poem read aloud at the memorial service at Ely Cathedral on 30 August 2002 by the father of Wells, titled ''Soham's Rose''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Royals Flock to Flower Show|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3038061.stm|accessdate=18 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=19 May 2003}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2004, the three-bedroomed house in College Close in which the murders occurred was demolished and the site levelled, with all rubble from the property being destroyed and later discarded in various, undisclosed locations.<ref name=\"housegone\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3595801.stm|title=Soham Murder House is Demolished|accessdate=28 April 2017|agency=BBC News}}</ref> The site where 5 College Close once stood is now a vacant patch of grass.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nWithin days of Huntley's formal sentencing, he reflected to the media on the prospect of his spending the remainder of his life behind bars and of his fears for his security, exclaiming: \"I'm going to rot inside this place. I'll rot in here, I know it. I'll spend the rest of my life in here ... I'm going to be inside forever, and it'll be torture.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/did-she-watch-jessica-die-1-1297313|title=Did She Watch Jessica Die?|accessdate=19 December 2019|agency=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\nIn the years since his incarceration, Huntley has been repeatedly attacked by other inmates. On 14 September 2005, he was [[Scalding|scalded]] with boiling water while incarcerated at [[HM Prison Wakefield]] by a fellow inmate. The injuries Huntley received in this attack resulted in his being unable to attend the hearing at which his minimum term of imprisonment was decided.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/west_yorkshire/4248052.stm|title=Huntley Scalded in Prison Attack|work=BBC News|date=15 September 2005|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Following this attack, Huntley alleged that prison authorities had failed in their [[Duty of care in English law|duty of care]] towards him, and launched a claim for \u00a315,000 in compensation. He was reportedly awarded \u00a32,500 in [[legal aid]] to pursue this claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.gov.agency.csa.narkive.com/fDMVabgO/anyone-facing-jail-by-the-csa-compare-it-with-this|title=Anyone Facing Jail by the Child Support Agency Compare it With This|date=6 August 2005|publisher=|work=uk.gov}}</ref>\n\nHuntley was transferred from Wakefield prison to [[HM Prison Frankland|Frankland prison]] on 23 January 2008. Three years later, on 21 March 2010, he received non life-threatening injuries to his neck after his throat was [[Slashing (crime)|slashed]] by a convicted [[armed robbery|armed robber]] named Damien Fowkes. The injuries Huntley received in this attack required hospital treatment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/8579226.stm |title=Soham Murderer Ian Huntley Attacked by Jail Inmate |work=[[BBC News]] |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Huntley again applied for compensation for the injuries he received in this attack, seeking \u00a320,000 in [[damages]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ian Huntley Could Get \u00a320,000 Compensation After Prison Attack|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7502752/Ian-Huntley-could-get-20000-compensation-after-prison-attack.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15163465 |title=Ian Huntley: Prisoner Admits Attacking Soham Killer |work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15181854 |title=Ian Huntley Attacker Damien Fowkes Gets Life Term |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 October 2011 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2006, Huntley attempted to commit suicide by taking an overdose of antidepressants he had accumulated in his prison cell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/5314944.stm |title=Soham Killer Treated for Overdose |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 September 2006 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> This suicide attempt resulted in his hospitalisation and a thorough search of his cell, in which a cassette tape was recovered. This cassette tape contains a markedly different account of the murders of Wells and Chapman than that Huntley had testified to at his trial. In what Huntley had believed would be his posthumous confession, he claims to have confessed to having murdered both girls to Carr prior to their arrest and his plans to confess to authorities, to which, Huntley alleged, Carr had slapped his face and informed him to \"pull [himself] together\" as she did not wish to lose the teaching position she had yearned for all her life. Huntley further alleges Carr had encouraged him to burn both bodies in an attempt to destroy all forensic evidence linking him to the crime.<ref name=\"Steele\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1546975/Huntley-revealed-all-in-taped-confession.html |title=Huntley Revealed All in Taped Confession |work=The Telegraph |date=29 March 2007 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |first=John |last=Steele}}</ref> It is believed Huntley had agreed to make this recording for a fellow prisoner (who had hoped to later sell the confession to the media after his release), in return for his being provided with the antidepressants he had used to attempt suicide.<ref name=\"Steele\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1546975/Huntley-revealed-all-in-taped-confession.html |title=Huntley Fooled Prison's Suicide Watch by Hiding 29 Anti-depressant Pills in Teabags |work=The Telegraph |date=10 June 2003 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |first=Sean |last=O'Neill}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, Huntley confessed to having sexually assaulted an 11-year-old girl whom he had dragged into an orchard in 1997. This admission\u2014in which Huntley also confessed to having a sexual interest in children while insisting the murders of Wells and Chapman had not been sexually motivated\u2014was welcomed by the victim of this sexual assault.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1499498/Judge-outlines-reasons-for-sentence.html |title=Judge Outlines Reasons for Sentence |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=29 September 2005 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Following Huntley's admission of guilt, this victim issued a press statement in which she confessed to feeling \"a massive sense of relief\", although she concluded this statement with the sentence: \"Yet, I still feel upset that Huntley was left at large, resulting in the deaths of two innocent children.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1549612/Huntley-admits-sex-attack-on-girl-in-1997.html |title=Huntley Admits Sex Attack on Girl in 1997 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 April 2007 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London |first=John |last=Steele}}</ref>\n\nCarr was released on [[probation]] from [[HM Prison Foston Hall]] on 14 May 2004 after serving a total of 21 months' imprisonment (including the 16 months she had been detained while on remand).<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 285</ref> She was given a secret identity to protect her from threats of attack from vengeful members of the public<ref>{{cite news|title=How Maxine Carr Might Start a New Life |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/3700583.stm|accessdate=16 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=11 May 2004}}</ref> in addition to being provided with a new home in an undisclosed location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446601/Jessica-and-Holly-doted-on-Maxine-Carr-says-teacher.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Maxine Carr to Get Police Guard on Release|last1=O'Neill|first1=Sean|date=7 February 2004|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Carr is one of four former prisoners in the United Kingdom to be given an entirely new identity upon release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3713243.stm |title=Carr Released from Prison |work = BBC News |date= 14 May 2004 |accessdate = }}</ref> Carr won an [[injunction]] on 24 February 2005, granting her lifelong anonymity on the grounds that her life would otherwise be in danger. The costs of imposing this order have been reported by differing tabloid newspapers as being between \u00a31&nbsp;million and \u00a350&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/feb/28/pressandpublishing.mondaymediasection2 |title=Selling Lies is Not Press Freedom |work= The Guardian |first=Roy |last=Greenslade |authorlink=Roy Greenslade |date=28 February 2005|accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nAt least a dozen women have been falsely identified as being Carr and either persecuted or physically attacked due to false stories speculating as to her whereabouts and new identity which have been printed in tabloid publications.<ref name=\"Guardian 16 May 2005\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/16/mondaymediasection11|title=PCC Must Act Over Hounding of Maxine Carr |work=The Guardian |first=Roy |last=Greenslade |authorlink=Roy Greenslade |date=16 May 2005 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/5282960.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Look-alike Claim 'Nightmare' | date=24 August 2006 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article473996.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Mob Torments Scots Woman Mistaken for Maxine Carr | first=Gillian | last=Harris | date=25 August 2004 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4403113.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Look-alike Goes into Hiding | date=2 April 2005 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nShortly after her release from prison, Carr and her family contacted a [[Tyneside]]-based publishing company with view to publishing her [[autobiography]]. Although [[Mirage Publishing]] initially agreed to publish Carr's autobiography, the company soon withdrew their offer after a feature on [[BBC Radio Newcastle]] prompted scores of complaints from the public.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Publisher Scraps Carr Book Deal |date=5 March 2005|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/4310763.stm}}</ref>\n\nIn the years since her release, Carr has married. She reportedly gave birth to her first child in 2011. The imposed lifetime anonymity order extends to include the birth date and gender of her child, in order that he or she should never know their mother's previous identity.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2055570/Soham-liar-Maxine-Carr-gives-birth--baby-know-mother-really-is.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Maxine Carr Gives Birth to Her First Child: Baby Will Never Know True Identity of its Mother | date=31 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n===Literature===\n* {{cite book|last=Gerrard|first=Nicci |title=Soham: A Story of Our Times|year=2004|publisher=Short Books|isbn=978-1-904-09592-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nathan |title=Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley|year=2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=1844541428}}\n\n===Television===\n* The [[Channel 4]] documentary ''Being Maxine Carr'' focuses on the lasting public outrage at Carr's efforts to pervert the course of justice following the Soham murders, and how numerous women across the UK have been falsely accused of being Carr.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/mum-mistaken-maxine-carr-hopes-3737370 | work=Teesside Live | title=Mum Mistaken as Maxine Carr Hopes TV Show Will End Ordeal | date=12 December 2007 | accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref> This documentary was first broadcast on 14 December 2007.<ref name=\"Being Maxine Carr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/being-maxine-carr/episode-guide/series-1/episode-1 |title=Being Maxine Carr |publisher=[[Channel 4]] |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n* The 90-minute documentary ''Soham Revisited: 15 Years On'' was first broadcast on 25 April 2017. Narrated by [[Alison Steadman]], this documentary features interviews with previous lovers of Huntley.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.itnproductions.co.uk/latest-news/soham-revisited-15-years-on-documentary-1 | work=ITN Productions | title=Soham Murders: 15 Years On | date=27 April 2017 | accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Investigation Discovery]] channel has broadcast a 60-minute documentary focusing upon the Soham murders as part of their ''Faking It: Tears of a Crime'' true crime documentary series. This documentary primarily focuses upon the efforts made by Huntley and Carr to deceive police and public alike, and was first broadcast on 18 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tv24.co.uk/p/faking-it-tears-of-a-crime-season-2-episode-1-d7tl77 |title=Faking It: Tears of a Crime |publisher=TV24 |date=18 August 2007 |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] have also commissioned a documentary focusing upon the Soham murders. This documentary, titled ''5 Mistakes That Caught a Killer'', was first broadcast on 23 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/ian-huntley-5-mistakes-killer-facing-justice-revealed-in-tonight-channel-5-documentary-501484 | work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] | title=Ian Huntley: The 5 Mistakes That Led to The Soham Killer's Downfall Explored in Tonight's Channel 5 Documentary | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Bichard report]]\n* [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Child abduction]]\n* [[Child sexual abuse]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Criminal Justice Act 2003]]\n* [[List of solved missing persons cases]]\n* [[Perverting the course of justice]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Law|England|United Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Bruce|first=Alison |title=Cambridgeshire Murders|year=2012|publisher=History Press|isbn=978-0-752-48413-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Collins|first=Danny |title=Crimes That Shocked The World|year=2010|publisher=John Blake Publishing Ltd|isbn=1-844-54974-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Duffy|first=Wendy |title=Children and Bereavement|year=2003|publisher=Church House Publishing| isbn=0-715-14998-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gerrard|first=Nicci |title=Soham: A Story of Our Times|year=2004|publisher=Short Books|isbn=978-1-904-09592-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=Thomas|title=Court Number One: The Old Bailey Trials that Defined Modern Britain|year=2019|publisher=John Murray Publishing|isbn=978-1-473-65161-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=McKenzie|first=Dennis |title=Being the Soham Psychic|year=2009|publisher=Headline Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-755-31982-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wells|first=Kevin|title=Goodbye, Dearest Holly|year=2005|publisher=Psychology News Press Ltd|isbn=978-0-907633-02-0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/goodbyedearestho0000well}}\n* {{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nathan |title=Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley|year=2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=978-1844-54142-3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* August 2002 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2205778.stm news article] pertaining to the arrest of Ian Huntley\n* November 2003 [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3251181.stm BBC News article] pertaining to the trial of Ian Huntley and Maxine Carr\n* December 2003 [[BBC News]] article [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3312551.stm detailing Ian Huntley's conviction of the murders of Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman]\n* September 2005 news article [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/4293158.stm detailing the minimum sentence imposed upon Ian Huntley]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3313501.stm BBC News report Retrospective news article] detailing Ian Huntley's criminal record\n* ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' article pertaining to Ian Huntley's [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1546975/Huntley-revealed-all-in-taped-confession.html confessions to the murders of Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman]\n* [https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/reports/a11435528/soham-murders-jessica-chapman-holly-wells-ian-huntley/ ''Soham Murders: What Happened to Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman''] at cosmopolitan.com\n* 2017 ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' article questioning Ian Huntley's [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/soham-murders-ian-huntley/ actual motive for committing the Soham Murders]\n* 2019 ''[[Coventry Telegraph]]'' article detailing [https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/uk-world-news/maxine-carr-ian-huntley-murder-16320346 Maxine Carr's efforts] to [[Perverting the course of justice|pervert the course of justice]]\n* ''[https://www.wired-gov.net/wg/wg-news-1.nsf/54e6de9e0c383719802572b9005141ed/1ec1e945929a7eac802572ab004b9a75?OpenDocument Summary]'' of the official [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Constabulary and Fire & Rescue Services|HMIC]] report into the Soham Murders investigation\n* {{Find a Grave|26787966|Holly Wells}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6693471|Jessica Chapman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soham murders}}\n[[Category:2000s in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2002 in England]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:August 2002 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Crime in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:English murderers of children]]\n[[Category:English sex offenders]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people found dead]]\n[[Category:History of Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in England]]\n[[Category:Murder in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Murdered English children]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Soham]]\n[[Category:Violence against children]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Jessica Chapman<br />Holly Wells\n| image           = File:HollyWellsJessicaChapmanSummer2002SohamCambridgeshire2.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Jessica Chapman (left) and Holly Wells (right), pictured in the summer of 2002\n| birth_name      = Jessica Aimee Chapman<br />{{Birth date|1991|9|1|df=y}}<br />Holly Marie Wells<br />{{Birth date|1991|10|4|df=y}}\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = [[Soham]], [[Cambridgeshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date      = Both [[Circa|c.]] {{Death date and age|2002|8|4|1991|9|1|df=y}}\n| death_place     = Soham, Cambridgeshire, England\n|death_cause      = [[Determinism|Undetermined]]. Possible [[asphyxiation]]<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref>\n| body_discovered = 17 August 2002<br />[[Lakenheath]], [[Suffolk]], England\n| resting_place      = Soham Cemetery, Cambridgeshire, England\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord|52.32662|N|0.34642|W|region:UK_type:landmark|display=inline}} (approximate) <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| known_for = Victims of [[child murder]]\n| parents         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Soham Murders''' are the murders of two 10-year-old girls which occurred in [[Soham]], [[Cambridgeshire]], England on 4 August 2002. The victims, Holly Marie Wells and Jessica Aimee Chapman, were lured into the home of a local resident, Ian Kevin Huntley,<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> who subsequently murdered the children\u2014likely via [[asphyxiation]]\u2014before disposing of their bodies in an irrigation ditch close to [[RAF Lakenheath]], [[Suffolk]]. The girls' bodies were discovered on 17 August 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Arrested in Girls' Murder Enquiry|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2199168.stm|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nHuntley was convicted of the [[Murder in English law|murder]] of both girls on 17 December 2003 and sentenced to two terms of [[life imprisonment]], with the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] later imposing a [[Mandatory sentencing|minimum term]] of 40 years. His girlfriend, Maxine Ann Carr\u2014the girls' [[teaching assistant]]\u2014had knowingly provided Huntley with a false [[alibi]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr Gave Alibi to Save Me; Not to Deceive Police|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448355/Maxine-gave-alibi-to-save-me-not-to-deceive-police.html|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=3 December 2003}}</ref> She received a three-and-a-half year prison sentence for [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiring]] with Huntley to [[perverting the course of justice|pervert the course of justice]].<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Judge Gives Huntley Forty Years - And Little Hope|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499550/Judge-gives-Huntley-40-years-and-little-hope.html|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=30 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe efforts made to locate Wells and Chapman in the thirteen days of their disappearance have been described as one of the most intense and extensive in British criminal history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caretaker Charged with Murder of Two Girls and Sent to Rampton|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404950/Caretaker-charged-with-murder-of-two-girls-and-sent-to-Rampton.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=21 August 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\">{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/last-hours-of-holly-and-jessica-6950277.html | title = Last Hours of Holly and Jessica| work = The Evening Standard| accessdate = 4 November 2019 | date = 6 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance==\nAt 11:45&nbsp;a.m. on Sunday, 4 August 2002, Jessica Chapman left her home in Brook Street, Soham, to attend a barbecue at the home of her best friend, Holly Wells, in nearby Redhouse Gardens.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/> Prior to leaving her home, Chapman informed her parents of her intention to also give her friend a necklace engraved with the letter ''H'' she had purchased for her on a recent family holiday to [[Menorca]].<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/>\n\nThe two girls and a friend named Natalie Parr played computer games and listened to music for approximately half an hour<ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\">{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting For News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> before Parr returned home.<ref name=\"The Scotsman\">{{cite news|title=At Night I Sometimes Just Lay There and Cry|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/at-night-i-sometimes-just-lay-there-and-cry-1-897763|accessdate=27 October 2019|work=The Scotsman|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> By 3:15&nbsp;p.m., both girls had changed into distinctive replica [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] football shirts; one of which belonged to Wells and the other to her older brother, Oliver.<ref name=\"Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved t\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/23/childprotection.uk |title=Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved to Woodland |work=The Guardian |date=23 August 2002 |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref> At 5:04&nbsp;p.m., a photograph of the two friends was taken by Wells' mother before the children ate dinner with the other house guests. They then returned to playing in Wells' bedroom at approximately 6:10&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/><ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\"/>\n\nAt approximately 6:15&nbsp;p.m., the two girls left the Wells residence without informing any of the house guests to purchase sweets from a vending machine at the local sports centre. While returning to 4 Redhouse Gardens,<ref>{{cite news|title=Holly and Jessica: Timetable|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=4 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> Wells and Chapman walked past the College Close home of Ian Huntley, the senior caretaker at the local [[secondary school]]. Huntley evidently lured the girls into his house, stating that his girlfriend, Maxine Carr\u2014the girls' teaching assistant at [[St Andrew's Primary School (Soham)|St Andrew's Primary School]]\u2014was also present in the house. (Carr was actually visiting her mother in [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]] on this date.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mistake Made by Maxine Carr that Showed She Knew Ian Huntley had Killed Soham Schoolgirls|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/maxine-carr-ian-huntley-soham-16320951|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=Chronicle Live|date=23 May 2019}}</ref>)\n\nThe precise chain of events to occur after the girls entered 5 College Close is unknown, although investigators believe sections of Huntley's later claims in initial interviews granted to the media prior to his arrest and his later trial testimony\u2014such as that he had been cleaning his dog at the time the girls passed by his house at approximately 6:30&nbsp;p.m. and that one girl had been suffering from a mild nosebleed\u2014may have actually been true.<ref name=\"https\"/> In any event, the [[cause of death]] of both girls was later ruled to be [[asphyxiation]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite news|title=As Day Breaks, Huntley's House is Turned Into Dust and Rubble |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/apr/04/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=3 April 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"Huntley guilty of Soham Murders\"/> Chapman's [[Nokia 6110|Nokia]] mobile phone was switched off at 6:46&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=Was Jealousy Over Maxine the Trigger for Murder?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449727/Was-jealousy-over-Maxine-the-trigger-for-murder.html|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nAt 8:00&nbsp;p.m., Nicola Wells entered her daughter's bedroom to invite the girls to say goodbye to her house guests, only to discover both children were missing from their home. Alarmed, she and her husband, Kevin, searched their house and nearby streets. Minutes after their daughter's 8:30&nbsp;p.m. [[curfew]] had expired, Nicola Wells phoned the Chapman residence to determine if the girls were at this location, only to learn Leslie and Sharon Chapman were becoming concerned why their youngest daughter had not returned home.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting For News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> Following subsequent frantic efforts by the families of both girls to locate their daughters, Wells and Chapman were reported [[missing person|missing]] by their parents at 9.55&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3244403.stm | work=BBC News | title=Timeline: Girls' Last Movements | date=5 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nPolice immediately launched an intensive manhunt to locate the missing children.<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref> Over 400 officers were assigned full-time to search for the girls.<ref>{{cite news|title='Calculated Cover-up' by Huntley and Carr as Girls Lay Dead in Wood|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446118/Calculated-cover-up-by-Huntley-and-Carr-as-girls-lay-dead-in-wood.html|accessdate=25 October 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> These officers conducted extensive house-to-house enquiries across Soham;<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404950/Caretaker-charged-with-murder-of-two-girls-and-sent-to-Rampton.html | work=The Telegraph | first1=Sean | last1=O'Neill | first2=David | last2=Sapsted |title=Caretaker Charged With Murder of Two Girls and Sent to Rampton | date=21 August 2002}}</ref> their efforts to search local terrain were bolstered by the assistance of hundreds of local volunteers<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm | title = How Huntley's Charade Crumbled| work = BBC News | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 17 December 2003}}</ref> and, later, [[United States Air Force]] personnel stationed at nearby airbases.<ref>{{cite news|title=Holly and Jessica: Two Bodies Found in Woods|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/18/childprotection.society6|accessdate=7 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=18 August 2002}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|The total population of [[Soham]] in 2002 was 8,700<ref>{{cite news|title=The Whole Town is Weeping: A Community Dazed by Grief and Disbelief|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/19/childprotection.children1|accessdate=25 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 August 2002}}</ref>}}\n\nTo assist in their public appeals for information, [[Cambridgeshire Constabulary|Cambridgeshire Police]] released the photograph Nicola Wells had taken of the children less than two hours before their disappearance depicting both girls wearing distinctive Manchester United replica football shirts. A physical description of each girl was also released to the media, describing both girls as being white, approximately 4&nbsp;ft 6 in tall, and slim. Chapman was described as being tanned, with shoulder-length, brown hair; Wells was described as being [[Light skin|fair]], with blonde hair.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2173505.stm | title = 'Extreme Concern' for Missing Girls | work = BBC News | accessdate = 30 August 2008 | date = 5 August 2002}}</ref> The parents of both girls were adamant their daughters had been wary of talking with strangers, having warned them not to trust individuals they did not know from early childhood. This insistence was supported by the headteacher of St Andrew's Primary School, who informed reporters: \"The possible danger from strangers is something we have impressed upon [the children] from an early age.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 98</ref>\n\nSuspecting the children had been [[kidnapping|kidnapped]], investigators questioned every registered [[sex offender]] in Cambridgeshire and Lincolnshire.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 171</ref> Over 260 registered sex offenders across the UK\u2014including fifteen high-risk [[paedophile]]s\u2014were also questioned, although all were eliminated from the enquiry.<ref name=\"Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls\">{{cite news | url = https://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/missing-abduction-linked-to-soham-girls-1-104788 | title = Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls | work = Peterborough Telegraph | accessdate = 22 November 2019 | date = 13 August 2002}}</ref> Police also investigated the possibility that the girls had arranged to meet with an individual either or both had contacted via an [[Chat room|internet chat room]], although this possibility was soon discounted.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2002/aug/12/childprotection.missingpersons | title = Chatroom Contact Dismissed as False Lead | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 12 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/3232051.stm|title=Soham Trial Timeline|date=3 November 2003|publisher=}}</ref> [[CCTV]] footage of the girls, recorded minutes before their disappearance, was released to the public. This footage depicted the children arriving at the local sports centre at 6:28&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/09/childprotection.children | title = Film Released of Missing Girls | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 9 August 2002}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators were able to obtain extensive footage of the children's movements following their departure from the Wells household. The last piece of footage of Wells and Chapman depicts the children walking onto a car park on the grounds of Soham Village College<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 106</ref>}} A televised reconstruction of the children's last known movements was also broadcast nationally on 10 August,<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404103/Reconstruction-of-childrens-walk-too-painful-for-parents-to-watch.html | title = Reconstruction of Children's Walk Too Painful for Parents to Watch | work = The Telegraph | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 11 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/11/childprotection.society2 | title = Walking in the Last Known Footsteps of Holly and Jessica | work = The Guardian | accessdate = 8 April 2017 | date = 11 August 2002}}</ref> and both sets of parents granted an interview with presenter Colin Baker on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] programme ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'', which was broadcast on 12 August.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404171/Parents-in-TV-plea-for-return-of-girls.html | title = Parents in TV Plea for Return of Girls | work = The Telegaph | accessdate = 16 December 2019 | date = 12 August 2002}}</ref> Other family members and friends of both girls also appealed via the media for the safe return of the children.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 5</ref> These appeals for information regarding the whereabouts of Wells and Chapman would see more than 2,000 phone calls and tips received from the public, with all information obtained entered into the investigation's [[HOLMES 2]] database.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2177998.stm|title=Van Seized in Missing Girls Inquiry|date=7 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley was present at one of the [[press conference]]s in which the parents of Wells and Chapman pleaded for the safe return of their daughters.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 13</ref> On this occasion, he offered his condolences to the father of Wells, stating: \"Kevin, I'm so sorry. I didn't realise it was your daughter.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3263615.stm | title = Huntley 'Comforted Holly's Dad' | work = BBC News | accessdate = 31 December 2019 | date = 12 November 2003}}</ref>}} A [[candlelight vigil]] was held by the community on 7 August.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/friend-tells-of-worry-for-girls-6310331.html | title = Friends Tell of Worry for Girls | work = The Evening Standard | accessdate = 31 October 2019 | date = 8 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the children's disappearance, [[Staffordshire Police]] contacted their counterparts to report their suspicions the girls' likely [[Child abduction|abduction]] may be linked to an abduction which had occurred in their jurisdiction the previous year, in which a six-year-old girl had survived an [[indecent assault]] by an abductor who was still at large and whose green [[Ford Mondeo]] was identified as having number-plates which had earlier been stolen in [[Peterborough]]. The individual responsible for this abduction and assault was also believed to have followed a 12-year-old girl in the same area, although in this instance, his car had been fitted with number-plates which had been stolen in [[Nottinghamshire]].<ref name=\"Abductionn Linked to Soham Girls\"/> The same vehicle had recently been sighted in [[Glatton]], Cambridgeshire. This information was later included in a televised appeal pertaining to the children's disappearance on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Crimewatch]]'', although this potential lead ultimately failed to bear fruition or relevance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Abduction-sixyearold-linked-missing-girls/story-21477497-detail/story.html|title=Abduction of Six-year-old May be Linked to Missing Girls|date=12 August 2002|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Sightings===\nSeveral members of the public reported having seen the children in the early days of the investigation. One individual, Mark Tuck, informed investigators that as he had driven past the girls upon Sand Street in Soham town centre at approximately 6:30&nbsp;p.m. on 4 August,<ref>{{cite news|title=A Long Night Waiting for News That Never Came|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446599/A-long-night-waiting-for-news-that-never-came.html|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 November 2003}}</ref> his attention had been drawn toward their Manchester United replica shirts, causing him to remark to his wife, Lucy: \"Look! There's two little [[David Beckham|Beckhams]] over there.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Countdown to Murder of 'Two Little Beckhams'|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/countdown-to-murder-of-two-little-beckhams-20031106-gdhqdv.html|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> A young woman named Karen Greenwood also reported seeing the girls walking \"arm in arm\" along College Road approximately two minutes later.<ref name=\"A Long Night Waiting For News That\"/> Another woman living in the nearby village of [[Little Thetford]] claimed to have seen two girls whose appearance and clothing matched those of Wells and Chapman walking past her home the morning after the children had been reported missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2175995.stm|title=Beckham's Plea to Missing Girls|date=6 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Police also received statements regarding a white van that had been seen in Soham on the evening of the children's disappearance. Investigators located and seized this vehicle from a caravan park in [[Wentworth, Cambridgeshire|Wentworth]] on 7 August, although this lead ultimately proved fruitless.<ref name=\"BBC News\"/>\n\nOn 12 August, police launched a media appeal to trace the driver of a four-door, dark green saloon car seen struggling with two young girls by a taxi driver who stated he had observed this individual \"thrashing his arms\" as he struggled to either placate or contain two female children inside his vehicle as he had driven upon the [[A142 road|A142]] south of Soham towards [[Newmarket, Suffolk|Newmarket]] on the early evening of 12 August. The following evening, a jogger alerted police to two mounds of recently disturbed earth he had encountered at Warren Hill, just outside Newmarket.<ref>{{cite news |title=Soham Murders: Timeline|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/soham-murders-timeline-8045799.html |newspaper=The Evening Standard |date=14 August 2012}}</ref> The initial speculation by this individual had been that these mounds of earth may be the impromptu burial locations of the two missing girls. However, an overnight examination of this location revealed the two mounds of earth to simply be [[Sett|badger setts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1404211/Driver-struggled-with-two-children.html|title=Driver 'Struggled' With Two Children|date=12 August 2002|publisher=|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOne individual who claimed to have spoken with the girls immediately before their disappearance was 28-year-old Huntley, who informed investigators on 5 August he had engaged in a brief conversation with both girls on his doorstep the previous afternoon.<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\">{{cite news|title=Huntley Cries in Dock|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-cries-in-dock-7235641.html|accessdate=5 November 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=1 December 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley's precise motivation for voluntarily informing police of his encountering the children outside his home is unknown, although it is speculated he chose to do so out of concerns [[witness|eyewitnesses]] may have seen him engaging in conversation with the girls outside his home<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 113</ref>}} According to Huntley, Wells and Chapman had briefly enquired as to whether his partner, Carr, had been successful in a recent application for a full-time teaching assistant position at their school.<ref name=\"Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine C\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446601/Jessica-and-Holly-doted-on-Maxine-Carr-says-teacher.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine Carr, Says Teacher|last1=O'Neill|first1=Sean|last2=Clough|first2=Sue|date=13 November 2003|access-date=16 November 2019}}</ref> When he had replied Carr had been unsuccessful, one of the girls had said, \"Tell her we're sorry\" before both children had walked along College Street in the direction of a bridge leading towards Clay Street.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Piece Together Last Sightings of Girls|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/police-piece-together-last-sightings-of-girls-1-616210|accessdate=4 January 2020|work=The Scotsman|date=9 August 2002}}</ref> Police were suspicious of Huntley's account of the children's disappearance. His house was searched by a single police officer on 5 August. Although no [[incriminating evidence]] was discovered on this date, this officer noticed numerous items of clothing upon the washing line despite the fact it had been raining. In reference to the evident extensive cleaning of the house's interior, Huntley stated: \"Excuse the dining room. We had a flood.\"<ref name=\"O'Neill\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446118/Calculated-cover-up-by-Huntley-and-Carr-as-girls-lay-dead-in-wood.html|work=The Telegraph|title='Calculated Cover-up' by Huntley and Carr as Girls Lay Dead in Wood|last=O'Neill|first=Sean|date=7 November 2003|access-date=9 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators would later determine Wells and Chapman had most likely been attacked\u2014and possibly murdered\u2014in the dining room of College Close<ref>{{cite news|title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm|accessdate=3 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>}} This officer was unconvinced by Huntley's claims and suspicious of his agitated demeanour, and he remained a strong suspect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime6|title=Poor Intelligence, Poor Data System and Poor Media Strategy: Police Own Up to Failures|date=17 December 2003|publisher=|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nOne day later, on 6 August, Huntley drove from Soham to Grimsby to pick up Carr. Shortly before the two returned to College Close,<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley's Question to Police: 'Am I a Suspect?'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/18/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=27 December 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 November 2003}}</ref> a neighbour of Carr's mother named Marion Clift observed the couple standing at the rear of the vehicle, with the [[Trunk (car)|boot]] open. According to Clift, a \"pale, shaking\"<ref name=\"Huntley's Question to Police: Am I\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/18/soham.ukcrime|work=The Guardian|title=Huntley's Question to Police: Am I a Suspect?|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=18 November 2003|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> Huntley had simply gazed into the boot for several moments, while Carr stood alongside him, her head bowed, weeping. When Huntley became aware of Clift's presence, he had abruptly closed the boot.<ref name=\"O'Neill\"/>\n{{quote box\n| quote =  I don't know the girls. I was stood on the front doorstep [[Dog grooming|grooming]] my dog down. She'd run away and come back a bit of a mess ... they just came across and asked how [Maxine] was ... I just said she weren't very good as she hadn't got the job and they just says please tell her that we're very sorry and off they walked; in the direction of the library over there.<ref>{{cite news |title=TV No Preparation for Witness Box|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/dec/18/broadcasting.comment1 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n| source = Ian Huntley, interviewed by [[Sky News]] correspondent [[Jeremy Thompson]]. 15 August 2002<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\">{{cite news |title=Last TV Interviews of the Accused|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447185/Last-TV-interviews-of-the-accused.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 November 2003}}</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\n\n===Media interviews===\nIn the weeks following the disappearances, Huntley reluctantly<ref>{{cite news|title=Caretaker was Sure Holly and Jessica had Not Run Away|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11955143.its-got-to-be-two-people-they-trust-caretaker-was-sure-holly-and-jessica-had-not-run-away/|accessdate=23 November 2019|work=Herald Scotland|date=17 August 2002}}</ref> granted several television interviews to media outlets such as [[Sky News]] and the regional [[BBC News]] programme, ''[[BBC Look East]]'', speaking of the general shock in the local community and his apparent dismay at being the last individual to see the children alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/missing-girls-police-in-appeal-to-abductor-172646.html|title=Missing Girls: Police Appeal to Abductor|date=9 August 2002|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|By the second week of the children's disappearance, Huntley had volunteered to become a spokesman for the community of Soham. His explanation for this decision was that he wished to convey the frustration and despair the community was feeling to the media, and to vocalise his belief the criticism some members of the public had begun to direct towards the police for failing to locate the children was misguided consternation.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 177</ref>}} In one interview granted to Sky News correspondent [[Jeremy Thompson]] during the second week of the search, he claimed to be holding on to a \"glimmer of hope\"<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\"/> the children would be found safe and well, claiming that he had last seen the girls walking in the direction of a local library.<ref name=beyond/> Having actively participated in the search for the children, Huntley also made efforts to ingratiate police officers; regularly asking questions as to how their investigation was progressing and just how long [[DNA profiling|DNA evidence]] could survive before deteriorating.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> One of these officers observed three vertical scratches upon Huntley's left jaw, each measuring approximately three centimetres, which he claimed had been recently inflicted by his dog.<ref name=\"Huntley's Question to Police: Am I\"/>\n\nCarr was also interviewed by the press during the second week of the search for the children.<ref name=\"Last TV Interviews of the Accused\">{{cite news |title=Last TV Interviews of the Accused|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447185/Last-TV-interviews-of-the-accused.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=20 November 2003}}</ref> In this live interview, Carr [[Corroborating evidence|corroborated]] Huntley's claims to have conversed with the children on their doorstep as she had been bathing before both girls had walked away from their doorstep, adding: \"I only wish we had asked them where they were going ... if only we knew then what we know now. Then we could have stopped them, or done something about it.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 187</ref>\n\nDiscussing the individual personalities of each girl, Carr described Wells as being the \"more [[femininity|feminine]]\" of the two, adding that Chapman was \"more of a [[tomboy]]\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Arrested Couple Publicly Declared their Affection for Girls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404703/Arrested-couple-publicly-declared-their-affection-for-girls.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=18 August 2002}}</ref> and that on one occasion, she had jokingly remarked to Chapman how, unlike many of her friends, she seldom wore a skirt. To this question, Carr stated the child had expressed her desire to be a [[bridesmaid]] at her own future wedding, adding how Chapman had said she would willingly wear a dress for such an occasion.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 188</ref> Carr also displayed a thank-you card to this reporter which had recently been given to her by Wells on the last day of the school year. Referring to Wells in the [[past tense]], Carr stated, \"She was just lovely, really lovely\", before making a direct appeal to the children: \"Just get on the phone and just come home. Or if somebody's got them, just let them go.\"<ref name=beyond/>{{refn|group=n|Carr's decision to corroborate Huntley's blatant lies to investigators and media in the early stages of the police investigation briefly resulted in police discounting Huntley as a suspect before eyewitness accounts as to Carr's actual whereabouts on 4 August and a search of mobile phone and telephone records proved the [[False evidence|falsity]] of her claims.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3301589.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Prolonged Soham's Agony | date=17 December 2003 | accessdate=23 May 2010 | first=Peter | last=Gould}}</ref>}}\n\nBy the second week of the children's disappearance, Huntley had begun to lose weight and vividly displayed symptoms of [[insomnia]].<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 11</ref> To one officer, he begged the question: \"You think I've done it? I was the last person to see them!\" before beginning to weep. His erratic and distressful behaviour led to his being prescribed [[anti-depressant]]s on 13 August.<ref name=\"Evening Standard 17 December 2003\">{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title= Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html| date= 17 December 2003 |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard|Evening Standard]] |location=London| accessdate= 2 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Police suspicions==\nOn 16 August, twelve days after the children's disappearance, Huntley and Carr were first questioned by police. Both were questioned for approximately seven hours. Each provided formal [[witness statement]]s to investigators before being placed in a safe house in the village of [[Histon and Impington|Histon]].<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 215</ref> By this date, police had received information from several Grimsby residents who had recognised Huntley in the television interviews he had granted to the media; these individuals recalled that he had been accused of [[rape]] several years earlier. Other individuals recalled that, contrary to her own televised claims, Carr had in fact been socialising in Grimsby town centre on the night that the girls had disappeared, and not at home in Soham as she had indicated in the interview she had granted to the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Said Fake Alibi was Her Idea|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3244798.stm|accessdate=31 October 2019|work=BBC News|date=27 November 2003}}</ref>\n[[File:Soham Village College - geograph.org.uk - 269552.jpg|190px|right|thumb|[[Soham Village College]]. Police discovered charred remnants of the children's clothes at this location on 16 August<ref>{{cite web|title=I Cut Clothes off Bodies, Says Huntley|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447645/I-cut-clothes-off-bodies-says-Huntley.html|accessdate=30 November 2019|date=25 November 2003}}</ref>]]\nThe same evening, police conducted a thorough search of both 5 College Close and the grounds of [[Soham Village College]] where Huntley worked as a senior caretaker<ref name=\"Morris\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=16 April 2011|location=London}}</ref> as the couple remained under police watch at separate locations outside Soham. Although each room of Huntley's home had evidently been recently and meticulously cleaned<ref>{{cite news|title=Not a Single Fingerprint in the House|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449715/Not-a-single-fingerprint-in-the-house.html|accessdate=1 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> with what was later described as being a \"lemony\" cleaning fluid,<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref> these searches located numerous items declared as being of \"major importance\" to the ongoing investigation. Although the [[Evidence (law)|evidence]] and artifacts were not made public at the time, the items recovered from the school grounds included items of clothing the girls had been wearing when last seen, including their charred and cut Manchester United shirts, which were recovered from a bin within a [[hangar]] at Huntley's place of work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3233558.stm|title=Huntley Admits Cutting Up Clothes|date=24 November 2003|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley had attempted to burn these clothes in the late evening of 4 August, although the [[Fire accelerant|accelerant]] he used for this purpose had caused a blaze which he believed may attract attention, causing him to quickly extinguish the fire}} Fibres recovered upon these items of clothing proved to be a precise match to samples retrieved from both Huntley's body, his clothing and from 5 College Close. Furthermore, his [[fingerprint]]s were recovered from the bin.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/>\n\nHuntley's car was also subjected to a detailed forensic examination on 16 August. The forensic examination of this vehicle revealed the car had also been recently, extensively cleaned, although traces of a distinctive mixture of brick dust, chalk and concrete of precisely the same type used to pave the road leading to where the girls' bodies would be discovered were found around the wheel arches and upon and around the [[Car controls|pedals]].<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> Furthermore, a cover from the rear seat was missing, and the lining of the boot had been recently removed and replaced with an ill-fitting section of household carpet.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators would later discover that one week before his arrest, Huntley had taken his car to an [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]] garage to have the vehicle's tyres changed. Using a false identity,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 148</ref> he had paid a mechanic \u00a310 to place a false number plate on the receipt for this purchase<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=How Huntley's Charade Crumbled |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257664.stm |newspaper=BBC News |date=17 December 2003}}</ref>}}\n\n==Arrest==\nHaving discovered the children's clothes at Soham Village College,<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3249887.stm | work=BBC News | title=Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths | date=7 November 2003}}</ref> police decided to arrest Huntley and Carr. Both were arrested on suspicion of abduction and murder at 4:30&nbsp;a.m. on 17 August.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2180946.stm | work=BBC News | title=Timeline of events | date=18 August 2002}}</ref> Although investigators had publicly stated they strongly believed the children had been abducted; on 7 August,<ref name=\"BBC News\"/> they publicly announced their strong suspicions both girls had been murdered.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two Held on Suspicion of Murdering Missing Girls |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/17/childprotection.children5 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=17 August 2002 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nDuring initial questioning, Huntley refused to answer questions and appeared evasive, confused, and [[Emotional detachment|emotionally detached]]; occasionally drooling throughout police attempts to question him in an effort to feign symptoms of [[Mental disorder|mental illness]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/17/newsid_3985000/3985667.stm|title=Ian Huntley Guilty of Soham Murders|website=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref> This tactic left police with no option but to initially refer Huntley to a mental hospital to undergo an extensive [[psychological evaluation]].<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Carr quickly confessed to detectives she had lied about her whereabouts and her partner's actions on 4 August as, shortly before she had returned to Soham from Grimsby three days later, Huntley had claimed to her in a phone call to have seen the two girls shortly before their disappearance, admitting: \"The thing is, Maxine, they came in our house!\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 157</ref> According to Carr, Huntley then informed her the children had entered their home in order that Wells could stanch her nosebleed. He then claimed to her Chapman had sat upon their bed as he had helped Wells control the bleeding from her nose before both girls had left their home. Referencing one of the 1998 rapes he had committed but had earlier claimed to her to have been falsely accused of in this phone call, Huntley then began voicing concerns as to again being falsely accused of involvement on this occasion, also claiming his previous arrest had caused him to suffer a [[nervous breakdown]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Said Fake Alibi was Her Idea|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3244798.stm|accessdate=23 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=27 November 2003}}</ref> She had therefore later agreed to concoct a false story with her partner to support his version of events.<ref name=\"O'Neill\"/>\n\nAfter being informed of the discovery of the children's bodies and the ample evidence attesting to Huntley's guilt, including his fingerprints being recovered from the bin in which the children's clothes had been found, Carr burst into tears, shouting: \"No! He can't have been! It can't have been! He hasn't done it!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/28/soham.ukcrime2|work=The Guardian|title=Tearful Carr Confronted with Evidence Against Lover, Court Hears |last=Branigan|first=Tania|date=28 November 2003|access-date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Despite these revelations, Carr initially remained emotionally attached to Huntley and professed her belief in his innocence to both the police and her family.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 258-259</ref>\n\n===Discoveries===\nAt approximately 12:30&nbsp;p.m. on 17 August,<ref>{{cite news|title=Police Reveal Horrors of Bodies in Ditch|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/police-reveal-horror-of-bodies-in-ditch-1-620448|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=24 August 2002}}</ref> a 48-year-old gamekeeper named Keith Pryer discovered the bodies of both girls lying side by side in a five feet deep irrigation ditch close to a pheasant pen near the perimeter fence of [[RAF Lakenheath]] in [[Suffolk]];<ref>''Crimes That Shocked The World'' {{ISBN|1-844-54974-7}} p. 65</ref> a location more than 10 miles east of Soham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2199785.stm|title=Bodies Found in Missing Girls Inquiry|date=18 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Pryer had noticed what he later described as an \"unusual and unpleasant smell\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/jury-hears-of-gamekeepers-discovery-6984709.html | work=Evening Standard | title=Jury Hears of Gamekeeper's Discovery | date=25 November 2003}}</ref> in the vicinity several days earlier; when returning to the area with two friends on 17 August, he had decided to investigate the cause of this odour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Uc4AAAAQBAJ|title=Beyond Evil - Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley|first=Nathan|last=Yates|date=18 October 2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> Walking through an overgrown [[Road verge|verge]] approximately 600 [[yard]]s from a partially tarmacked road, Pryer and one of his companions, Adrian Lawrence, discovered the children's bodies. Immediately upon viewing the corpses, Lawrence turned in the direction of his girlfriend, Helen Sawyer, and shouted: \"Don't come any closer, Helen! Get back in the van!\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 2</ref> Lawrence immediately reported the discoveries to police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Huntley: Girls Died in Freak Accidents |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/26/soham.ukcrime |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nBoth girls had been missing for thirteen days when their bodies were found, and both corpses were in an advanced state of [[human decomposition|decomposition]].<ref name=beyond/> In an apparent effort to destroy [[Forensic science|forensic evidence]], the murderer or murderers had attempted to burn both bodies.<ref name=\"Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3246118.stm |title=Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=28 November 2003 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> In addition, no clear footprints were discovered at the crime scene.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 137</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley would later inform investigators he had taped bin liners around his feet prior to carrying the children's bodies from his vehicle to the irrigation ditch}}\n\nDespite the perpetrator(s) efforts to destroy evidence and hinder identification, investigators rapidly deduced who the two victims most likely were, and that both had not died at the location of their discovery.<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2211087.stm|title=Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'|date=23 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> Numerous hairs later determined to belong to Chapman were also discovered on a tree branch close to the location of the girls' bodies.<ref>{{cite news|title='Smothered and Set Alight'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/smothered-and-set-alight-6976321.html|accessdate=18 December 2019|work=The Evening Standard|date=7 November 2003}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At his subsequent trial, Huntley admitted that, in an effort to destroy any [[Forensic science|forensic evidence]], he had returned to the body disposal site several days after the murders to set the bodies alight<ref name=\"Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3246118.stm |title=Huntley Set Fire to Girls' Bodies |work=[[BBC News]] |date=28 November 2003 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"The Crime of Her Life\">{{cite news|title=The Crime of Her Life|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/10/gender.uk|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2005}}</ref>}}\n\nThe following day, a Cambridgeshire Deputy Chief Constable named Keith Hodder released a [[Press release|press statement]] to the media confirming the discovery of the children's bodies, adding that both families had been informed of the developments and that although positive formal identification would take several days, investigators were as \"certain as [they] possibly could be\" the bodies were those of Wells and Chapman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Bodies are Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/two-bodies-are-holly-and-jessica-1-128657|accessdate=17 January 2020|work=Ipswich Star|date=19 August 2002}}</ref>\n[[File:Ely Cathedral (18).JPG|190px|right|thumb|[[Ely Cathedral]]. A service to remember and celebrate the lives of the children was held at this location on 30 August 2002<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\">{{cite web|title=Last Farewell: Holly Buried in Private Service with Flowers from The Beckhams; Jessica is Laid to Rest 24 Hours Earlier as The Two Families Grieve Alone|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/LAST+FAREWELL%3B+Holly+buried+in+private+service+with+flowers+from+the...-a091024546|accessdate=30 October 2019|date=4 September 2002}}</ref>]]\n\n==Identification==\nOn 21 August, the bodies of both girls were conclusively identified via [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]].<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Police Identify Holly and Jessica's Bodies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2002/aug/21/childprotection.uk?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 August 2002 |location=London}}</ref> Nine days later, a public memorial service was held at [[Ely Cathedral]] to remember and celebrate the lives of both girls.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/soham-murders-ian-huntley/ |title=Soham Murders: Why Did Ian Huntley Kill Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman? |work=The Telegraph |date=4 August 2017 |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> This service was attended by approximately 2,000 people, including the girls' classmates, teachers and the six [[family liaison officer]]s who had provided 24-hour service for both families.<ref name=\"thefreelibrary.com\"/> The Reverend Tim Alban Jones officiated at this service, informing all present: \"Would not the best and most lasting memorial to these two lovely young girls be a change for the better in how we behave towards each other? Today's service is a small milestone in our shared journey of grief and sorrow ... it is our hope that we may perhaps draw a line under one phase of our grieving and begin to look forward.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 237-238</ref>\n\nAn online [[Condolence book|book of condolence]] attracted more than 31,000 messages of grief and sympathy<ref name=\"Judd\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-640559.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Terri | last=Judd | title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Huntley is Charged on Two Counts of Murder | date=21 August 2002}}</ref> and on 24 August, football clubs across Britain held a [[Moment of silence|minute's silence]] prior to commencing scheduled football matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/inquest-into-deaths-of-murdered-cambridgeshire-girls-opens-today-1.1092894 |title=Inquest Into Deaths of Murdered Cambridgeshire Girls Opens Today |work=The Irish Times |date=23 August 2002 |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Inquest===\nThe formal [[Coroner#inquest|inquest]] into the children's deaths was held at [[Shire Hall, Cambridge|Shire Hall]], [[Cambridge]], on 23 August 2002.<ref name=\"Coroner: Girls' Bodies Were Moved t\"/> At this hearing, [[coroner]] David Morris testified the bodies of both girls were partially [[skeletonization|skeletonized]], and that no precise cause of death could be determined for either decedent, although Morris stated that the most likely cause of death of both girls had been asphyxiation.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|title=Soham Girls 'Likely to Have Been Asphyxiated'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/07/soham.ukcrime7|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=7 November 2003}}</ref> Furthermore, Morris stated the girls had almost certainly not died at the location where their bodies had been discovered,<ref name=\"Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2211087.stm|title=Girls' Bodies 'Dumped in Ditch'|date=23 August 2002|publisher=|work=BBC News}}</ref> and that both bodies had been placed at this location within 24 hours of their deaths.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>{{refn|group=n|Huntley would later inform investigators that he had waited for nightfall before opting to drive to RAF Lakenheath to dispose of the girls' bodies. He further elaborated that a deciding factor to dispose of the bodies in this particular location had been that RAF Lakenheath was just two miles from the home of his disabled grandmother, and that if eyewitnesses spotted his vehicle, he could falsely claim his purpose for being in this vicinity had been his decision to visit his grandmother<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 131</ref>}} These conclusions were physically supported by an analysis of the [[shoot]]s of [[Urticaceae|nettles]] located at the [[crime scene]] which enabled forensic [[Ecology|ecologist]] and [[Forensic palynology|palynologist]] [[Patricia Wiltshire]] to approximate that the actual time the bodies had been placed at this location had been almost two weeks prior.<ref name=\"The Crime of Her Life\">{{cite news|title=The Crime of Her Life|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/jan/10/gender.uk|accessdate=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 January 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Formal charges==\nBy 20 August, investigators had established sufficient [[Real evidence|physical evidence]] from Huntley's home, vehicle and Soham Village College to formally charge him with two counts of murder.<ref name=\"Judd\"/> He was formally charged with these offences while detained for observation at [[Rampton Secure Hospital]], and all [[preliminary hearing]]s against him were postponed until the conclusions of his [[mental health]] assessment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-174152.html|work=The Independent|title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Ian Huntley is Charged On Two Counts of Murder|last=Judd|first=Terri|date=21 August 2002|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> Carr was also charged with attempting to [[pervert the course of justice]] on this date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/in-a-secure-mental-unit-huntley-is-charged-on-two-counts-of-murder-174152.html|work=The Independent|title=In a Secure Mental Unit, Ian Huntley is Charged On Two Counts of Murder|last=Judd|first=Terri|date=21 August 2002|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At this hearing, Carr was informed by Principal Crown Prosecutor Marion Bastin this charge carried a maximum sentence of life imprisonment. Upon hearing this fact, Carr slumped forward.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/outrage-as-carr-appears-in-court-1-618413|work=The Scotsman|title=Outrage as Carr Appears In Court|date=22 August 2002|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>}} She was further charged with two counts of assisting an offender on 17 January 2003.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nWhile held on [[remand (detention)|remand]] at [[Holloway Prison]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/soham-accused-carr-to-testify-via-prison-video-link-1.1093546|work=The Irish Times|title=Soham Accused Carr to Testify Via Prison Video Link |date=29 August 2002|access-date=14 December 2019}}</ref> Carr regularly enquired as to Huntley's welfare,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 15</ref> and is known to have penned several letters in which she professed her continued love for him.<ref name=\"The Evening Standard\">{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr to Wed as She Finds Man Ready to Forget Her Past|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/maxine-carr-to-wed-as-she-finds-a-man-ready-to-forget-her-past-6630174.html|accessdate=5 December 2019|work=The Evening Standard|date=30 January 2008}}</ref> Carr would only sever all contact with Huntley in December 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Holly, Jessica and the Unravelling of a Dark and Terrible Mystery |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/07/ukcrime.soham |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 December 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Mental health assessment===\nTo determine Huntley's state of mental health, he was detained under Section 48 of the [[Mental Health Act 1983|Mental Health Act]] for almost two months at Rampton Secure Hospital. Here, his mental state was extensively assessed by Dr Christopher Clark, a consultant [[Forensic psychiatry|forensic psychiatrist]], to determine whether he suffered from any form of mental illness and whether he was [[Competence (law)|mentally competent]] to stand trial. Clark concluded in October that, although [[psychopathy|psychopathic]],<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 14</ref> Huntley did not suffer from any major mental or [[Psychosis|psychotic illness]].<ref name=\"Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html|title=Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill' |publisher=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003 |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/find_out/guides/uk/holly_and_jessica/newsid_3327000/3327903.stm |title=Holly and Jessica: Timeline of Events |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=19 December 2003 |accessdate=25 October 2019}}</ref> Resultingly, on 8 October, Huntley was deemed mentally competent to stand trial.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n{{quote box\n| quote = Although Mr Huntley made clear attempts to appear [[insane]], I have no doubt that the man currently, and at the time of the murders, was both physically and mentally sound and therefore, if he is found guilty, carried out the murders totally aware of his actions.\n| source = Dr. Christopher Clark. Consultant [[Forensic psychiatry|forensic psychiatrist]] reciting the conclusions of his assessment of Ian Huntley's mental state (2002)<ref name=\"Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html|title=Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill' |publisher=The Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003 |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\nHaving been declared mentally fit to stand trial, Huntley was faced with a sentence of [[Life imprisonment in England and Wales|life imprisonment]] if a jury could be convinced of his guilt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://89.207.56.140/news/2002/1008/soham.html |title=Huntley Declared Fit for Trial |publisher=RT\u00c9 News |date=8 October 2002 |accessdate=18 June 2011}}</ref> He was subsequently transferred to a [[Prison#Control_units|segregation unit]] at [[Woodhill (HM Prison)|Woodhill prison]] in [[Milton Keynes]], [[Buckinghamshire]]. On 9 June 2003, he attempted [[suicide]] by consuming 29 antidepressants which he had accumulated in his cell. Although staff initially feared Huntley might die as a result of this [[Drug overdose|overdose]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-184129/Soham-suspect-comfortable.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Soham Suspect 'Comfortable' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> he was returned to his prison cell within 48 hours. Huntley was later transferred to London's [[HM Prison Belmarsh|Belmarsh prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/ian-huntley-back-in-prison-after-taking-drug-overdose-1.116419 |title=Ian Huntley Back in Prison After Taking Drug Overdose |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date=11 June 2003 |accessdate=18 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Funerals==\nThe funeral services for Wells and Chapman were conducted on consecutive days in September 2002. Services for both children were held at St Andrew's parish church and both were officiated by the Reverend Tim Alban Jones. Both girls were laid to rest in private ceremonies attended by only family and close friends. At the request of both families that their privacy be respected, the media refrained from reporting upon either service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11952316.holly-and-jessica-laid-to-rest-in-private/|title=Holly and Jessica Laid to Rest in Private|access-date=October 23, 2019|newspaper=Herald Scotland|date=4 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1417463/MBE-for-vicar-who-united-Soham.html|title=MBE for Vicar Who United Soham|access-date=October 23, 2019|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 December 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Pretrial hearing==\nAt a preliminary hearing held at the [[Old Bailey]] on 16 June 2003, Huntley pleaded not guilty to the formal charges of murdering Wells and Chapman, although he chose to plead guilty to the charge both stood accused of: conspiracy to pervert the course of justice. Carr pleaded not guilty to the charges of attempting to pervert the course of justice and assisting an offender.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 264</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nThe trial of Huntley for the murders of Wells and Chapman opened at the Old Bailey on 5 November 2003 before Justice [[Alan Moses]]; Huntley was charged with two counts of murder, to which he entered a formal plea of not guilty. Carr was charged with two counts of assisting an offender and one count of perverting the course of justice.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nIn his [[opening statement]] on behalf of [[the Crown]], prosecutor Richard Latham [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] described the last day of the friends' lives and how, by \"pure chance\", they had happened to pass by Huntley's home at a time when Carr was not present. Latham contended Huntley had deliberately lured the girls into his home at approximately 6:37&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Jury Visits Huntley's House|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3257725.stm|accessdate=21 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=10 November 2003}}</ref> and that both girls had been murdered shortly thereafter, with cell site analysis proving Huntley had switched off Chapman's mobile phone either outside his home or within the grounds of Soham Village College after both girls had been murdered.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jessica's Mobile 'is Vital Clue to Murder'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446018/Jessicas-mobile-is-vital-clue-to-murder.html|accessdate=11 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> Latham further emphasised that mobile phone records and eyewitness accounts proved Carr had been in Grimsby on the evening in question,<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Trial: 'Crucial' Phone Evidence|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3246111.stm|accessdate=26 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=6 November 2003}}</ref> thus proving the statements she had given to police and press alike had been false. Latham then outlined the details of how Keith Pryer and his two friends had discovered the children's bodies on 17 August<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/a-clever-spot-to-hide-bodies-1-2532117 | work=The Yorkshire Post | title=A Clever Spot to Hide Bodies | date=7 November 2003}}</ref> at a location Huntley had known to be restricted via his plane spotting hobby and thus where they were unlikely to be discovered.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/soham-trial-hears-further-witness-evidence-1.510629 | work=The Irish Times | title=Soham Trial Hears Further Witness Evidence | date=13 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nReferencing the likely [[Motive (law)|motive]] for the girls' murder and the actual cause of death of each decedent, Latham stated that due to the extensive state of decomposition of the bodies, the coroner had been unable to determine the precise cause of death of either child, or whether the girls had been [[sexual assault|sexually assaulted]] before or after death. However, Latham stated neither body showed signs of compressive neck injuries, knife wounds, drugging or poisoning, and that both girls had most likely died of asphyxiation.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nIn a direct reference to Huntley's claims both girls' deaths had been [[Accidental death|accidental]], Latham stated that \"only one person knows what happened\" after the friends entered his home.<ref name=\"Last Hours of Holly and Jessica\"/> However, he further stressed the cause of death was undoubtedly murder, adding: \"Ten-year-old girls don't just drop dead.\"<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> In reference to Carr's attempts to pervert the course of justice, Latham stated that \"as surely as night follows day\" the two had conspired to concoct a false [[alibi]] to divert suspicion from Huntley,<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> although he warned the jury Carr could only be convicted of assisting an offender if they believed she had known Huntley had murdered the girls, adding her actual motive for providing lies to police with reference to the charge of perverting the course of justice was irrelevant.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/>\n\nOver the course of three days, Latham outlined the efforts of both defendants to divert suspicion away from Huntley, and Huntley's own efforts to destroy all physical and [[circumstantial evidence]] linking him to the crime,<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> although despite these efforts, investigators had retrieved enough evidence to prove the children had been murdered within his home and\u2014within approximately twelve hours of their deaths\u2014transported in his vehicle to the location where their bodies would be discovered on 17 August. This had included ample fibre evidence retrieved from Huntley's vehicle, clothes and carpets which had been a \"precise match\" to the Manchester United shirts the girls had been wearing at the time of their disappearance.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3251009.stm | work=BBC News | title=Soham Prosecution: The Forensic Case| date=7 November 2003}}</ref> Latham then closed his opening statement by again bringing the jury's attention to Huntley's claim both deaths had been accidental, remarking, \"We pose this question: Two of them?\" He then speculated Huntley's defence counsel may try and argue that he had been confused, commenting: \"In that case, they would have to consider [Huntley's] behaviour over the fortnight between the girls' disappearance and their bodies being found.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 268-269</ref>\n\nTestimony pertaining to the forensic evidence linking Huntley was heard on 24 November. On this date, a forensic scientist named Helen Davey testified as to the [[Real evidence|biological evidence]] recovered from the girls' clothing, footwear and a dishcloth discovered within the hangar at Soham Village College on 16 August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Trial Hears Forensic Evidence|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/24/soham.ukcrime|accessdate=20 December 2019|work=The Guardian|date=24 November 2003}}</ref> Davey testified she had found minute traces of blood and [[saliva]] upon these garments, although she had found no positive traces of [[semen]] upon the clothing. She further explained the reason for the lack of any definitive traces of semen being discovered could have been a result of the charred and melted condition of the articles she had inspected. A scenes of crime officer also testified on this date that, despite Huntley's exhaustive efforts to remove any physical evidence of his crime from his home, a forensic examination had revealed several traces of [[blood spatter]]ing about the hallway and main entrance to the master bedroom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley: 'I Hid Clothes'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-i-hid-clothes-7224896.html|accessdate=19 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=24 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Defendants' testimony===\nOn 1 December, Huntley testified before the court in his own [[defense (law)|defence]]. Responding to questioning by his own defence counsel, Stephen Coward QC,<ref>{{cite news|title=SPlease Don't Think I Could Kill, Said Huntley in Call to Mother|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448043/Please-dont-think-I-could-kill-said-Huntley-in-call-to-mother.html|accessdate=15 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=29 November 2003}}</ref> Huntley admitted both girls had died in his house but denied that either death had been intentional. According to Huntley, he, Wells and Chapman had entered his bathroom to stem a mild nosebleed Wells had been suffering when the girls had walked by his home. The bath was already filled with water as he had been cleaning his dog that afternoon. In the bathroom, he had slipped and accidentally knocked Wells into his bath while helping her [[wikt:stanch|stanch]] her nosebleed, and this unintentional act had caused her to drown as he himself had simply \"panicked and froze\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley 'Just Panicked and Froze'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3252382.stm|accessdate=28 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=1 December 2003}}</ref> He further claimed Chapman had witnessed this accident and began repeatedly screaming, \"You pushed her!\"<ref>{{cite news|title='You Pushed Her,' Jessica Screamed, then Huntley Moved to Silence Her|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447732/You-pushed-her-Jessica-screamed-then-Huntley-moved-to-silence-her.html|accessdate=26 January 2020|work=The Telegraph|date=26 November 2003}}</ref> and that he had then accidentally [[Asphyxia|suffocated]] her while attempting to stifle her screaming, which had preoccupied his attention as opposed to ensuring Wells did not drown. By the time his state of panic had waned, it had been too late to save the lives of either of the children<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\"/> and that his first coherent memory had been of himself sitting on his vomit-stained landing close to Chapman's body.<ref name=\"Evening Standard 17 December 2003\">{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->| title= Huntley 'Not Mentally Ill'|url= https://www.standard.co.uk/news/huntley-not-mentally-ill-6952555.html| date= 17 December 2003 |newspaper= [[London Evening Standard|Evening Standard]] |location=London| accessdate= 2 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nWhen questioned as to his failure to call emergency services and subsequent, extensive efforts to both destroy evidence and divert suspicion from himself, Huntley insisted he had first become preoccupied with whether the police and public alike would believe the girls' deaths had actually been accidental, and he had therefore decided to conceal all evidence of the deaths as opposed to either notifying police or paramedics.<ref name=\"How Huntley's Charade Crumbled\"/> Weeping, Huntley admitted responsibility for both deaths, but repeated his insistence both deaths had been accidental. He further tearfully claimed he had not attempted to feign insanity upon his arrest; insisting the trauma of the children's deaths had temporarily erased his memory and his being in the presence of police had caused his mind to temporarily seize.<ref name=\"ReferenceF\"/>\n\nOn 3 December, Carr took the stand to testify in her own defence. Responding to questioning from her own defence counsel, Michael Hubbard QC, Carr briefly discussed her initial acquaintance with Huntley, their subsequent relationship and plans to start a family once they both obtained financial stability before Hubbard directed his questioning toward her return to Soham on 6 August and her discovering Huntley had recently washed their bedding and had evidently cleaned sections of the house. To these questions, Carr explained that her first impression had been that Huntley had \"had a woman in the house\", adding their bedding had been washed shortly before 4 August. Carr further testified to having noted a crack in the [[enamel]] of the bathtub which had not been there when she had travelled to Grimsby four days previously.<ref>{{cite news|title='I Thought He'd Had a Woman in the House|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1448464/I-thought-hed-had-a-woman-in-the-house.html|accessdate=15 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=4 December 2003}}</ref> When questioned as to why she had then assisted Huntley in extensively cleaning their home in the days following the children's murder, Carr claimed she had done so as she had always been \"obsessive about tidiness.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceG\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 278</ref>\n\nQuestioned as to the efforts she had subsequently made to mislead both police and the media to divert suspicion from her partner, Carr emphasised she had only lied to police, the media and \"anyone who asks\" to protect Huntley, who had repeatedly assured her of his innocence of any wrongdoing and his fear or being \"fitted up\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A 'Charmer' Drawn to Schoolgirls|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3301527.stm|accessdate=22 December 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> by police for the girls' disappearance should they discover the 1998 rape allegation made against him.<ref>{{cite news|title='If, For a Minute, I Knew or Believed He Had Murdered Those Girls I Would be Horrified'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/if-for-a-minute-i-knew-or-believed-he-had-murdered-those-girls-i-would-be-horrified-81071.html|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=4 December 2003}}</ref> She further claimed to have referred to Wells and Chapman using past tense merely because had worked with the children in the past.<ref name=\"ReferenceG\"/>\n\nCarr further claimed she had initially attempted to persuade Huntley to contact police and \"be open\" as to his claims to have invited the children into his home in order that Wells could stanch her nosebleed, but that he had refused to do so, as inviting children into their home had been a violation of the rules imposed by St Andrew's Primary School. She further explained her focus had therefore been to protect Huntley's job and reputation, adding that had she known of Huntley's actual guilt, she would never have attempted to provide him with a false alibi, stating to her counsel: \"If, for a minute, I [had known] or believed he'd murdered either of those girls I would have been horrified.\"<ref name=\"biography.com\"/>\n\nConcluding his questioning, Hubbard cautioned the jury not to succumb to the temptation of judging Carr's [[morality]], but to consider her state of mind prior to her arrest when considering whether the lies she had told warranted any criminal liability, stating she had \"done no wrong\" on the date of the children's murder, and had not returned to Soham until 6 August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr Takes the Stand to Tell the Court Why She Stood by Huntley|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/maxine-carr-takes-the-stand-to-tell-the-court-why-she-stood-by-huntley-1.397193|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Irish Times|date=4 December 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Closing arguments==\nOn 10 December, counsels for both prosecution and defence delivered their [[closing argument]]s to the jury. Latham delivered his closing argument on behalf of the prosecution by describing both Huntley and Carr as \"accomplished liars\"<ref name=\"ReferenceG\"/> before outlining the prosecution's case both children had to die to satisfy Huntley's \"selfish self-interest\" before Huntley\u2014with Carr's support\u2014had embarked on twelve days of \"cynical deception\", with Carr only revealing the truth about her lies to police after being informed of the discovery of the children's bodies.<ref name=\"Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'\">{{cite news|title=Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3306221.stm|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=10 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nReferencing Huntley's likely motive for the murders and his claims at trial that both deaths had been accidental, Latham stated: \"We invite you to reject the accounts of both deaths [being accidental] as desperate lies; the only way out for him. We suggest that this whole business in the house was motivated by something sexual. But, whatever he initiated, plainly went wrong. Therefore, in this ruthless man's mind, both girls had to die in his own selfish self-interest.\" Referencing Carr's conscious efforts to deceive the police and media alike, Latham simply stated: \"She had the prospect of marriage, a baby, a nice home and a new start. She preferred to do what she could to make the best of the position she was in. That involved at all costs protecting Ian Huntley.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} pp. 277-279</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the prosecution's closing argument, Coward delivered his argument on behalf of the defence. He conceded his client was indeed guilty of physical responsibility for the girls' actual deaths\u2014as Huntley had admitted\u2014and therefore deserved punishment, although he argued the prosecution had failed to provide definitive [[Evidence (law)|proof]] Huntley had actually intended to actually murder the children or cause them actual [[bodily harm]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Him Guilty of Manslaughter, QC Tells Jury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/11/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=14 November 2019|work=The Guardian]|date=11 December 2003}}</ref> Furthermore, Coward contended the prosecution had failed to provide conclusive evidence to support their claim that Huntley's actual motive for the murders had been sexual. Coward concluded his closing argument by requesting the jury deliver a verdict of [[manslaughter]] in relation to both deaths.<ref>{{cite news|title=Find Him Guilty of Manslaughter, QC Tells Jury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/11/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=The Guardian]|date=11 December 2003}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote =  Your tears have never been for them; only for yourself. In your attempts to escape responsibility, in your lies and [[Psychological manipulation|manipulation]] ... you have increased the suffering of two families. There is no greater task for the criminal justice system than to protect the vulnerable. There are few worse crimes than your murder of these two young girls.\n| source = Section of Judge [[Alan Moses]]'s, formal [[Sentence (law)|sentencing]] of Ian Huntley. 17 December 2003<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 280</ref>\n| width = 25%}}\nFollowing the conclusion of both counsels' closing argument, Judge Moses announced the jury would begin their deliberations on 12 December.<ref name=\"Soham Pair 'Convincing Liars'\"/>\n\n===Convictions===\nThe jury deliberated for four days before reaching their verdicts against both defendants.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 279</ref> On 17 December 2003, they returned a majority verdict of guilty on two counts of murder against Huntley. He was subsequently [[Sentence (law)|sentenced]] to life imprisonment, with a minimum term of imprisonment to be imposed by the [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]] at a later date.<ref name=\"Huntley guilty of Soham Murders\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3312551.stm | work=BBC News | title=Huntley guilty of Soham Murders | date=17 December 2003|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> Huntley's face displayed no emotion as the verdict was announced, although the mothers of both Wells and Chapman burst into tears.<ref name=\"ReferenceH\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 280</ref><ref name=\"The Legacy of Holly and Jessica\">{{cite news|title=The Legacy of Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/the-legacy-of-holly-and-jessica-1.400875|accessdate=22 October 2019|work=The Irish Times|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Carr willingly pleaded guilty to the charge of perverting the course of justice, she pleaded not guilty to the charge of assisting an offender. The jury accepted Carr's insistence that she had only lied to the police and media in order to protect Huntley because, prior to their arrest, she had actually believed his claims of innocence.<ref name=\"Asphyxia 'Likely Cause' of Soham Deaths\"/> As such, she was found not guilty of assisting an offender. Carr was sentenced to serve three-and-a-half years in prison for perverting the course of justice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr: What Happened to Ian Huntley's Girlfriend After the Soham Murders?|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/uk/maxine-carr-ian-huntley-girlfriend-where-now-what-happened-soham-murders-holly-wells-jessica-chapman-501362|accessdate=29 October 2019|work=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|date=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMinutes after the convictions, the parents of both girls granted an interview to the media. Discussing Huntley's mindset, Leslie Chapman opined: \"I think he was a time bomb waiting to go off and both our girls were in the wrong place at the wrong time. I hope the next time I see him, it will be like we saw our daughters\u2014and it will be in a coffin.\"<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 281</ref>\n\n==Motive==\nHuntley's actual motive for killing the children is unknown, although minutes prior to encountering Wells and Chapman, he is known to have engaged in a heated argument with Carr, culminating in his slamming the telephone down.<ref name=beyond>{{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nathan|title=Beyond Evil|date=2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|location=London|isbn=1844541428}}</ref> Huntley had allegedly suspected Carr of conducting affairs throughout their relationship, leading both his mother and some police officers to suspect Huntley had killed the two girls in a fit of [[jealousy|jealous]] [[Rage (emotion)|rage]].<ref name=beyond/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-204291/Huntley-flipped-killed.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Huntley 'Flipped and Killed' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> However, prior to his trial, a [[Offender profiling|criminal profile]] had resulted in his being ruled by an eminent [[Criminal psychology|criminal psychologist]] as a \"latent, predatory paedophile\"<ref name=\"He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Wa\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/17/soham.ukcrime4 | work=The Guardian | title=He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Way Through Life | date=17 December 2003}}</ref> who had chosen to lure Wells and Chapman into his home upon a moment of [[opportunism]].<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news|title=His Lies and Shallow Charm Fooled Dozens of People but They Hid a Violent, Bitter Man |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime2|accessdate=2 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe prosecution had contended at Huntley's trial a likely [[sexual desire|sexual motive]] existed for the murders. Testimony from Carr had indicated her suspicions sexual activity had occurred in their home in her absence as, although Huntley had insisted throughout the entirety of their relationship that Carr perform all domestic chores, she had observed that he had washed the quilts, pillow cases and sheets of their bed in her absence.<ref name=\"https\"/> However, [[Forensic pathology|pathological evidence]] retrieved from the bodies indicating at least one of the girls had been subjected to a sexual assault either before or after her murder was not disclosed to the jury at Huntley's trial. The reason for this decision had been that both bodies were too extensively decomposed and damaged by fire to enable a conclusive determination of either the actual cause of death or if either girl had been subjected to a sexual assault.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAlthough prosecutors at Huntley's trial contended he had intentionally lured the children into his house with a likely sexual motivation, investigators found no evidence of [[Malice aforethought|premeditation]] in relation to the murders.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-203297/Huntley-asked-sexual-motive.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | first=Paul | last=Harris | title=Huntley Asked About 'Sexual Motive' | date=19 April 2014}}</ref> However, at the September 2005 hearing in which the minimum term Huntley should serve before any form of parole eligibility was decided, Justice Alan Moses stated: \"There is a likelihood of [a] sexual motivation, but there was no evidence of sexual activity, and it remains no more than a likelihood.\"<ref name=\"The Daily Telegraph\"/>\n\n===Psychology===\nPrior to murdering Wells and Chapman, Huntley had established an extensive record of consensual and unconsensual sexual activity with females\u2014many of whom had been beneath the legal [[age of consent]]. He would typically use guile and/or force to achieve his desires. Between 1992 and 2002, he had committed numerous acts of [[physical violence#Types|physical]] and [[sexual violence]] against women and children for which he had been legally unpunished.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley: A History of Violence|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huntley-a-history-of-violence-8967h3q6f6j|accessdate=27 November 2019|work=The Times|date=27 November 2006}}</ref> The youngest girl Huntley is known to have raped had been 12 years old, with another girl he had attempted to rape being 11 years old.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p.34</ref>{{refn|group=n|Investigators believe that prior to his 2002 arrest, Huntley had engaged in illegal sexual activity with up to 60 underage girls<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 35</ref>}}\n\nFollowing his arrest, several former girlfriends and sexual partners stated that, although Huntley presented himself as a charming and considerate individual in the early stages of a relationship, he would become domineering and [[domestic violence|violent]] upon having established a sense of control.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 37</ref> Having established control over his partner, Huntley severely restricted and supervised any contact she held with her family or social acquaintances. He would also [[Emotional blackmail|emotionally blackmail]] his partner if he detected any signs of her developing resistance to his control or indicating a desire to leave him.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 45</ref>\n\nAccording to one columnist, the fact that Huntley had remained unpunished for these often blatant and continuous acts had embellished Huntley's confidence and reinforced his domineering, [[misogynist]]ic mindset in addition to fuelling his [[recidivism]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/maxine-carr-is-one-more-huntley-victim-why-do-we-demonise-her-rn2jjbqk6fd | work=The Times | first=Joan | last=Smith | title=Maxine Carr is One More Huntley Victim: Why Do We Demonise Her? | date=11 May 2004}}</ref> Psychologists have also determined Huntley has [[Mental block|mentally blocked]] any attempts to accept either the reality or enormity of his actions pertaining to his repeated violence against females in order that he may cope with the consequences of his actions.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\"/>\n\n==Sentencing==\nThe minimum term of imprisonment Huntley should serve before being considered eligible for [[parole]] was decided on 29 September 2005. On this date, High Court judge Mr Justice Moses announced that Huntley must remain in prison until he had served a minimum of 40 years' imprisonment; a term which would not allow parole eligibility until 2042, by which time Huntley would be 68 years old.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham Murders: Why Did Ian Huntley Kill Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/0/soham-murders-ian-huntley/|accessdate=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=4 August 2017}}</ref> In setting this minimum term of imprisonment, Mr Justice Moses stated: \"The order I make offers little or no hope of the defendant's eventual release.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= [2005] EWHC 2083 (QB) Paragraph 16|url=http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/144_7208.htm|publisher= Her Majesty's Courts Service|date=29 September 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226093346/http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/cms/144_7208.htm|archivedate=26 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nHuntley avoided eligibility for a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment, as the passing of the [[Criminal Justice Act 2003]] had been just one day after his conviction; thus taking effect on 18 December 2003 and applying solely to murders committed on or after this date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Ian Huntley\n| image_name     = Ian Kevin Huntley portrait.jpg\n| image_size     = 100px\n| image_caption  = Ian Huntley\n| birth_name = Ian Kevin Huntley\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|1|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]\n| alias          = Ian Nixon\n| conviction     = [[Murder]] (x2)\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] (40-year minimum term)\n| conviction_status = Convicted\n| occupation  = School [[Janitor|caretaker]]\n| education = [[Healing Comprehensive School]]\n| spouse =\n}}\n\n==Ian Huntley==\nIan Kevin Huntley was born in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, on 31 January 1974, the first of two sons born to Kevin Huntley and his wife, Lynda ([[n\u00e9e]] Nixon).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1449738/Trail-of-underage-sex-and-violence-that-led-to-murders.html|title=Trail of Underage Sex and Violence that Led to Murders|date=18 December 2003|work=Telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The Huntley family were working class and at the time of the birth of their first child, lodged with Lynda's parents in Grimsby. Following the birth of their second child, Wayne, in August 1975, the family moved into a rented property in [[Immingham]], where Huntley attended school.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 19</ref>\n\nHuntley was a timid child, and something of a [[mother's boy]]. In his early years, he frequently threw tantrums in order to obtain his mother's attention, although childhood friends would later remark how markedly afraid he was of his stern father.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 22</ref>\n\nAt both primary and secondary school, Huntley was an average scholar. He was regarded as a loner, an oddball and an attention seeker by his peers, and became a frequent target for bullies.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 20</ref> The bullying Huntley endured escalated when he entered [[Healing School|Healing Comprehensive School]] at age 11, resulting in his academic performance waning. As a result, Huntley's parents enroled their son in Immingham Comprehensive at age 13. He was again the target of physical and verbal bullying at this school, although he did form a few friendships via a shared interest in computer games.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley also enjoyed football, and was an avid supporter of Manchester United.<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\nAt the urging of his father, Huntley joined the [[Air Training Corps]] at age 13. His activities with this youth organisation fuelled an interest Huntley had held since childhood for aeroplanes, and he seriously considered a future career with the [[Royal Air Force]]. Huntley also developed a hobby of [[Aircraft spotting|plane spotting]]. Via this hobby, he became familiar with the environs of RAF Lakenheath.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 24</ref>\n\nDespite having few friends, Huntley did form several relationships with girls while attending Immingham Comprehensive. Each of these girls was at least one year younger than himself, although none of these relationships lasted longer than a few weeks.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 25</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Huntley finished his schooling, obtaining five [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] passes. He chose not to enrol in college or university and instead committed himself to finding employment. Between 1990 and 1996, Huntley worked in a succession of menial jobs, although he seldom held any job for an extensive period of time.<ref name=\"Ian Huntley Biography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> He also viewed himself as something of a [[ladies' man]], and was scrupulous with regards to his personal appearance and personal hygiene.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 10</ref>\n\n===Marriage===\nIn June 1994, Huntley began dating 18-year-old Claire Evans, with whom he first became acquainted through his employment at a local [[Heinz]] factory. After approximately two months of courtship,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley proposed to Evans. The couple married at Grimsby Registry Office on 28 January 1995,<ref>{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=28 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> although the marriage lasted scarcely one week due to Huntley's volatile temper. On one occasion, he is known to have beaten his wife so extensively she suffered a [[miscarriage]].<ref name=\"The Scotsman\"/> Shortly after their separation, Huntley's wife formed a relationship with and later married Huntley's younger brother, Wayne.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=27 October 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref>\n\n===Previous criminal offences===\nIn March 1996, Huntley was charged with [[burglary]]. In this offence, he and an accomplice [[Allegation|allegedly]] broke into the house of a neighbour in Grimsby and stole numerous electrical goods, jewellery and cash. Although this case reached court, the prosecution offered no evidence, resulting in a judge ordering the offence to [[lie on file]].<ref name=\"Previous Allegations Against Huntley\">{{cite news|title=Previous Allegations Against Huntley|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3313501.stm|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nBetween August 1995 and May 1996, Huntley established numerous sexual relationships with teenage girls, all of whom were under the legal age of consent. Three of these girls were aged 15, and one 13. One of these girls would become pregnant,<ref name=\"Ian Huntley Biography\"/> and gave birth to a baby girl in 1998.<ref name=\"https\"/> Although reported to police on three occasions, Huntley was not charged for any of these offences as each of the girls denied having engaged in sex with Huntley. Each refused to file criminal complaints and/or rebuffed offers of help from social services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-detective Says 'Unspectacular' Huntley Did Not Stand Out|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/mar/02/childrensservices.soham|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=2 March 2004}}</ref> Despite not being charged with any of these offences, rumours of Huntley's sexual interest in underage girls soon became community gossip, and he was regularly insulted by neighbours and work colleagues. As a result, Huntley began rebuffing any offers to socialise with work colleagues for fear of being attacked while alone in their company.<ref name=\"Former Neighbour Describes Huntley\">{{cite news|title=Former Neighbour Describes Huntley Paedophile Slurs and Former Girlfriend Reveals His Violent Behaviour|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/12_december/17/realstory_soham.shtml|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1998, Huntley was arrested on suspicion of raping an 18-year-old woman. He admitted engaging in sex with the claimant, but claimed the act had been [[consensual sex|consensual]]. He was not formally charged with this offence. Just one month later, Huntley was charged and remanded in custody at [[HM Prison Wolds]] for one week after another 18-year-old Grimsby woman claimed to have also been beaten and raped by Huntley while walking home from a local nightclub.<ref name=\"Previous Allegations Against Huntley\"/> This complainant further stated Huntley had threatened to kill her before assaulting her. Huntley admitted engaging in sex with this woman, although he insisted the act had been consensual.<ref name=\"He Charmed, Bullied and Lied His Wa\"/> The criminal charge was dropped a week later after the [[Crown Prosecution Service]], having examined CCTV footage from the nightclub and environs and finding evidence of the two socialising within the nightclub, determined [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]] existed to secure a conviction for this offence.<ref name=\"https\"/> As a result of this criminal complaint, further rumours regarding Huntley's [[sexual violence]] also became community gossip,<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 49</ref> resulting in Huntley being fired from his job and forcing him to move into his mother's home. Furthermore, he was forbidden from initiating contact with his baby daughter or her mother.<ref name=\"Huntley Cries in Dock\"/>\n\nIn July 1998, police were notified Huntley had also sexually assaulted an 11-year-old girl in September 1997; having also threatened to kill the child if she informed her mother. He was never charged with this offence, although he subsequently confessed to this attack in April 2007.<ref name=\"The Scotsman\"/>\n\nThe final criminal allegation against Huntley prior to his committing the Soham murders dates from July 1999. In this instance, a woman was raped and Huntley\u2013by this stage suspected by police as being a serial sex offender\u2013was interviewed. Huntley supplied a DNA sample to assist in their enquiries, with Carr also providing an alibi to support his claims of innocence. The victim of this assault subsequently stated her belief that Huntley had not been the perpetrator of her assault. (This would prove to be the sole instance in which a suspected or proven victim of Huntley had not identified or named him as being her assailant.)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3313501.stm | work=BBC News | title=Previous Allegations Against Huntley | date=17 December 2003|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley had never been convicted of any of these criminal allegations, although his burglary charge had remained on file. Howard Gilbert, then-headteacher of Soham Village College\u2014having admitted the college's failure to check Huntley's references prior to offering him employment\u2014later said that he would not have employed Huntley if he had been aware of the burglary charge, as one of Huntley's key responsibilities was to ensure security in the school grounds\u2014a role unfit for a suspected burglar.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/mar/13/childrensservices.soham | work=The Guardian | title=School Admits Huntley References Not Checked | date=13 March 2004|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n\nBy 2001, Huntley's proven and alleged criminal activities had been reported to [[Humberside Police]] on ten separate occasions and to the social services on five occasions.<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\n===Acquaintance with Maxine Carr===\nIn February 1999, Huntley became acquainted with 22-year-old Maxine Carr, whom he first encountered in a Grimsby nightclub. On this occasion, Carr had been drinking with a former boyfriend named Paul Selby when Huntley\u2014a casual acquaintance of Selby\u2014approached the two and immediately initiated a conversation.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 70</ref> According to Carr, she was \"instantly attracted\" to Huntley's self-certain and pleasant persona, and agreed to begin dating him that same evening.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Within four weeks of their acquaintance,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/like-the-gullible-young-girls-before-her-carr-fell-for-huntley-s-evil-spell-1-498396 | work=The Scotsman | title=Like the Gullible Young Girls Before Her, Carr Fell for Huntley's Evil Spell | date=18 December 2003 | accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> she had moved into Huntley's [[Barton-upon-Humber]] flat, and the couple informed relatives of their eagerness to start a family.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/maxine-carr-the-teenage-anorexic-who-loved-working-with-children-and-nights-on-the-town-577012.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Maxine Carr: The Teenage Anorexic Who Loved Working With Children and Nights on the Town | first=Terri | last=Judd | date=18 December 2003 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, the couple moved to a ground-floor flat in [[Scunthorpe]], where Huntley formally proposed to Carr in June 1999.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 78</ref>\n\nAlthough publicly a besotted couple, Huntley was notably possessive of Carr, and is known to have both [[emotional abuse|emotionally abused]] and/or [[Assault|physically assaulted]] her on numerous occasions, often culminating in Carr returning to live with her mother before Huntley persuaded her to return to live with him.<ref name=\"Former Neighbour Describes Huntley\"/> Furthermore, both Huntley and Carr are known to have conducted affairs throughout the course of their relationship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carr Cheated on Fiancee with Teenager|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/carr-cheated-on-fiance-with-teenager-7237002.html|accessdate=10 December 2019|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> Noting how Carr often became [[Flirting|flirtatious]] whenever she had consumed alcohol, Huntley actively sought to minimise any opportunity for her to drink or otherwise socialise outside his presence for fear of her cheating on him with other males.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nAt the time of their acquaintance, Huntley temporarily worked for an insurance company in [[Market Rasen]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.marketrasenmail.co.uk/news/rasen-area-link-to-soham-murders-1-1178676 | work=Market Rasen Mail | title=Rasen Area Link to Soham Murders | date=21 August 2002 | accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> He soon found alternate employment at a finance company in [[Binbrook, Lincolnshire|Binbrook]] while Carr maintained her employment packing fish at a local fish processing factory. The couple would relocate to [[East Anglia]] in early 2001. Shortly thereafter, Huntley secured employment as a bartender.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=13 March 2017|location=London}}</ref>\n\nBy 2001, Huntley had re-established contact with his father,{{refn|group=n|Huntley's parents had separated in 1993. Following their separation, Huntley had distanced himself from his father for several years}} who worked as a school caretaker in the village of [[Littleport, Cambridgeshire|Littleport]], near [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]]. He would regularly travel to Cambridgeshire from East Anglia on his days free from work to help his father, and soon developed aspirations to become a school caretaker himself. Via his father, Huntley learned of a school caretaker vacancy in nearby Soham Village College in the summer of 2001. He applied for and secured employment as a senior caretaker at this secondary school in September 2001, supervising the work of four other employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/crime-figure/ian-huntley |title=Ian Huntley Biography |publisher=biography.com |date=2 April 2004 |accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref>\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = Maxine Carr\n| birth_name   = Maxine Ann Capp<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1977|2|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Grimsby]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]]<ref name=\"ReferenceI\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 53</ref>\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| conviction     = [[Perverting the course of justice]]\n| conviction_penalty        = 42 months' imprisonment\n| conviction_status         = Released\n| occupation     = [[Teaching assistant (United Kingdom)|Teaching assistant]]\n}}\n\n==Maxine Carr==\nMaxine Carr was born Maxine Ann Capp. She was was born in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, on 16 February 1977, the second of two daughters born to Alfred Capp and his wife, Shirley (n\u00e9e Suddaby).<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 52</ref>\n\nThe marriage between Capp's parents was marred by frequent arguments. Following a heated argument in the summer of 1979, Shirley ordered her husband to leave the household. Shortly thereafter, she and her daughters relocated to the village of [[Keelby]]. Alfred seldom maintained contact with his wife and children, and refused to provide any financial support for his daughters. Capp and her older sister, Hayley (born 1967), were largely raised by their mother and grandparents. The family regularly experienced severe financial difficulties, although Shirley would later state she \"spoiled\" her daughters to the best of her financial ability.<ref name=\"ReferenceI\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 53</ref>\n\nAs a child and adolescent, Capp was viewed by her peers as something of a timid outcast, with few friends.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maxine is Another of His Victims|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/maxine-is-another-one-of-his-victims-7224619.html|accessdate=3 December 2019|work=Evening Standard|date=17 December 2003}}</ref> She performed poorly academically, although she always held aspirations to become a teacher.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 83</ref>\n\nBy the time Capp entered adolescence, she was slightly overweight, leading her to become insecure about her physical appearance. Although she had shunned the company of boys as a child, as a teenager, she craved\u2014but seldom received\u2014the attention of boys her age, occasionally leading to bouts of [[binge eating]]<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 56</ref> in addition to her developing the habit of [[self-harm]]ing.<ref name=\"The Maxine Question\">{{cite news|title=The Maxine Question|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime3|accessdate=21 November 2019|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> By age 15, Capp weighed more than 10 [[Stone (unit)|stones]], resulting in her becoming the recipient of bullying by her classmates. In an effort to lose weight, she developed a habit of forcing herself to [[purging disorder|vomit after eating]].<ref name=\"The Evening Standard\"/> This habit led to Capp developing [[anorexia]] by the age of 16, with her weight at one stage plummeting to just six stones, and her mother forcing her to eat in order for her to regain weight.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>\n\nIn 1993, Capp finished her schooling, having obtained no qualifications. She briefly worked alongside her mother in a fish processing plant as she considered which career path she should choose before enrolling at the [[Grimsby Institute of Further & Higher Education]], having chosen to study general care. Capp obtained her diploma in 1996. The same year, she and her mother moved from Keelby back to Grimsby. Shortly thereafter, she briefly obtained employment as a junior care assistant at a care home for the elderly in Grimsby before opting to return to work alongside her mother as a labourer at Bluecrest fish processing plant.<ref name=\"ReferenceJ\">''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 61</ref>\n\nSeveral of Capp's colleagues would later remark how they found her to be a distant and immature figure with few friends and few hobbies. To one colleague, Capp would talk incessantly about her dreams of leaving this employment and embarking on a teaching career.<ref name=\"ReferenceJ\"/>\n\nBy the time Capp had obtained employment at Bluecrest, she had garnered sufficient courage to begin dating men, although none of these relationships lasted more than a few months.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrested Couple Publicly Declared Their Affection for Girls|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404703/Arrested-couple-publicly-declared-their-affection-for-girls.html|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=18 August 2002}}</ref> Notably shy and reserved and prone to wear clothing which concealed her figure when sober, Capp became markedly flirtatious when having consumed alcohol, and is known to have occasionally engaged in [[exhibitionism]] in addition to frequently engaging in [[one-night stands]] with individuals she encountered in pubs and clubs.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>{{refn|group=n|Several of Carr's former partners would later inform reporters they found her to be an [[Emotional detachment|emotionally detached]] and sexually promiscuous individual who had also been markedly jealous by nature. These had been the reasons several of her early relationships had ended<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 65</ref>}}\n\nWhile Capp resided with her mother in Grimsby, she unofficially adopted the surname Benson.<ref>{{cite news|title=Soham's 'Couple from Hell'|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/soham-s-couple-from-hell-1-1378495|accessdate=13 December 2019|work=The Scotsman|date=18 August 2002}}</ref> She later legally changed her surname to Carr in an apparent effort to distance herself from her father.<ref name=\"The Independent\"/>\n\n==Soham employment==\nIn September 2001, Huntley responded to a job advertisement relating to a vacant position of senior caretaker at Soham Village College. He applied for this position using the alias Ian Nixon.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 81</ref>{{refn|group=n|Huntley's mother's maiden name had been Nixon. Following the separation of his parents in 1993, Huntley chose to use his mother's surname. He would only resume using his father's surname following the 2002 reconciliation of his parents.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Steven|title=Ownership of Red Fiesta is Key Issue in Soham Trial|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/nov/06/soham.ukcrime2|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=13 March 2017|location=London}}</ref>}} No form of [[background check]] was conducted before or after this job interview,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and although Huntley lacked extensive experience in this form of employment, his application for this position was successful.<ref name=\"https\"/> His employers assisted in his securing the tenancy of 5 College Close,<ref name=\"housegone\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3595801.stm|title=Soham Murder House is Demolished|accessdate=28 April 2017|agency=BBC News}}</ref> and he and Carr relocated to Soham in late September.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=1 November 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> Huntley began his employment at Soham Village College on 26 November. He worked as a senior caretaker at these premises until the date of his arrest.<ref name=\"Morris\"/>\n\nIn February 2002, Huntley secured part-time employment for Carr at St Andrew's Primary School, although Carr did lie as to her academic qualifications when applying for this position.<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite news|title=Maxine Carr: The Teenage Anorexic Who Loved Working with Children and Nights on the Town|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/maxine-carr-the-teenage-anorexic-who-loved-working-with-children-and-nights-on-the-town-83059.html|accessdate=2 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=18 December 2003}}</ref> Although this employment was initially voluntary work, Carr later became a teaching assistant in the school's Year 5 class. Wells and Chapman became two of the pupils she taught,<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> and both girls were notably fond of her.<ref name=\"Jessica and Holly Doted on Maxine C\"/>\n\nIn July 2002, Carr applied for a vacant full-time teaching assistant position at St Andrew's Primary School. She received notification on 23 July that her application was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murder Trial Hears of Soham Final Walk|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/murder-trial-hears-of-soham-friends-final-walk-76858.html|accessdate=18 November 2019|work=The Independent|date=5 November 2003}}</ref> One of the children to express dismay at this decision was Wells who, having broken down in tears upon learning Carr's application for the teaching position had been unsuccessful, had presented her with a hand-drawn card,<ref>{{cite news|title=Rootless and Troubled Lives of Couple Suspected of Killing Holly and Jessica|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1404854/Rootless-and-troubled-lives-of-couple-suspected-of-killing-Holly-and-Jessica.html|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Telegraph|date=20 August 2002}}</ref> depicting a smiling face, in which she stated: \"I'll miss you a lot. Thank you! C ya! Miss ya! Luv Holly.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Class Helper Failed to Win Full-time Post|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/aug/19/childprotection.children3|accessdate=5 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=19 August 2002}}</ref>\n[[File:MaxineCappHollyWellsCardSoham2002a.jpg|184px|right|thumb|Maxine Carr, seen here on 8 August 2002 displaying the hand-drawn card given to her by Holly Wells. This card was made approximately two weeks before the child's murder.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 190</ref>]]\n\n===Summer 2002===\nBy the summer of 2002, the physical relationship between Huntley and Carr had begun to deteriorate. By Huntley's own later admission, he had become sexually frustrated, and he had unsuccessfully attempted to persuade a married colleague to date him on the weekend Carr visited her mother in Grimsby.<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 107</ref>\n\nAt 9:53&nbsp;a.m. on 4 August, Huntley attempted to phone Carr, although she did not answer her mobile phone. Carr only replied to his missed call at 6:23&nbsp;p.m. This four-minute phone call escalated into a heated argument, culminating in Huntley angrily terminating the phone call after she informed him of her intentions to again socialise in Grimsby that evening. Four minutes later, Carr sent Huntley a text message which read: \"Don't make me feel bad because I'm with my family.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> Huntley did not reply to this message.<ref name=\"The Maxine Question\"/>\n\n==Bichard enquiry==\nImmediately following Huntley's conviction, his previous criminal history was disclosed to the public. These disclosures revealed that, despite his extensive record of sexual offences against underage girls and young women and evident criminal recidivism, not only had police failed to pursue these previous criminal complaints and allegations, but Huntley had secured a position of employment facilitating his access to children.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huntley Investigated Eight Times|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/17/soham.ukcrime6|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=17 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nUpon learning of these public disclosures, [[Home Secretary]] [[David Blunkett]] announced a [[public inquiry|public enquiry]] into the [[Criminal Records Bureau|intelligence-based record keeping]] and [[Vetting|vetting system]] which had allowed Huntley to obtain employment as a school caretaker despite these previous criminal complaints, which had been reported to both police and social services. Chaired by [[Michael Bichard, Baron Bichard|Sir Michael Bichard]], the [[Bichard report|Bichard enquiry]] opened on 13 January 2004.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Holly and Jessica\"/> The results of this enquiry were published in June that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://police.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/operational-policing/bichard-inquiry-report|title=The Bichard Report|date=17 June 2009|publisher=|work=homeoffice.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe stated purpose of the Bichard enquiry was:\n{{cquote|Urgently to enquire into child protection procedures in [[Humberside Police]] and [[Cambridgeshire Constabulary]] in the light of the recent trial and conviction of Ian Huntley for the murder of Jessica Chapman and Holly Wells.\n\nIn particular to assess the effectiveness of the relevant intelligence-based record keeping, the vetting practices in those forces since 1995 and information sharing with other agencies, and to report to the Home Secretary on matters of local and national relevance and make recommendations as appropriate.}}\n\nOne of the pertinent issues of concern to be scrutinised by the Bichard report surfaced almost immediately when Humberside Police stated their belief in it being unlawful under the [[Data Protection Act 1984|Data Protection Act]] to hold data regarding criminal allegations which had not lead to a conviction; this claim was criticised by other police forces who thought this too strict an interpretation of the Act. The enquiry severely scrutinised the actual investigation by Cambridgeshire Police into the children's disappearance and murder, as almost two weeks had elapsed following the disappearance of Wells and Chapman before Cambridgeshire Police became aware of Huntley's previous criminal background, despite his claims to be the last individual to see the children alive.<ref name=\"Blunder After Blunder\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/children.soham | title=Blunder After Blunder| work=The Guardian |date=18 December 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Further criticism was directed at the force for their initial failure to scrutinise Carr's claims to have been in Soham on the date of the children's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poor Intelligence, Poor Data System and Poor Media Strategy: Police Own Up to Failures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/dec/18/soham.ukcrime6|accessdate=9 January 2020|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe enquiry also severely criticised Humberside Police for deleting information relating to the previous criminal allegations against Huntley and also criticised Cambridgeshire Police for not following standard vetting guidelines. Both the Humberside and Cambridgeshire Police were heavily criticised for their failings in maintaining criminal intelligence records on Huntley.<ref name=\"Blunder After Blunder\"/>\n\nBichard later ordered the suspension of the Chief of Humberside Police, [[David Westwood]], for ordering the destruction of criminal records pertaining to alleged child molesters which had not resulted in a conviction. (This suspension was later overturned.) Westwood retired from the position of Chief of Humberside Police in March 2005. The Chief Constable of Cambridgeshire Constabulary, Tom Lloyd, was also subjected to severe criticism as his force had failed to contact Humberside Police during the investigation into Huntley's criminal background prior to his securing employment at Soham Village College.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Cambridge Chief Tom Lloyd|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3827459.stm|date=22 June 2004|accessdate=11 March 2014|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nAn added complication in these criminal vetting procedures was the fact that Huntley had applied for the caretaker's job under the name of Ian Nixon, although he did divulge upon the application form for this position that he was previously known as Ian Huntley. It is believed that Cambridgeshire Police failed to perform a background check under the name Huntley. Had they actually done so, they would have discovered an outstanding burglary charge on file relating to his November 1995 arrest for this crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Blunkett Orders Police Chief's Suspension |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/jun/22/childrensservices.schools|accessdate=21 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=22 June 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Recommendations===\nThe Bichard enquiry recommended the implementation of a mandatory registration scheme for people working with children and vulnerable adults such as the elderly and mentally handicapped.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2003/dec/17/childrensservices.soham | work=[[The Guardian]] | title=The CRB Explained: How the Criminal Records Bureau Operates| date=17 December 2003|accessdate=16 April 2011| location=London| first=Polly| last=Curtis}}</ref> This recommendation later led to the foundation of the [[Independent Safeguarding Authority]]. The findings also suggested a national system should be implemented for police forces to share intelligence information, and that all police forces should follow a clear code of practice on record-keeping. These findings ultimately led to the tightening of various procedures within the Criminal Records Bureau system, including compulsory checks into potential criminal backgrounds of people who apply to work with children.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4612038.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Concerns About Teachers' List 99| date=14 January 2006|accessdate=16 April 2011| first=Gary| last=Eason}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAn orange-petalled rose, dedicated to the memory of Wells and Chapman, was unveiled by representatives of Soham Town Council at the 2003 [[Chelsea Flower Show]]. The inspiration for dedicating a flower to the children's memory sourced from a poem read aloud at the memorial service at Ely Cathedral on 30 August 2002 by the father of Wells, titled ''Soham's Rose''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Royals Flock to Flower Show|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3038061.stm|accessdate=18 January 2020|work=BBC News|date=19 May 2003}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2004, the three-bedroomed house in College Close in which the murders occurred was demolished and the site levelled, with all rubble from the property being destroyed and later discarded in various, undisclosed locations.<ref name=\"housegone\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/3595801.stm|title=Soham Murder House is Demolished|accessdate=28 April 2017|agency=BBC News}}</ref> The site where 5 College Close once stood is now a vacant patch of grass.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>\n\nWithin days of Huntley's formal sentencing, he reflected to the media on the prospect of his spending the remainder of his life behind bars and of his fears for his security, exclaiming: \"I'm going to rot inside this place. I'll rot in here, I know it. I'll spend the rest of my life in here ... I'm going to be inside forever, and it'll be torture.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/did-she-watch-jessica-die-1-1297313|title=Did She Watch Jessica Die?|accessdate=19 December 2019|agency=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\nIn the years since his incarceration, Huntley has been repeatedly attacked by other inmates. On 14 September 2005, he was [[Scalding|scalded]] with boiling water while incarcerated at [[HM Prison Wakefield]] by a fellow inmate. The injuries Huntley received in this attack resulted in his being unable to attend the hearing at which his minimum term of imprisonment was decided.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/west_yorkshire/4248052.stm|title=Huntley Scalded in Prison Attack|work=BBC News|date=15 September 2005|accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Following this attack, Huntley alleged that prison authorities had failed in their [[Duty of care in English law|duty of care]] towards him, and launched a claim for \u00a315,000 in compensation. He was reportedly awarded \u00a32,500 in [[legal aid]] to pursue this claim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.gov.agency.csa.narkive.com/fDMVabgO/anyone-facing-jail-by-the-csa-compare-it-with-this|title=Anyone Facing Jail by the Child Support Agency Compare it With This|date=6 August 2005|publisher=|work=uk.gov}}</ref>\n\nHuntley was transferred from Wakefield prison to [[HM Prison Frankland|Frankland prison]] on 23 January 2008. Three years later, on 21 March 2010, he received non life-threatening injuries to his neck after his throat was [[Slashing (crime)|slashed]] by a convicted [[armed robbery|armed robber]] named Damien Fowkes. The injuries Huntley received in this attack required hospital treatment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/8579226.stm |title=Soham Murderer Ian Huntley Attacked by Jail Inmate |work=[[BBC News]] |date=21 March 2010 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> Huntley again applied for compensation for the injuries he received in this attack, seeking \u00a320,000 in [[damages]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ian Huntley Could Get \u00a320,000 Compensation After Prison Attack|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7502752/Ian-Huntley-could-get-20000-compensation-after-prison-attack.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15163465 |title=Ian Huntley: Prisoner Admits Attacking Soham Killer |work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-15181854 |title=Ian Huntley Attacker Damien Fowkes Gets Life Term |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 October 2011 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2006, Huntley attempted to commit suicide by taking an overdose of antidepressants he had accumulated in his prison cell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/5314944.stm |title=Soham Killer Treated for Overdose |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 September 2006 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> This suicide attempt resulted in his hospitalisation and a thorough search of his cell, in which a cassette tape was recovered. This cassette tape contains a markedly different account of the murders of Wells and Chapman than that Huntley had testified to at his trial. In what Huntley had believed would be his posthumous confession, he claims to have confessed to having murdered both girls to Carr prior to their arrest and his plans to confess to authorities, to which, Huntley alleged, Carr had slapped his face and informed him to \"pull [himself] together\" as she did not wish to lose the teaching position she had yearned for all her life. Huntley further alleges Carr had encouraged him to burn both bodies in an attempt to destroy all forensic evidence linking him to the crime.<ref name=\"Steele\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1546975/Huntley-revealed-all-in-taped-confession.html |title=Huntley Revealed All in Taped Confession |work=The Telegraph |date=29 March 2007 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |first=John |last=Steele}}</ref> It is believed Huntley had agreed to make this recording for a fellow prisoner (who had hoped to later sell the confession to the media after his release), in return for his being provided with the antidepressants he had used to attempt suicide.<ref name=\"Steele\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1546975/Huntley-revealed-all-in-taped-confession.html |title=Huntley Fooled Prison's Suicide Watch by Hiding 29 Anti-depressant Pills in Teabags |work=The Telegraph |date=10 June 2003 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |first=Sean |last=O'Neill}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, Huntley confessed to having sexually assaulted an 11-year-old girl whom he had dragged into an orchard in 1997. This admission\u2014in which Huntley also confessed to having a sexual interest in children while insisting the murders of Wells and Chapman had not been sexually motivated\u2014was welcomed by the victim of this sexual assault.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1499498/Judge-outlines-reasons-for-sentence.html |title=Judge Outlines Reasons for Sentence |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=29 September 2005 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Following Huntley's admission of guilt, this victim issued a press statement in which she confessed to feeling \"a massive sense of relief\", although she concluded this statement with the sentence: \"Yet, I still feel upset that Huntley was left at large, resulting in the deaths of two innocent children.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1549612/Huntley-admits-sex-attack-on-girl-in-1997.html |title=Huntley Admits Sex Attack on Girl in 1997 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 April 2007 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London |first=John |last=Steele}}</ref>\n\nCarr was released on [[probation]] from [[HM Prison Foston Hall]] on 14 May 2004 after serving a total of 21 months' imprisonment (including the 16 months she had been detained while on remand).<ref>''Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley'' {{ISBN|978-1-844-54142-3}} p. 285</ref> She was given a secret identity to protect her from threats of attack from vengeful members of the public<ref>{{cite news|title=How Maxine Carr Might Start a New Life |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/3700583.stm|accessdate=16 November 2019|work=BBC News|date=11 May 2004}}</ref> in addition to being provided with a new home in an undisclosed location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1446601/Jessica-and-Holly-doted-on-Maxine-Carr-says-teacher.html|work=The Telegraph|title=Maxine Carr to Get Police Guard on Release|last1=O'Neill|first1=Sean|date=7 February 2004|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Carr is one of four former prisoners in the United Kingdom to be given an entirely new identity upon release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3713243.stm |title=Carr Released from Prison |work = BBC News |date= 14 May 2004 |accessdate = }}</ref> Carr won an [[injunction]] on 24 February 2005, granting her lifelong anonymity on the grounds that her life would otherwise be in danger. The costs of imposing this order have been reported by differing tabloid newspapers as being between \u00a31&nbsp;million and \u00a350&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/feb/28/pressandpublishing.mondaymediasection2 |title=Selling Lies is Not Press Freedom |work= The Guardian |first=Roy |last=Greenslade |authorlink=Roy Greenslade |date=28 February 2005|accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nAt least a dozen women have been falsely identified as being Carr and either persecuted or physically attacked due to false stories speculating as to her whereabouts and new identity which have been printed in tabloid publications.<ref name=\"Guardian 16 May 2005\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/may/16/mondaymediasection11|title=PCC Must Act Over Hounding of Maxine Carr |work=The Guardian |first=Roy |last=Greenslade |authorlink=Roy Greenslade |date=16 May 2005 |accessdate=5 October 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/5282960.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Look-alike Claim 'Nightmare' | date=24 August 2006 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article473996.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Mob Torments Scots Woman Mistaken for Maxine Carr | first=Gillian | last=Harris | date=25 August 2004 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/4403113.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carr Look-alike Goes into Hiding | date=2 April 2005 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nShortly after her release from prison, Carr and her family contacted a [[Tyneside]]-based publishing company with view to publishing her [[autobiography]]. Although [[Mirage Publishing]] initially agreed to publish Carr's autobiography, the company soon withdrew their offer after a feature on [[BBC Radio Newcastle]] prompted scores of complaints from the public.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Publisher Scraps Carr Book Deal |date=5 March 2005|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/4310763.stm}}</ref>\n\nIn the years since her release, Carr has married. She reportedly gave birth to her first child in 2011. The imposed lifetime anonymity order extends to include the birth date and gender of her child, in order that he or she should never know their mother's previous identity.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2055570/Soham-liar-Maxine-Carr-gives-birth--baby-know-mother-really-is.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Maxine Carr Gives Birth to Her First Child: Baby Will Never Know True Identity of its Mother | date=31 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n===Literature===\n* {{cite book|last=Gerrard|first=Nicci |title=Soham: A Story of Our Times|year=2004|publisher=Short Books|isbn=978-1-904-09592-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Yates|first=Nathan |title=Beyond Evil: Inside the Twisted Mind of Ian Huntley|year=2005|publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=1844541428}}\n\n===Television===\n* The [[Channel 4]] documentary ''Being Maxine Carr'' focuses on the lasting public outrage at Carr's efforts to pervert the course of justice following the Soham murders, and how numerous women across the UK have been falsely accused of being Carr.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/mum-mistaken-maxine-carr-hopes-3737370 | work=Teesside Live | title=Mum Mistaken as Maxine Carr Hopes TV Show Will End Ordeal | date=12 December 2007 | accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref> This documentary was first broadcast on 14 December 2007.<ref name=\"Being Maxine Carr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/being-maxine-carr/episode-guide/series-1/episode-1 |title=Being Maxine Carr |publisher=[[Channel 4]] |date=14 December 2007 |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n* The 90-minute documentary ''Soham Revisited: 15 Years On'' was first broadcast on 25 April 2017. Narrated by [[Alison Steadman]], this documentary features interviews with previous lovers of Huntley.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.itnproductions.co.uk/latest-news/soham-revisited-15-years-on-documentary-1 | work=ITN Productions | title=Soham Murders: 15 Years On | date=27 April 2017 | accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Investigation Discovery]] channel has broadcast a 60-minute documentary focusing upon the Soham murders as part of their ''Faking It: Tears of a Crime'' true crime documentary series. This documentary primarily focuses upon the efforts made by Huntley and Carr to deceive police and public alike, and was first broadcast on 18 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tv24.co.uk/p/faking-it-tears-of-a-crime-season-2-episode-1-d7tl77 |title=Faking It: Tears of a Crime |publisher=TV24 |date=18 August 2007 |accessdate=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] have also commissioned a documentary focusing upon the Soham murders. This documentary, titled ''5 Mistakes That Caught a Killer'', was first broadcast on 23 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/ian-huntley-5-mistakes-killer-facing-justice-revealed-in-tonight-channel-5-documentary-501484 | work=[[i (newspaper)|i]] | title=Ian Huntley: The 5 Mistakes That Led to The Soham Killer's Downfall Explored in Tonight's Channel 5 Documentary | date=23 May 2019 | accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin