{"title_page": "Southeast Asian long-fingered bat", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| status = EN \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn|last1=Fukui|first1=D.|last2=Sano|first2=A.|year=2019|title=Miniopterus fuscus|volume=2019|page=e.T13564A22104728}}</ref>\n| genus = Miniopterus\n| species = fuscus\n| authority = [[J. Lewis Bonhote|Bonhote]], 1902\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''Southeast Asian long-fingered bat''' (''Miniopterus fuscus'') is a species of [[vesper bat]] in the family [[Vespertilionidae]].\n\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Japan]].\n\nIt has been assessed as [[Endangered species|endangered]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Southeast Asian Long-fingered Bat|last=Museum)|first=Akira Sano (Mie Prefectural|last2=Tokyo )|first2=Dai Fukui (University of|date=2018-07-25|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe bat has an average body mass of 10.8 grams and a forearm length of 41.5 mm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eol.org/pages/289554/data|title=Miniopterus fuscus Bonhote 1902 data - Encyclopedia of Life|website=eol.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Biology ==\n\n=== Reproduction ===\nFemales give birth to a single young in early June.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Diet ===\nThe species forages over forests and mainly feeds on [[Butterfly|butterflies]], [[Moth|moths]], [[Hymenoptera]], and [[flies]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Habitat and distribution ==\nThe species is found in [[Amami \u014cshima|Amami-Oshima]], [[Tokunoshima|Tokuno-shima]], [[Okinoerabujima|Okinoerabu Island]], [[Okinawa Island]], [[Kume Island]], [[Ishigaki Island|Ishigaki]], and [[Iriomote Island]] in Japan. It was collected from the [[Kii Peninsula|Kii peninsula]] in [[Honshu]] in 1933, but is now considered [[Extinction|extinct]] there.\n\nIt inhabits [[Forest|forest habitats]].\n\nThe species roosts in mines and caves, in colonies of several hundred individuals. There were large maternity colonies in the past, but these have become rare. There is a colony of 10,000 females on Okinawa Island.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Conservation ==\nThe species has been assessed as endangered by the [[IUCN Red List]] due to its small area of inhabitance, degradation of its habitat, and disturbance of caves where it roosts.\n\nThe species faces threats from the continuing degradation of its habitat. It is also threatened by the disturbance of its roosts. Some caves roosted by this species are lined with electricity for tourism and also face development near the caves.  new airport has been constructed near on Ishigaki Island above several caves frequented by these bats.\n\nIt does not occur in any protected areas.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Miniopterus nav}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2051769}}\n\n[[Category:Miniopteridae]]\n[[Category:Bats of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1902]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by J. Lewis Bonhote]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| status = EN \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn|last1=Fukui|first1=D.|last2=Sano|first2=A.|year=2019|title=Miniopterus fuscus|volume=2019|page=e.T13564A22104728}}</ref>\n| genus = Miniopterus\n| species = fuscus\n| authority = [[J. Lewis Bonhote|Bonhote]], 1902\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''Southeast Asian long-fingered bat''' (''Miniopterus fuscus'') is a species of [[vesper bat]] in the family [[Vespertilionidae]].\n\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Japan]].\n\nIt has been assessed as [[Endangered species|endangered]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Southeast Asian Long-fingered Bat|last=Museum)|first=Akira Sano (Mie Prefectural|last2=Tokyo )|first2=Dai Fukui (University of|date=2018-07-25|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe bat has an average body mass of 10.8 grams and a forearm length of 41.5 mm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eol.org/pages/289554/data|title=Miniopterus fuscus Bonhote 1902 data - Encyclopedia of Life|website=eol.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Biology ==\n\n=== Reproduction ===\nFemales give birth to a single young in early June.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Diet ===\nThe species forages over forests and mainly feeds on [[Butterfly|butterflies]], [[Moth|moths]], [[Hymenoptera]], and [[flies]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Habitat and distribution ==\nThe species is found in [[Amami \u014cshima|Amami-Oshima]], [[Tokunoshima|Tokuno-shima]], [[Okinoerabujima|Okinoerabu Island]], [[Okinawa Island]], [[Kume Island]], [[Ishigaki Island|Ishigaki]], and [[Iriomote Island]] in Japan. It was collected from the [[Kii Peninsula|Kii peninsula]] in [[Honshu]] in 1933, but is now considered [[Extinction|extinct]] there.\n\nIt inhabits [[Forest|forest habitats]].\n\nThe species roosts in mines and caves, in colonies of several hundred individuals. There were large maternity colonies in the past, but these have become rare. There is a colony of 10,000 females on Okinawa Island.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Conservation ==\nThe species has been assessed as endangered by the [[IUCN Red List]] due to its small area of inhabitance, degradation of its habitat, and disturbance of caves where it roosts.\n\nThe species faces threats from the continuing degradation of its habitat. It is also threatened by the disturbance of its roosts. Some caves roosted by this species are lined with electricity for tourism and also face development near the caves.  new airport has been constructed near on Ishigaki Island above several caves frequented by these bats.\n\nIt does not occur in any protected areas.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n